sequence: Year 1176 ( MCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday. This year was the first to have two years of leap years (calendar years) occurring within a single year.In the Roman Calendar, this year began at midnight on August 28, 1261, when the Emperor Justinian II decreed that one year of the Gregorian calendar be added in order to avoid a possible discrepancy between the calendars. The day after this decree, King Edward I of England officially adopted the Julian calendar, which had been set out by John Wycliffe.

Year 1490 (MCDXC) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – Anne of Brittany announces that all those who ally themselves with the king of France will be considered guilty of the crime of Lèse-majesté. March 13 – Charles II becomes Duke of Savoy at age 1; his mother Blanche of Montferrato is regent. March or April – 1490 Ch'ing-yang event, a presumed meteor shower or air burst over Qingyang in Ming dynasty China, said to have caused casualties.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack , such as on a fishing line, etc. Shark fins are elongated parts of the snout along the upper jaws of the shark. Shark fins also vary in length from about 0.5 cm (∼3/4 inch) for the smallest shark species, and some species can be over 30 cm (12 inches). Sharks have been found with different types of shark fins; for example, manta rays and hammerhead sharks possess very short fin tails, while baleen fishes such as mackerels and catfish have keeled ones.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendars and two days behind the Islamic calendar. It is also known as the Day of Jubilee, due to its status as a day off for celebrating the Christian holiday of  or the Day of Mourning, which in Sweden marks the death of a family member in childbirth. The German word "Königskörle" (or könnigskorn) is a derogatory term used to refer to all persons who have not been baptized into the Church.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as the earliest history of their city in terms of legend and myth. The most familiar of these myths, and perhaps the most famous of all Roman myths, is the story of Romulus and Remus, twins who were suckled by a she-wolf as infants. Another account, set earlier in time, claims that the Roman people are descended from Trojan War hero Aeneas, who escaped to Italy after the war, and whose son, Iulus, was the ancestor of the family of Julius Caesar.

Year 1377 (MCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Battle of Đồ Bàn: Trần Duệ Tông, Trần dynasty Emperor of Đại Việt (Vietnam), is killed. January 17 – Pope Gregory XI moves the Papacy back from Avignon to Rome. January 27 – The Bad Parliament begins sitting in England. Influenced by John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster, it undoes the work done by the Good Parliament, the previous year, to reduce corruption in the Royal Council.

In cosmology, the cosmological constant (usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda: Λ), alternatively called Einstein's cosmological constant, is the constant coefficient of a term Albert Einstein temporarily added to his field equations of general relativity. He later removed it. Much later it was revived and reinterpreted as the energy density of space, or vacuum energy, that arises in quantum mechanics. It is closely associated with the concept of dark energy.Einstein originally introduced the constant in 1917 to counterbalance the effect of gravity and achieve a static universe, a notion which was the accepted view at the time.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (often referred to as the Four Horsemen) are figures in Christian religion, first appearing in the Old Testament's prophetic Book of Zechariah and in the Book of Ezekiel, where they are named as punishments from God, and later in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, an apocalypse written by John of Patmos.Revelation 6 tells of a book or scroll in God's right hand that is sealed with seven seals. The Lamb of God/Lion of Judah opens the first four of the seven seals, which summons four beings that ride out on white, red, black, and pale horses.

Proline (symbol Pro or P) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid (used in the biosynthesis of proteins), although it does not contain the amino group  but is rather a secondary amine. The secondary amine nitrogen is in the protonated NH2+ form under biological conditions, while the carboxyl group is in the deprotonated −COO− form. The "side chain" from the α carbon connects to the nitrogen forming a pyrrolidine loop, classifying it as a aliphatic amino acid. It is non-essential in humans, meaning the body can synthesize it from the non-essential amino acid L-glutamate.

Year 1319 (MCCCXIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 8 – Upon the death of his maternal grandfather, King Haakon V, three-year-old Magnus Eriksson becomes King of Norway. July 8 – Three-year-old Magnus Eriksson is elected king of Sweden, thus establishing a union with Norway. His mother Ingeborg of Norway is given a place in the regency, in both Sweden and Norway. July 23 – A Knights Hospitaller fleet scores a crushing victory over an Aydinid fleet, off Chios.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting , gluing , rearranging and overlapping elements that were not previously in the same image.The term may be used to describe an image taken using digital photo processing, such as photomultiplier tubes (or "pixillator" or "digital camera"), digital cameras, digital scanners, software programs and other applications. It may also refer to a computer application for creating or manipulating photographs. The term has often been shortened to simply "photomontage." Gödel wrote the book Foundations of mathematics (1962) and later expanded it in his incompleteness theorems .

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces. He presides over the militia and is subject to the federal control of the state's armed forces. A macroeconomist, a macroeconomist looks at how the economy operates and what drives its economic activity. In particular, they consider the relationship between aggregate supply and demand in the economy (the market) and how these are influenced by individual choices, financial decisions, and policies such as monetary policy.In general, macroeconomists focus on the effects of changes in aggregate supply and demand with regard to output and employment.

Year 997 (CMXCVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  1 February: Empress Teishi give birth to Princess Shushi - she is the first child of the emperor, but because of the power struggle between Michinaga and Korechika, the empress is not allowed to go to the palace 18 May: The imperial court decides to pardon Korechika and Takaie under the illness of Teishi Byzantine Empire  July 16 – Battle of Spercheios: Byzantine forces, under General Nikephoros Ouranos, defeat the Bulgarians at the Spercheios River in Greece.

Year 1230 ( MCCXXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday in England. The year 1230 was one of the few years without a leap year. The year starts with January 1 as the first Monday of the previous year followed by February 1 which is the first Thursday of the next. The Chinese character 縛 is an archaic form of the English letter D  , used in writing to represent certain syllables or sounds, for example 性 (zě), dōu (dǔ) and 金 (léng).

Year 1552 (MDLII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 15 – Henry II of France and Maurice, Elector of Saxony, sign the Treaty of Chambord. February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds the Chilean city of Valdivia, as Santa María la Blanca de Valdivia. February 24 – The privileges of the Hanseatic League are abolished in England. March – The Act of Uniformity imposes the Protestant Book of Common Prayer on England. March 26 – Guru Amar Das becomes the Third Sikh Guru.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

Stigmata (, plural of  , 'mark, spot, brand'), in Christianity, are the appearance of bodily wounds, scars and pain in locations corresponding to the crucifixion wounds of Jesus Christ, such as the hands, wrists, and feet. Stigmata are primarily associated with Roman Catholicism. Many reported stigmatics are members of Catholic religious orders. St. Francis of Assisi was the first recorded stigmatic. For over fifty years, St. Padre Pio of Pietrelcina of the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin reported stigmata which were studied by several 20th-century physicians.

Year 1230 (MCCXXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 9 – Battle of Klokotnitsa: Byzantine forces under Theodore Komnenos (Doukas) invade Bulgaria, breaking the peace treaty with Tsar Ivan Asen II. Theodore gathers a large army, including western mercenaries. The two armies meet near the village of Klokotnitsa. Ivan applies clever tactics and manages to surround the Byzantines. They are completely defeated, only a small force under Theodore's brother Manuel Doukas manages to escape the battlefield.

Events January–June January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the `` Cavalier Parliament '' , after nearly 18 days of debate.January 30 – Queen Elizabeth II abdicates and abdicates Prince Albert, her only child, as heir. February 4 – Pope Pius VI declares Martin Luther's papal supremacy invalid.March 3 – The House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha formally elects a new king: Henry IV of England. The Great British Bicentennial is an international celebration of British national identity and its role in global politics. The celebration was inaugurated on April 25, 2016 by the Queen at Buckingham Palace.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller; May 24, 1878 – January 2, 1972) was an American psychologist, industrial engineer, consultant, and educator who was an early pioneer in applying psychology to time-and-motion studies. She was described in the 1940s as "a genius in the art of living." Gilbreth, one of the first female engineers to earn a Ph.D., is considered to be the first industrial/organizational psychologist. She and her husband, Frank Bunker Gilbreth, were efficiency experts who contributed to the study of industrial engineering, especially in the areas of motion study and human factors.

Year 993 (CMXCIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The 12-year-old King Otto III gives the Sword of Saints Cosmas and Damian (also known as the Sword of Essen) as a gift to the convent in Essen. It symbolises the martyrdom of Cosmas and Damian, the patron saints of the city. Charles, duke of Lower Lorraine, dies in prison in Orléans (see 991). He is succeeded by his son Otto II, who inherits the full dukedom and pledges his allegiance to Otto III.

Symbiosis ( from Greek , , `` living together '' , from , , `` together '' , and , "living on the same page") is the social interaction between organisms that can occur by means of exchange or mutualism, as well as natural processes involving mutual interactions. There are many types of symbiosis, all of which have similar mechanisms of mutualism.Natural symbiosis may be caused by genetic recombination (such as in plant and animal hybrids) or by endosymbiosis. In both cases, the organism in question becomes part of another organism's ecology.In nature, the two organisms often compete each other to take advantage of different resources.

Year 1494 (MCDXCIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – The Cetinje Octoechos (Цетињски октоих, an Eastern Orthodox octoechos (liturgy), first tone), the first incunabulum written in the Serbian recension of Church Slavonic, and the first book printed in Cyrillic in Southeast Europe, is completed in Cetinje. January 25 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples. May – Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognises Perkin Warbeck as rightful King of England. May 5 – Christopher Columbus first sights Jamaica.

Events January–June January 20 – Russo-Polish War ( 1654–1667 ) : Poland cedes Kiev , Smolensk , and eastern Ukraine to Grand Duke Konstantin IV of Russia. The Russian Army advances northward into the Volga Delta, but is unable to defeat the Polish armies. Francisco d'Alva  (; 17 June 172217 October 1779) was Spanish admiral who commanded the squadron that defeated the French naval fleet at Jutland, on 1 December 1775, during the American Revolutionary War. He is commonly referred to as the "Siege of Yorktown", after its capture by General George Washington's navy on 19 September 1776.

Year 1184 ( MCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday 31 March 1295.The year begins on the first Monday after the  day of the Hebrew week Yom Kippur. The new Gregorian Julian calendar introduced for Europe in the years 1602, 1604 and 1606 does not follow the normal Gregorian pattern of leap years; instead, it introduces a period of one-month intervals followed by a leap second every four years. Dartmouth College is a private, liberal arts university in New Hampshire located in Northampton, MA.

The Asian Games, also known as Asiad, is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia. The Games were regulated by the Asian Games Federation (AGF) from the first Games in New Delhi, India, until the 1978 Games. Since the 1982 Games, they have been organized by the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA), after the breakup of the Asian Games Federation. The Games are recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and are described as the second largest multi-sport event after the Olympic Games.There have been nine nations that have hosted the Asian Games.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the UK's air forces. It also acted in the role of coordinating the development and use of military technologies, as well as developing strategic relationships with other countries. British Airways is the world's largest airline by passenger traffic, with a fleet of approximately 3,000 operated by more than 4,500 airlines worldwide. Founded in 1869, British Airways has grown to be one of the largest airlines in the world and the third-largest privately-owned airline.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty , ending hostilities between the tribes. February 15 – George Washington begins construction of Fort Independence, the first permanent structure in the United States to bear the name "George Washington" on its base. Grammar is the art of forming sentence structure, including syntax, grammar, and usage. Grammar involves understanding the relationships that exist in language, and how words refer to each other and can be combined to form more than one meaning or concept.

The African clawed frog (Xenopus laevis, also known as the xenopus, African clawed toad, African claw-toed frog or the platanna) is a species of African aquatic frog of the family Pipidae. Its name is derived from the three short claws on each hind foot, which it uses to tear apart its food. The word Xenopus means 'strange foot' and laevis means 'smooth'.The species is found throughout much of Sub-Saharan Africa (Nigeria and Sudan to South Africa), and in isolated, introduced populations in North America, South America, Europe, and Asia.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov ( ; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974 ) was a Soviet general and Marshal of Russia from 1956 to his death, and leader of the Communist Party of Russia from 1924 to 1927.Early lifeIn 1901, Zhukov was an army officer at the age of 19. In 1909 he joined the Tcheka, the secret police. In 1912, he was assigned to the Cheka's General Staff.At the height of the Civil War of 1905–1913, he was in command of the Cossack Guard. He was then given command of the Russian Army and commanded troops during the Russo-German War.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two Olympic silver medals in 1994 and 2000. He was selected as one of the best players in the world at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, becoming the youngest to medal in the event.Uytdehaage has competed since he was a teenager, winning several national championships, but never breaking into the top ten in the World Championships. John James Audubon (1908 – 8 December 1910) was an American ornithologist, zoologist, and conservationist.

Year 1372 ( MCCCLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the first month of the Gregorian calendar and ending on Monday ( link will display the standard Julian calendar ). This year is known in many Western countries as December 15, 1681. The Church of England (also called the Episcopal Church or simply the Anglican Communion) is the largest religious group in the United Kingdom by population. Formed in the early 16th century, it was established by King Charles II of Great Britain as a confessional church following the Anglican Reform Bill of 1660.

Year 1250 (MCCL) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeWorld  The world population is estimated at between 400 and 416 million individuals. World climate transitions from the Medieval Warm Period to the Little Ice Age. Medieval music: The Notre Dame school of polyphony ends.Europe  February 2 – King Eric XI (Eriksson) dies and is succeeded by the 10-year-old Valdemar I, who is the eldest son of Birger jarl. He is elected as ruler of Sweden, and becomes the first Swedish king of the House of Folkung.

Year 1137 ( MCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a leap day at the beginning of August. It is the seventh year in the Julian Calendar.The name comes from the Latin word "Juliana", which means "Jupiter's birthday". In mathematics, a binomial coefficient is a function or series of functions given by the coefficients of some set of polynomials. Binomials are defined as any function whose coefficients have a monotone ratio. Binomial coefficients are useful for solving linear and quadratic equations.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking. They may be eaten ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. Many cooking bananas are referred to as plantains (/ˈplæntɪn/ US: /plænˈteɪn/,UK: /ˈplɑːntɪn/) or green bananas. In botanical usage, the term "plantain" is used only for true plantains, while other starchy cultivars used for cooking are called "cooking bananas". True plantains are cultivars belonging to the AAB Group, while cooking bananas are any cultivars belonging to AAB, AAA, ABB, or BBB groups.

Year 1362 (MCCCLXII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Grand Duchy of Lithuania switches New Year to January 1, before any other country does. January 16 – The "Grote Mandrenke" storm tide strikes the Netherlands, England, Germany and Denmark, destroying the Danish settlement of Rungholt in the Duchy of Schleswig, and the Humber estuary port of Ravenser Odd in England. The East Frisian island of Buise is broken into two by North Sea floods.

Year 993 ( CMXCIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday (link will display the partial calendar ). It was also used for New Year's Day. The Christian Church is a worldwide Christian church that is recognized as the official church of more than 300 million people, with approximately one in four persons in the world who identify themselves as Christian. A number of major Christian denominations have existed throughout the history of humanity, though there is a distinct lack of organized Christianity in the Americas today.

Year 1422 (MCDXXII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 10 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Deutschbrod: The Hussites defeat 2,000 Royalist Crusaders. March 21–May 2 – Hundred Years' War – Siege of Meaux: Meaux surrenders to the English. June 10–September – The Ottoman sultan Murad II besieges Constantinople; the siege is broken off as a result of the rebellion of Küçük Mustafa. August 22 – Use of the Spanish era dating system in the Kingdom of Portugal ceases.

Year 1298 ( MCCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar . The date corresponds to the Julian day count of 29 February in the Julian calendar. It marks the beginning of the three year cycle from January 1 through March 31 and the beginning of what is known as the reign of the Roman Emperors. (also known by other names, often abbreviated with a capital 'E') is an important historical period in European history which lasted from about 500 to 1200 AD.

Year 1470 ( MCDLXX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) . This year began when the Gregorian Calendar came into effect , but it is not an exact year because the years were not always evenly divisible by 365. As with the Gregorian calendar, the dates in this year follow the Julian Calendar. There are some variations, such as leap years, which are used to compute the date of every day in the year. The number of days in this year follows the periodicity of the Earth's orbit around the sun.

Frederick ( Middle High German : Friderich , Standard German : Friedrich ; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440), also known as Frederick the Great, was a German prince and archduke of Austria from 1410 until his death in 1460. Francisco Javier López de Ramírez (; 23 June 1821 – 9 January 1877) was a Spanish-born English philosopher, poet, novelist, and essayist who is considered one of the most influential writers of the nineteenth century. His books were among those that formed the basis of a new philosophical outlook on Western philosophy during the Enlightenment period.

Year 1171 (MCLXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 12 – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) orders the arrest of all Venetians in his empire, and seizes their ships and goods. In September, Doge Vitale II Michiel leads a Venetian fleet (120 ships) against the Byzantines, conquering the cities of Trogir and Dubrovnik. But the plague takes a heavy toll among the fleet's crewmen; half the ships have to be burned to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech , 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol ( ; ; ; 11 May 1887 – 28 June 1910), was an Argentine painter known for his surrealist-influenced paintings, drawings, prints and sculptures. His work has been shown internationally throughout the 20th and 21st century. The Eagle  is one of the most iconic symbols of the Roman empire, as it was often seen perched on a statue of the god Jupiter . It is also a popular motif in several European and American Celtic religions, including the Etruscans, Scots, Picts, and Irish Celts.

Freestyle skiing is a  skiing discipline comprising aerials, moguls, cross, half-pipe, slopestyle and big air as part of the Winter Olympics. It can consist of a skier performing aerial flips and spins and can include skiers sliding rails and boxes on their skis. Known as "hot-dogging" in the early 1970s, it is also commonly referred to as freeskiing, jibbing, as well as many other names, around the world.History Ski acrobatics have been practiced since the 1930s/1940s. Aerial skiing was popularized in the 1950s by Olympic gold medalist Stein Eriksen. Early US competitions were held in the mid-1960s.

Year 1513 ( MDXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar and ending on Wednesday ( MDXV ) of the Gregorian calendar. It is the fifth year of the reign of Charles VIII of France and lasted for about six months. In the early years of the reign, Charles VIII's mother died, and he remarried his first cousin Anne Boleyn. Calendar in Arabic is the name given to the Western system of timekeeping used throughout the Middle East, North Africa, Asia, and India.

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae. These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are easily recognised by their characteristic flower spikes and fruiting "cones" and heads. Banksias range in size from prostrate woody shrubs to trees up to 30 metres (100 ft) tall. They are found in a wide variety of landscapes: sclerophyll forest, (occasionally) rainforest, shrubland, and some more arid landscapes, though not in Australia's deserts.Heavy producers of nectar, banksias are a vital part of the food chain in the Australian bush.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch (15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908) was a German humorist, poet, illustrator, and painter. He published wildly innovative illustrated tales that remain influential to this day.Busch drew on the tropes of folk humour as well as a profound knowledge of German literature and art to satirize contemporary life, any kind of piety, Catholicism, Philistinism, religious morality, bigotry, and moral uplift.His mastery of drawing and verse became deeply influential for future generations of comic artists and vernacular poets. Among many notable influences, The Katzenjammer Kids was inspired by Busch's Max and Moritz.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to Charles Beauclerk, his illegitimate son by Nell Gwyn. January 15 (January 5 O.S.) - To demonstrate that the River Thames, frozen solid during the Great Frost that started in December, is safe to walk upon, "a Coach and six horses drove over the Thames for a wager" and within three days "whole streets of Booths are built on the Thames and thousands of people are continually walking thereon." Sir Richard Newdigate, 2nd Baronet, records the events in his diary.

For other nobles of the same name, please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria (26 July 1439 – 1 February 1501) was a member of the Wittelsbach dynasty. He ruled as Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, and then as Duke of Bavaria-Dachau until his death.BiographySigismund was the third son of Albert III of Bavaria with Princess Anna of Brunswick-Grubenhagen-Einbeck his second wife.Sigismund was Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, until 1463 together with his brother John IV. In 1467, he resigned in favor of his younger brother Albert IV and then kept only the new duchy of Bavaria-Dachau as his domain until his death.

Events  January–June  January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia, by Ivan the Terrible. January 11 – Sir Walter Mildmay is given a royal licence to found Emmanuel College, Cambridge. March 18 (N.S. March 28) – Ivan the Terrible, ruler of Russia since 1533, dies; he is succeeded as Tsar by his son, Feodor. May 17 – The conflict between Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Tokugawa Ieyasu culminates in the Battle of Nagakute. June 1 – With the death of the Duc d'Anjou, the Huguenot Henry of Navarre becomes heir-presumptive to the throne of France.

Year 1363 ( MCCCLXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, December 26. It was also the birthday of Saint Christopher Columbus. The date is not in use in the Roman calendar, since there is no year 1363 in that order. A car is a three-wheeled, motor vehicle powered mainly by internal combustion engine, which is used primarily for moving large numbers of humans or other non-cargo vehicles through city streets. Most modern cars are manufactured from steel and aluminum, but most early cars were made of wood, iron, or some other lightweight material.

Year 1316 (MCCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 28–March 18 – Llywelyn Bren revolts against English rule in Wales. February 22 – Battle of Picotin: Catalan forces of Ferdinand of Majorca defeat those of Matilda of Hainaut on the Peloponnese. July 5 – Battle of Manolada: Forces of the Duchy of Burgundy defeat the Kingdom of Majorca, kill its king, Ferdinand, and conquer the Principality of Achaea. August – Battle of Gransee: A North German-Danish alliance, led by Henry II of Mecklenburg, decisively defeats the forces of Waldemar of Brandenburg.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

Year 1035 (MXXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July – The 8-year-old William I becomes duke of Normandy, after his father Robert I (the Magnificent) dies, on a pilgrimage at Nicaea (modern Turkey). Robert's death leads to a period of instability in Normandy, as William is too young to take his father's place. The Norman nobles in the region take the opportunity to settle old feuds, and to increase their private wealth.

Events  January–June  January 13 – Edward Sexby, who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell, dies in the Tower of London. February 6 – Swedish troops of Charles X Gustav of Sweden cross The Great Belt in Denmark, over frozen sea. February 26 (March 8 NS) – The peace between Sweden and Denmark is concluded in Roskilde by the Treaty of Roskilde, under which Denmark is forced to cede significant territory. March 22 – The ship Waeckende Boey is wrecked on the coast of Java; the four survivors walk overland to Jepara.

In probability theory, the central limit theorem (CLT) establishes that, in many situations, when independent random variables are summed up, their properly normalized sum tends toward a normal distribution (informally a bell curve) even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed. The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions. This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.

Mariner 3 (together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed and built by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) for NASA's Mariner-Mars 1964 project that were intended to conduct close-up (flyby) scientific observations of the planet Mars and transmit information on interplanetary space and the space surrounding Mars, televised images of the Martian surface and radio occultation data of spacecraft signals as affected by the Martian atmosphere back to Earth.Although the launch was initially successful, there was a separation issue and Mariner 3 stopped responding when its batteries ran out of power.

Broca's area, or the Broca area (, also , ), is a region in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, usually the left, of the brain with functions linked to speech production.Language processing has been linked to Broca's area since Pierre Paul Broca reported impairments in two patients. They had lost the ability to speak after injury to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus (pars triangularis) (BA45) of the brain. Since then, the approximate region he identified has become known as Broca's area, and the deficit in language production as Broca's aphasia, also called expressive aphasia.

ext3, or third extended filesystem, is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel. It used to be the default file system for many popular Linux distributions. Stephen Tweedie first revealed that he was working on extending ext2 in Journaling the Linux ext2fs Filesystem in a 1998 paper, and later in a February 1999 kernel mailing list posting. The filesystem was merged with the mainline Linux kernel in November 2001 from 2.4.15 onward. Its main advantage over ext2 is journaling, which improves reliability and eliminates the need to check the file system after an unclean shutdown.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative , facultative anaerobic , rod-shaped , coliform bacterium. It is a member of the genus Escherichia, but is most closely related to Klebsiella pneumoniae . Like other aerobic and anaerobic bacteria, it reproduces by a division of labor whereby each cell utilizes a different enzyme for fermentation. In E. coli, the cells form clusters called sporangiocytes that colonize food particles such as sugars, polysaccharides, and proteins in the intestines of vertebrates.Spores of E. coli can be used to establish new strains of the bacterium that are more virulent or efficient at causing disease when transferred to hosts.

Kanji (; also  武知; ; pronounced "ka-nu") is a Japanese ideograph which represents the kanji characters in Chinese character form. Many characters use the same symbol for both phonemes: for instance, 得 can represent both う and 財.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Before the release of DeCSS, open source operating systems (such as BSD and Linux) could not play encrypted video DVDs.DeCSS's development was done without a license from the DVD Copy Control Association (CCA), the organization responsible for DVD copy protection—namely, the Content Scramble System (CSS) used by commercial DVD publishers. The release of DeCSS resulted in a Norwegian criminal trial and subsequent acquittal of one of the authors of DeCSS.

Year 1484 ( MCDLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar.It was used from November 2, 1752 to December 31, 1857. It was adopted as an official holiday of Great Britain on the eve of Christmas in 1878, and in France on April 30, 1883. The date has been used since 1752 for the Roman Catholic celebration of Easter. The American Civil War (commonly referred to as the Civil War) took place from June 12, 1861 until August 9, 1865, with over four hundred thousand U.S. soldiers losing their lives during that period.

1581 ( MDLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Europe and Latin America. Abigail  (January 1819 – April 21, 1919) was an American actress who won an Academy Award for best actress for her performance in the 1920 film, The Producers. She also made numerous television appearances.Early lifeAbigail was born on January 18, 1819, to Richard Adams (17 December 1772 – 31 May 1841) and Emma Adams (17 October 1792 – 1 January 1835). Her parents were poor English farmers from Pennsylvania.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was a Roman empress who governed the empire from about 305 until death in 312.She is considered by historians to be one of the most brilliant and successful women rulers of the early first century, and is venerated for her humanitarian works throughout the Christian East.Early lifeHer birth took place on 25 January 311, after the emperor Vespasian reestablished control over the western territories which had been seized by his son Titus. Adrian was the daughter of Emperor Tiberius and his wife Julia Augusta.

Year 1420 (MCDXX) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March – The Çelebi Sultan Mehmed Mosque in Didymoteicho is inaugurated. May 21 – Treaty of Troyes:  With the Burgundian faction dominant in France, King Charles VI of France acknowledges Henry V of England as his heir, and as virtual ruler of most of France. May 25 –  Henry the Navigator is appointed governor of the Portuguese Order of Christ. June 2 – Catherine of Valois marries King Henry V of England.

Year 1539 (MDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Toungoo–Hanthawaddy War – Battle of Naungyo, Burma: The Toungoos decisively defeat the Hanthawaddys. Lead azide is an inorganic compound . More so than other azides , is explosive . Abraham Lincoln was the forty-third President of the United States from 1861 to 1865. He served from February 13, 1861 to March 3, 1865, during which time he became the longest serving president in US history. He was born on January 22, 1809, the second of three sons of John Todd Lincoln (1813–1892) and Mary Elizabetta Lincoln (1806–1885).

Jan Bos ( born 29 March 1975 ) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist . In the late 1990s he won several international championships, first as a member of the Belgian national team. He also won the World Youth Olympic Championship in 1998, as well as competing in the European Championships in 2001 and 2003, where he placed fourth in both events.In 2004, he became the youngest man ever to cross the 20-kilometre world marathon distance, completing the feat in 6 hours, 13 minutes and 10 seconds. Christer Jakobsson (; 28 November 1885 – 8 December 1967) was a Swedish author of science fiction novels.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde ( born 30 November 1971 ) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in double backflips during his long career as a professional. Year 1482 ( MCDLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar of the Roman Catholic Church. It was used from 1552 until its abolition in 1691 by the Reforma Ordinariae Apostolicae, the successor organization of the Congregation for Divine Worship.The Gregorian calendar was introduced in 1582 by Pope Sixtus IV during his papacy and remained in effect until 1878 when it was abolished by the Latin Patriarchate. Josiah Bartlett (November 23, 1772  – December 1, 1793) was an American minister and journalist.

Gravity , or gravitation, is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy, including planets, stars, galaxies and even light, are attracted to (or gravitate toward) one another. On Earth, gravity gives weight to physical objects, and the Moon's gravity causes the tides of the oceans. The gravitational attraction of the original gaseous matter present in the Universe caused it to begin coalescing and forming stars and caused the stars to group together into galaxies, so gravity is responsible for many of the large-scale structures in the Universe.

is the Latin name under which the `` Lamb of God '' is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other liturgies throughout the Roman Catholic Church, and in some Christian traditions to symbolize Christ's resurrection from the dead. It was originally called the "Lamb of God", but it has also been Anglicized as "The Lamb of God" (also ).The word is derived from Old High German, meaning "light". In mathematics , the number line (also known as the cardinality diagram) is a horizontal line that represents the set of all integers greater or equal to two.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

Year 1419 ( MCDXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic and Orthodox calendars. It is often associated with Mary, Queen of Scots, but is also associated with the 12th century saint Columban.The date of the birth of Jesus Christ was not determined until after his crucifixion for which he is widely accepted to have been born sometime between April 30 and May 1, according to some ancient sources. Carpathia  is a subfamily of the Sphenogaster subfamily; the two subfamilies are separated by a narrow peninsula off the Italian island of Sicily.

Year 1433 (MCDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 31 – Sigismund is crowned Holy Roman Emperor in Rome. There has been no crowned Emperor since the death of his father, Charles IV, in 1378. August 14 – Edward I becomes King of Portugal. September – Cosimo de' Medici, later the de facto ruler of Florence and patron of Marsilio Ficino, is exiled by the Albizzi/Strozzi faction (Cosimo returns a year later, in September 1434).

John Bunyan ( ; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688 ) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of Pilgrim's Progress.Bunyan is sometimes called the founding father of evangelical Christianity, which has become a dominant religious tradition in England since the early 17th century.In his life and preaching he is widely acknowledged to have been instrumental in the evangelisation of the American colonies and other regions of Christendom. He was born at London, where his father John Bunyan (15 July 1580 – 20 February 1692) was then living as a clergyman, and became a local parish priest.

Sigismund (26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496), a member of the House of Habsburg, was Duke of Austria from 1439 (elevated to Archduke in 1477) until his death. As a scion of the Habsburg Leopoldian line, he ruled over Further Austria and the County of Tyrol from 1446 until his resignation in 1490.BiographySigismund (or Siegmund, sometimes also spelled Sigmund) was born at the Tyrolean court in Innsbruck; his parents were the Further Austrian duke Frederick IV of Austria and his second wife , a daughter of the Welf duke Frederick I of Brunswick-Lüneburg.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage (born 9 July 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two Olympic gold medals in Salt Lake City and was the 2002 World Allround champion. He retired in 2007 at the age of 30, following two consecutive seasons of poor results.BiographyUytdehaage was born on 9 July 1976 in Oog in Al, Utrecht, Netherlands. He was the 2002 European Allround champion. During the 2002 Winter Olympics, he won the gold medal in the 5,000 and 10,000 meter events and the silver in the 1500 meter event.

Year 1216 ( MCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in January of every year. A chronometer is a mechanical instrument that measures time, usually for use in agriculture, as both a way to distinguish between long- and short-day conditions and to indicate how close one is to the future. The most common types are hand clocks and sundials, but other types exist for more mundane purposes such as telling the time during a medical exam.In mathematics, chronometers are often called atomic clocks, or atomic ticks, because there is only one unit of time measured by them.

Kaiyodo  is an umbrella term that covers several groups of Japanese companies, many of which are subsidiaries of the Toyota Corporation. The company is based in Kanda, Tokyo. It is the third-largest auto-industry corporation in Japan after Toyota and Honda. In 2003, the corporation had a market capitalisation of approximately US$6.5 billion.

Year 1427 (MCDXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Spring – Radu II of Wallachia resumes the throne for the fourth time, but a seven-year struggle for it ends when he is defeated in battle, and probably killed, by Dan II, who resumes the throne for a fifth term. April – The House of Balsic's rule of Montenegro comes to an end with the death of Balša III. August 4 – Hussite Wars: Battle of Tachov – The Hussites decisively beat the crusader armies, ending the Fourth Anti-Hussite Crusade.

Events January–June January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan , known as the Ratio Studiorum , is issued . March 16 – Pope Paul VI sends an encyclical letter in which he encourages Catholics and other believers to "do what you love without fear", and to "love thy neighbour as yourself". April 21 – The first mass of the liturgy of the Word is celebrated at St. Mary Major, Manchester, England. The House of Saud (Arabic:  شريق الوزار ;  نسى الجماع والناس) is a country in the Southern Arabian Peninsula that borders Oman to the north and the Gulf of Aqaba to the east.

Year 1379 ( MCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending with the feast of St. James the Apostle in July. The Julian calendar developed around this year, but the Julian day numbers started after 1378. It was adopted at the Council of Nicea in 325 as the official Julian calendar.The Julian calendar was first officially adopted by Emperor Justinian in 541, followed by his successor, Charles V (543-652), who made it the basis of his administration for nearly three decades.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman. Set in Hawaii, the show originally aired for 12 seasons from 1968 to 1980, and continues in reruns. At the airing of its last episode, it was the longest-running police drama in American television history and the last fictional primetime show that debuted in the 1960s to leave the air.The show starred Jack Lord as Detective Captain Stephen "Steve" McGarrett, the head of a special state police task force in Hawaii which was based on an actual unit that existed under martial law after  World War II.

Year 1337 ( MCCCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the medieval Christian Church. Abu Huraira b. Mu'azzam al-Qurazi (died 636/38) was the son of al-Mansur bin 'Abd Al-'Aziz Ibn 'Amir al-Kabir and daughter of Abdallah Bin Qays. He became a companion to the Prophet Muhammad and a strong advocate of Islam, although he is often seen as the founder of Wahhabism.

Year 1526 (MDXXVI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 14 – Treaty of Madrid: Peace is declared between Francis I of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. Francis agrees to cede Burgundy and abandons all claims to Flanders, Artois, Naples, and Milan. In astronomy and astrophysics, the  is the unit of the celestial sphere, the distance from Earth to the Sun, in arcminutes. The orbital period of the Earth's orbit around the Sun is approximately 365.242 days; this means that the Earth revolves around its axis more than once every 365.242 days, or almost every 30 years.

Year 1429 (MCDXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 12 – Battle of Rouvray (or "of the Herrings"): English forces under Sir John Fastolf defend a supply convoy, which is carrying rations (food) to the army of William de la Pole, 4th Earl of Suffolk at Orléans, from attack by the Comte de Clermont and John Stewart. April 29 – Siege of Orléans: Joan of Arc enters Orléans with a relief expedition. May 7 – The Tourelles, the last English siege fortification at Orléans, falls.

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. The Montreal Expos played their first game as an expansion franchise on June 29, 1969 in Washington D.C. The team was purchased from the Montreal Expos in August 1971 by George Brett of the Boston Red Sox for a reported $1.75 million. The Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) is the military arm of the Government of Canada. CAF personnel are trained primarily in ground forces, with the addition of special operations capabilities.

Juggling is a physical skill , performed by a juggler , involving the manipulation of objects for recreation , entertainment , or other purposes. Juggling originated in Medieval Europe . It has remained a popular form of traditional and modern juggling, with over twenty-thousand years of history behind it. Kurt Angle (  ; born August 2, 1964) is an American professional mixed martial artist (MMA fighter) who is currently the head coach for Team Alpha Male (TNA). He is the former wrestling champion for the now defunct World Wrestling Federation, which he led from 1993 until his defeat by Brock Lesnar at Wrestlemania XIX in 2005.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation. It commonly consists of a magnetized needle or other element, such as a compass card or compass rose, which can pivot to align itself with magnetic north. Other methods may be used, including gyroscopes, magnetometers, and GPS receivers.Compasses often show angles in degrees: north corresponds to 0°, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90°, south is 180°, and west is 270°. These numbers allow the compass to show azimuths or bearings which are commonly stated in degrees.

Uracil  (symbol U or Ura) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are represented by the letters A, G, C and U. The others are adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G). In RNA, uracil binds to adenine via two hydrogen bonds. In DNA, the uracil nucleobase is replaced by thymine. Uracil is a demethylated form of thymine.Uracil is a common and naturally occurring pyrimidine derivative. The name "uracil" was coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.

Bessarabia (; ; ; , Bessarabiya; ; , Bessarabiya; , Besarabiya) is a historical region in Eastern Europe, bounded by the Dniester river on the east and the Prut river on the west. About two thirds of Bessarabia lies within modern-day Moldova, with the Ukrainian Budjak region covering the southern coastal region and part of the Ukrainian Chernivtsi Oblast covering a small area in the north.In the aftermath of the Russo-Turkish War (1806–1812), and the ensuing Peace of Bucharest, the eastern parts of the Principality of Moldavia, an Ottoman vassal, along with some areas formerly under direct Ottoman rule, were ceded to Imperial Russia.

Events  January–June  January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England. February – English pirates carry out the sack of Campeche in Mexico. Events January–December February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna , ending the da Polenta Dynasty . The Romans (or Romani, as they are also called in France) were a Celtic people who inhabited Britain and Ireland around the 7th century BC. Some scholars believe that the origins of the Romans can be traced to two distinct tribes of Gauls called Celtiberii and Thraciani, whose origins are not known. Roman writers mention Celts as early as the 8th century AD when it is said that they had settled in Italy.

Year 1293 ( MCCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Europe and Southern Africa during the 11th century CE. In biology, an age class is a set of characteristics that may be measured over time, or across generations. Age classes are often used by biologists to assess the evolutionary processes at work in biological populations. A typical example is the population-wide life cycle, which spans a period ranging from a single generation to thousands of years.

Élie Ducommun (19 February 1833, Geneva – 7 December 1906, Bern) was a Swiss peace activist. He was a Nobel laureate, awarded the 1902 Nobel Peace Prize, which he shared with Charles Albert Gobat.Born in Geneva, he worked as a tutor, language teacher, journalist and a translator for the Swiss federal Chancellery (1869–1873).In 1867 he helped to found the Ligue de la paix et de la liberté (League of Peace and Freedom), though he continued working at other positions, including secretary for the Jura-Simplon Steel Company from 1873 to 1891.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It is one of the largest manufacturers of integrated circuits, graphics chips, and other technologies used in computer hardware, semiconductors, and telecommunications systems. As of March 2015, its revenue totaled $10.7 billion from sales of approximately $5.9 billion worldwide. It is listed on the S&P 500 Index.HistoryThe company was founded by Charles P. Thomson, Jr. and Thomas A. Thomson in 1891. Georgetown University (also Georgetown University), also known as Georgetown College, is a private Catholic liberal arts college founded in 1776.

Year 1578 (MDLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 31 – Battle of Gembloux: Spanish forces under Don John of Austria and Alexander Farnese defeat the Dutch; Farnese begins to recover control of the French-speaking Southern Netherlands. April 27 – The Duel of the Mignons claims the lives of two favorites of Henry III of France, and two favourites of Henry I, Duke of Guise. May 26 – The Alteratie in Amsterdam ends Catholic rule, and open Catholic worship there.

The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from over 70 countries, which began on November 1, 1952 and ended on September 8, 2018. Hosted annually by the Organizing Committee of the Commonwealth Games , the event draws participants from a wide range of nations throughout the Americas, Asia, Australia, Europe, Oceania, Africa, and beyond.History The Commonwealth Games were created in 1952 by the Federation of International Associations (FIAC). In physics there are three kinds of elementary particles known as bosons, fermions, and photons.

In mathematics, an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere, which is the set of points in -dimensional Euclidean space that are situated at a constant distance  from a fixed point, called the center. It is the generalization of an ordinary sphere in the ordinary three-dimensional space. The "radius" of a sphere is the constant distance of its points to the center. When the sphere has unit radius, it is usual to call it the unit -sphere or simply the -sphere for brevity.

Year 1059 ( MLIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Imperial Calendar.The first day of that year was named after Augustus, son of Tiberius, Emperor of Rome, who took the throne on November 19, 79 A.D. Abu Bakr  ( ; or تعبيد Abu-bakr; ) was a 7th-century Arabian historian, jurist, and poet who is one of the most prolific Islamic writers in history.

James Madison is commonly considered the father of the United States Constitution  and the most influential man in U.S. government history. At the age of 21, he was elected president of the Continental Congress, becoming the youngest person to serve as commander in chief of the continental army.

Year 1038 (MXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) travels to Southern Italy and holds court in Troia. He orders Pandulf IV of Capua to restore the territories of Monte Cassino. Pandulf holes himself up in the fortress of Sant'Agata de' Goti, and dispatches tribute (300 lb of gold) and his son as hostage to Troia as a token of peace. Conrad accepts his offer, but the son escapes.

Year 1541 (MDXLI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds Santiago del Nuevo Extremo, which will become the capital of Chile. April 7 – Francis Xavier leaves Lisbon, on a mission to the Portuguese East Indies. April 24 – Battle of Sahart: Gelawdewos is defeated by the forces of Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi. May 8 – Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto reaches the Mississippi River, naming it the Rio de Espiritu Santo ("River of the Holy Spirit").

Stigmata ( , plural of , 'mark , spot , brand ' ) , in Christianity , are the appearance of evil, sin, or imperfection on a person's body after death. The first known recorded instance of a stigmata took place in the 2nd century BC in Egypt; it was recorded by the Greek writer Plutarch. The Social Security Act (SSA), commonly referred to as the Social Security Act, is the largest federal legislation enacted since the Civil War and the most important federal legislation for providing health insurance to people under 65 years of age.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation for sale in its Radio Shack and Radio Shack Computer Center chains of stores.OverviewIn December 1983, an executive with Tandy Corporation, maker of TRS-80 computers, said about the new IBM PCjr: "I'm sure a lot of people will be coming out with PCjr look-alikes. The market is big". While preparing the Tandy 2000—the company's first MS-DOS computer—for release in November 1983, Tandy began designing the Tandy 1000, code named "August".

The National Botanic Gardens (Irish: Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin, 5 km north-west of Dublin city centre, Ireland. The 19.5 hectares are situated between Glasnevin Cemetery and the River Tolka where it forms part of the river's floodplain.The gardens were founded in 1795 by the Dublin Society (later the Royal Dublin Society) and are today in State ownership through the Office of Public Works. They house approximately 20,000 living plants and many millions of dried plant specimens. There are several architecturally notable greenhouses.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago. Formerly one of the "Big Five" accounting firms (along with PricewaterhouseCoopers, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Ernst & Young, and KPMG), the company had provided auditing, tax and consulting services to large corporations. By 2001, it had become one of the world's largest multinational corporations.In 2002, the firm voluntarily surrendered its licenses to practice as Certified Public Accountants in the United States after it was found guilty of crimes in the firm's auditing of Enron, an energy corporation based in Texas, which had filed for bankruptcy in 2001.

Perpignan (, , ;  ;  ;  ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department (known as Northern Catalonia) in southern France, in the heart of the plain of Roussillon, at the foot of the Pyrenees a few kilometres from the Mediterranean Sea and the scrublands of the Corbières massif. It is the centre of the Perpignan Mediterranée Métropole metropolitan area.In 2016 Perpignan had a population of 121,875 (Perpignanais(e) in French, Perpinyanés(a) in Catalan) in the commune proper, and the metropolitan area had a total population of 268,577, making it the last major French city before the Spanish border.

Year 1509 ( MDIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calender. There is nothing to say that it follows a specific pattern, and its meaning may vary depending on region and time periods. It is the first month of the Gregorian calendar. Galapagos  is a small archipelago located at the south-western part of the Northern Hemisphere. It is home to about 60,000 residents and is an important tourist destination. The island consists of more than 80,000 sq km of sand dunes and is inhabited by over 10,000 varieties of birds.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

GNU Privacy Guard ( GnuPG or GPG ) is a free-software replacement for Symantec 's PGP cryptographic software suite . It's been in development for more than 20 years. It was originally developed by Keith Teague at the University of Toronto and is maintained by David Langford at the University of California, Berkeley.GnuPG is based on the public key cryptography standard RFC 676, and as such supports several different backdoors. George Lucas ( July 12, 1946 – April 19, 2005) was an American film director, producer and writer.Lucas was born in Los Angeles, California, where he attended Hollywood High School.

Year 1043 (MXLIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Constantine IX Monomachos sends a Byzantine expeditionary force to the Balkans against the rebellious George Maniakes, governor of the Catepanate of Italy. The rebel army – better organized, seasoned and with superior leadership – fights initially successful, but Maniakes is killed by an arrow at the moment of his triumph. After this, his army is routed.

The Chagrian language is one of the four major Indo-European languages, spoken by more than 1.8 million people across the entire range of present-day Turkey.

Jacques René Chirac ( , , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019 ) was a French politician who served as Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1983. He is one of the few political figures in Europe who was elected to be president of both France and his own native country, the Republic of France. A member of the Socialist Party of France, he became prime minister after the second world war at the age of 28. Chiapas, commonly known as Tiahuanaco, is the capital city of the Mexican state of Chiapas, on the Yucatán Peninsula of Mexico.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 and Mariner 12 ) one of three Mariner probes launched into the solar system by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration to look for evidence of an alien megastructural civilization in the early 1970s. The Marmot, or Moccasin Mouse, is a medium-sized marsupial from eastern Australia which belongs to the family Cricetidae. In Australia they range from northern Queensland to central Victoria, although they are restricted to the lower reaches of the coastal plain. Males tend to be larger on average than females, measuring up to two metres in length.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive, Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed as a separate entity from 1977 until September 2001, when it was bought by RadiSys Corp., and became a division of that company. The rights to Microware OS-9 and related software were purchased by a group of distributors on 1 March 2013. The new owner was Microware LP. Microware initially produced a version of BASIC and a real-time kernel for the Motorola 6800 processor, and was asked by Motorola to develop what turned into BASIC09 for the then-new Motorola 6809 processor.

Year 1165 ( MCLXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Eastern Orthodoxy. It was used for counting the years from January 1 until December 31, which is equivalent to 2060–2061 in modern Western mathematics. In the Orthodox calendar, it corresponds with the first day of the first quarter of Tiberius Augustus's reign that lasted from March 3 to April 9, 4 BCE.In Roman Catholicism, the  has traditionally been used to define the feast days of the Holy Apostles, namely St. Mary Magdalene and St. John the Evangelist who both lived during the second century CE.

Year 1027 ( MXXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday.In ancient Roman history, the year 1000 is often referred to as "The Year of Ten". In Christianity, the Christian year (the 1st month of the Christian Gregorian calendar) began on October 25, 4004 BC. This entry gives the name of a mathematical construct which is named for its use in several related disciplines, such as mathematics, physics, computer science, applied mathematics, or engineering.

In the performing arts, a scenario (, ; from Italian: "that which is pinned to the scenery", ) is a synoptical collage of an event or series of actions and events. In the commedia dell'arte it was an outline of entrances, exits, and action describing the plot of a play, and was literally pinned to the back of the scenery. It is also known as canovaccio  or "that which is pinned to the canvas" of which the scenery was constructed.Surviving scenarios from the Renaissance contain little other than character names, brief descriptions of action, and references to specific lazzi with no further explanation.

Year 1211 (MCCXI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  June 17 – Battle of Antioch on the Meander: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I are initially victorious with the Latin mercenary cavalry (some 800 men) bearing the brunt of the casualties due to their flanking charge; exhausted by the effort in their attack, the Latin army under Emperor Theodore I (Laskaris) is struck in the flank and rear by the Seljuk forces.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

Optical rotation, also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence, is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it travels through certain materials. Circular birefringence and circular dichroism are the manifestations of optical activity. Optical activity occurs only in chiral materials, those lacking microscopic mirror symmetry. Unlike other sources of birefringence which alter a beam's state of polarization, optical activity can be observed in fluids. This can include gases or solutions of chiral molecules such as sugars, molecules with helical secondary structure such as some proteins, and also chiral liquid crystals.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim (Modern Gaelic: Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim, ), sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm, called Dén, "the Vehement" and, "the Black" (born c. 928 – died 967) was king of Alba. He was son of Malcolm I and succeeded to the throne when Indulf was killed in 962.While later chroniclers such as John of Fordun supplied a great deal of information on Dub's life and reign, and Hector Boece in his 'The history and chronicles of Scotland' tell tales of witchcraft and treason, almost all of them are rejected by modern historians.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' of Chicago investment firms and now known for its investments in consumer products, it is a subsidiary of Bank of America.It is headquartered at 715 West Randolph Street, Chicago, IL 60610.In 2011, it was the world's second-biggest firm, with revenues of $7.4 billion. In 2015, it became the eighth-largest firm in North America after being acquired by CitiFinancial Corporation (NYSE: Citi) for $2.6 billion in stock, cash and cash equivalents.

Events  January–June  January 7 – The Westminster Assembly begins debating the biblical proof texts, to support the new Confession of Faith. January 16 – Citizens of Dublin declare their support for Rinuccini, and refuse to support the army of the Marquis of Ormond. March 14 – Thirty Years' War: Bavaria, Cologne, France and Sweden sign the Truce of Ulm. April 3 – In England, a letter from the Agitators of the New Model Army, protesting delay of pay, is read in the House of Commons. May 13 – The 1647 Santiago earthquake rattles Chile.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

Events January–June January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London , for multiple thefts and a number of other offenses; February 1 – The Last Night of the Glorious Revolution takes place, ending the English civil war. In politics, government refers to the body that governs the affairs of an individual, state, political group, or community. A government is considered to be functioning only when there is an agreed upon set of policies and values to guide the activities of its elected representatives.Government has two main sources of power: the executive branch of government and the legislature.

Year 1161 ( MCLXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Europe. It is the 13th year of the Gregorian calendar and the 12th year of the Julian calendar, after which both calendars were replaced by the Roman calendar.The first six days are counted as "Sunday". In addition to being the first Monday in an annus reus, it also marks the end of one cycle of the New Moon. The Great Barrier Reef is a coral reef located in the northeastern part of Australia that is the world's third-largest coralship and second-largest living structure.

Johan August Arfwedson ( 12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841 ) was a Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical double bond in 1824. He is sometimes known as the "father of alkylation", for his pioneering work in the development of a new process for making ammonia from hydrocarbons.The Arfwedson process involves the reduction of ammonia to acetaldehyde, which is then transformed into various amines. Andrew Withers  (born September 21, 1951) is an English actor and musician. He has starred in more than 30 feature films over a span of twenty-six years, with his most recent roles coming between 2005 and 2009.

Lazzi ( ; from the Italian lazzo , a joke or witticism ) are stock comedic routines that are associated with certain cultures.The first Lazzi found their way to Spain during the early 16th century where they were used as punchlines by some of the most well-known comedians of that time, such as Gaspar De Fonseca and Diego de Barrios. In the Netherlands it was also popular during the 15th century. Lawrence Livermore Laboratory (LLNL), commonly referred to as Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, is a U.S. Department of Energy national laboratory based in Livermore, California.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

Year 1031 ( MXXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) for the Roman Empire in the Middle Ages.The Julian Calendar, used until the mid–15th century, followed a fixed year-round cycle of 31 March, 365 days, exactly as is the Gregorian Calendar. Konstantin Kievan Rus (February 9, 1868 – August 22, 1924), known also as Konstantin Kulevich or just Krumilov, was a Russian mathematician, scientist, philosopher, novelist, and essayist who wrote extensively on science, philosophy, history, politics, literature, art and music.

Year 1303 ( MCCCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) as opposed to Wednesday, the first day of the week. Amadeus Mozart ( ; 27 March 1492 – 22 January 1541) was an Italian composer and musical theorist best known for writing three operas, "Don Giovanni", "Violetta" and "Bridget". His music is considered to be the pinnacle of the Romantic period, but he is also widely regarded as one of the greatest classical composers of all time.Early lifeHe was born in Montefalco, Italy and educated at Milan, where his parents were from.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice. Most are variations of skiing, ice skating and sledding. Traditionally, such games were only played in cold areas during winter, but artificial snow and artificial ice allow more flexibility. Playing areas and fields consist of either snow or ice. Artificial ice can be used to provide ice rinks for ice skating, ice hockey, ringette, indoor broomball, bandy, rink bandy, rinkball, and spongee in a milder climate.

Year 1037 (MXXXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – A revolt in northern Italy is started by Archbishop Aribert of Milan. King Henry III (eldest son of Emperor Conrad II) travels south of the Alps to quell it. February – At an Imperial Diet in Pavia (assembled by Conrad II), Aribert is accused of fomenting a revolt against the Holy Roman Empire, Conrad orders his arrest. May – Conrad II, with Pavian assistance, lays siege to Milan at the Porta Romana side, but the city holds out.

A conjugate acid, within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, is a  chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H+) to a base—in other words, it is a base with a hydrogen ion added to it, as in the reverse reaction it loses a hydrogen ion. On the other hand, a conjugate base is what is left over after an acid has donated a proton during a chemical reaction. Hence, a conjugate base is a species formed by the removal of a proton from an acid, as in the reverse reaction it is able to gain a hydrogen ion.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow , twisting , banked , ski-like tracks, which may consist of multiple turns, corners and turns within a short distance. The athletes are covered in snow and have the advantage of being very efficient at moving across the track using their skis, as they are not bound by the weight of the sled.
