Teams compete in a series of events: speed, balance, endurance, and strategy.The history of this sport began in 1897, with the first Winter Olympics in Vancouver, Canada.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday 11 December. Chaucerianism is the belief in the existence of God, or an omnipotent being, who created heaven and earth and all human beings. This concept is associated with various religions and cults, most famously Christianity and Islam. There are several different types of Christian theology that do not believe in God's omnipotence: Some Christians believe that there are no gods, and that everything in the Universe is subject to change.

It is one of eight years ( CE ) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once ( 1000 ( M ), 993 ( L ), 992 ( T ), 886 ( S ) , 883 ( N ), 881 ( U ), 880 ( X ), 879 ( O ), 788 ( V ) , or 777 ( H ). All other years in the table are "incomplete". The Great Game is, in traditional Chinese and Japanese mythology, the competition among ancient Chinese warriors over control of the three great kingdoms: China, Japan and India.

Year 1579 ( MDLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the year 1577 in the Julian calendar. A number of years were considered to have been anniversaries of dates earlier than 1580, but these were mostly omitted from the standard chronology.It is generally accepted by historians that John Paul II was canonized on December 11, 1983 as an Archbishop of St. Peter and Raymond in the Archdiocese of Loyola-Marymount in Los Angeles County.HistoryIn 1581, Francis Xavier ascended the Papal Throne after Benedict XIV's death at the age of thirty-four.

Andorra, officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra<ref>Funk and Wagnalls Encyclopedia##, 1993</ref> , is a sovereign landlocked microstate in Southwestern Europe, located in the eastern Pyrenees mountains and bordered by Spain and France.9th to 19th centuriesAndorra claims it is the last independent survivor of the Marca Hispanica, the buffer states created by Charlemagne to keep the Islamic Moors from advancing into Christian France. Tradition holds that Charlemagne granted a charter to the Andorran people in return for their fighting the Moors.

Events January–March January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company , of the German state of Brandenburg , signs a greaty with the Duke of Hesse. Dalai Lama, (born August 8, 1930) is the spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhism, known as Lhasa Pratyeka, in the People's Republic of China, and the most prominent living Nobel laureate.The Dalai Lama is revered as both a hero and a prophet of the Tibetan people. His office has been occupied by the reincarnation of the 16th century Chinese emperor Gautama I, who was elected by his followers to lead their lives after his death.

Year 1198 (MCXCVIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place The volcano was formed around 4000 years ago and last erupted in 1198 during a phreatic eruption - a powerful steam eruption caused by groundwater interacting with magma. Europe  March 8 – Philip of Swabia, son of the late Emperor Frederick I, is elected "King of Germany" by his supporters at Mühlhausen in Thuringia. Archbishop Adolf of Cologne elects Otto of Brunswick, son of Henry the Lion, as Philip's rival.

Events January–June January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy , the millones . March – Maurice de la Mothe is elected Pope Leo I. February 14 – Charles II abdicates, and Charles VI re-admits his older brother, Louis of Valois as Regent of the Netherlands. The United States Census Bureau (USC) is the central office of the Federal Government responsible for conducting official census enumerations and for collecting, processing, and transmitting statistical information for the distribution to the public of all forms of governmental services, programs, and documents.

Maximilian II (31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576)  was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death in 1576. A member of the Austrian House of Habsburg, he was crowned King of Bohemia in Prague on 14 May 1562 and elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) on 24 November 1562. On 8 September 1563 he was crowned King of Hungary and Croatia in the Hungarian capital Pressburg (Pozsony in Hungarian; now Bratislava, Slovakia). On 25 July 1564 he succeeded his father Ferdinand I as ruler of the Holy Roman Empire.Maximilian's rule was shaped by the confessionalization process after the 1555 Peace of Augsburg.

Year 1136 (MCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Raymond of Poitiers, son of the late Duke William IX of Aquitaine, arrives at Antioch. Patriarch Ralph of Domfront (against the wishes of Princess Alice) arranges a marriage in secret with her 8-year-old daughter Constance. She is kidnapped and taken to the cathedral in Antioch, where Ralph hastily marries her to Raymond. Alice leaves the city, now under the control of Raymond and Ralph, and retires to Latakia, Syria.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc, as well as providing information to the user about the format and size of the media. Its origins can be traced to 1991 when its author, Peter Hessler, discovered that he could decompile Microsoft's .exe files to show how to save file contents in different formats, such as FLV, MPG, OGG, MP3, AAC, etc. In cryptography, public key cryptography involves generating keys from a set of numbers or other objects called public-private key pairs (PRKs).

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India. It was formed as Alleppey district on 17 August 1957, the name of the district being changed to Alappuzha in 1990, and is the smallest district in Kerala. Alleppey town, the district headquarters, was renamed Alappuzha in 2012, even though the anglicised name is still commonly used to describe the town as well as the district.The district is best known for its picturesque backwaters, by which it is well connected to other parts of Kerala, including the tourist destination of Kumarakom, the district being a well known tourist destination.

Gravity , or gravitation , is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy , including planets and galaxies, gravitate toward their own centers of gravity. They are governed by the curvature of space-time . Geopolitics (or geopolitics) is the conduct of national policy by governments towards other countries in the international arena. It is the application of political and legal power to resolve issues in foreign affairs within a given geographical region.Geopolitics consists of two components: foreign relations and internal affairs. Foreign relations involves the use of state power to influence the behaviour of non-state actors, particularly regional and international powers.

Year 1502 ( MDII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar for England and Scotland. The British Empire is an international political union established by Britain in 1867 to govern as a sovereign state.It is comprised of three components: Commonwealth countries, who are members of the European Union (EU) and which are part of the United Nations; independent countries, such as Canada, New Zealand, Australia, and other Pacific Island nations; and dominions, who are states that have no diplomatic ties with the UK.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold, Suffolk, England, by George and Ernest Adnams. It produces cask ale and pasteurised bottled beers. Annual production is around 85,000 barrels.In 2010, the company established the Copper House distillery for the production of gin, vodka and whisky.HistoryThe earliest recorded brewing on the Adnams site was in 1396 by Johanna de Corby.The Sole Bay Brewery in Southwold was purchased in 1872 by George and Ernest Adnams. The company was incorporated in 1890, and has remained independent since then, producing a range of beers for distribution mainly in East Anglia.

Year 1470 (MCDLXX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 12 – Wars of the Roses in England – Battle of Losecoat Field: The House of York defeats the House of Lancaster. March 20 (Julian calendar) – The Battle of Nibley Green is the last fought between the private armies of feudal magnates in England. Spring: Anglo-Hanseatic War: Hanseatic League privateers set sail. May 15 – Charles VIII of Sweden, who has served three terms as King of Sweden, dies.

Year 1293 (MCCXCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAfrica December – Mamluk sultan of Egypt Khalil is assassinated by his regent Baydara, who briefly claims the sultanate, before being assassinated himself by a rival political faction.Asia May 26 – An earthquake in Kamakura, Japan kills an estimated 23,000. May 31 – The forces of Raden Wijaya win a major victory in the Mongol invasion of Java, which is considered to be the founding date of the city of Surabaya. The Japanese era Shōō ends, and the Einin era begins.

Year 1373 (MCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 24 – The Treaty of Santarém is signed between Ferdinand I of Portugal and Henry II of Castile, ending the second war between the two countries. April 28 – Hundred Years' War: The French re-capture most of Brittany from the English, but are unable to take Brest. May 13 – English anchoress Dame Julian of Norwich receives the sixteen Revelations of Divine Love. June 16 – The Anglo-Portuguese Treaty is signed in London, and is the oldest active treaty in the world.

The Quirinal Hill ( ; ; ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome , at the north-east of the Colosseum, adjacent to the Campo dei Fiori and the Palatine hill. In Roman mythology, Quirinal Hill was the residence of the god Vulcan, an ancestor of Apollo who became the father of the gods. This legend is found in several classical writers, among them Juvenal's Satires and Propertius' Ante-Nicene Fathers. It is sometimes referred to as the "Horn Hill" of Rome, while others have proposed that it is simply known as Quirinal Hill.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

arXiv (pronounced "archive"—the X represents the Greek letter chi [χ]) is an open-access repository of electronic preprints and postprints (known as e-prints) approved for posting after moderation, but not peer review. It consists of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, electrical engineering, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, mathematical finance and economics, which can be accessed online. In many fields of mathematics and physics, almost all scientific papers are self-archived on the arXiv repository before publication in a peer-reviewed journal.

Year 1442 ( MCDXLII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian and Julian calendars in the Western world. It was followed by the Leap Year, which is used around the world for New Year's Day.Early YearsThe year 1442 was the only one that did not have leap years until 1792, when they were adopted in the Gregorian calendar. Arthurian Legend  is a legendary tale written by Geoffrey Chaucer about the Knights of the Round Table and their battles with the usurper King John I of England during the last days of the Roman Empire.

Year 1443 ( MCDXLIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in English–speaking countries.The Gregorian calendar, also known as the Julian Calendar, was adopted in 1582 and remains in place in many countries. In electronics, an interrupt is a signal delivered to a CPU when the CPU has finished processing a special purpose program or other event. There are various ways to interrupt a CPU, which can create some interesting results. Influenza A is a respiratory viral infection that typically infects both humans and animals.

.Year 1134 ( MCXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Latin America. In some regions it took place on Friday, others on Sunday. The year 1134 was also known as Magna Mater Novena (Latin: New Year's Day), Novembris Domini (New Year's Day), or novembris dominica (New Year of the Dog). An alchemy is a system of making chemical compounds by combining elements in various proportions and using the results to transform one element into another.Alchemical processes are used to manufacture many natural substances, both medicinal and industrial.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calends. The exact date of the year's beginning is also known, but is generally assumed to be February 28, 456, or earlier, depending on where in the world you live. Caligula (, ) was the Emperor from 44 to 45 AD. Caligula was elected by the Roman Senate and consul for his province of Rome in 41 AD. He was the last emperor in the Roman Empire, having governed until his death in 45.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, mainly occupied by Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, and parts of Southern Russia. The Caucasus Mountains, including the Greater Caucasus range, have historically been considered a natural barrier between Eastern Europe and Western Asia.Mount Elbrus, Europe's highest mountain, is in the Western Caucasus. On the southern side, the Lesser Caucasus includes the Javakheti Plateau and the Armenian highlands, part of which is in Turkey.The Caucasus is divided into the North Caucasus and South Caucasus, although the Western Caucasus also exists as a distinct geographic space within the North Caucasus.

The sousaphone is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba . Created around 1893, the sousaphone had an initial price of $7.50 per half-sock or $25 per quarter, and was available only in the United States (with a few exceptions). In Australia, Canada, and New Zealand, it became a popular musical instrument in the 1910s and 20s, with its popularity rising further in the 1960s and early 1970s. Sir Isaac Newton  (; ; 25 April 1727 – 14 February 1727) was one of the six most important scientists of the 18th century.

Freestyle skiing is a skiing discipline comprising aerials , moguls , cross , half-pipe , slopestyle and big air as defined by World Ski Federation (WSFS) criteria. They were first introduced at the 1984 Winter Olympics, and are now recognised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC). It has been included in the Olympic programs of more than 100 nations. In mathematics, a Bernoulli number is a number which is divided by two or more positive integers. It is sometimes denoted using the letter "n", often written as "B n ", but this can lead to ambiguities and contradictions in certain contexts.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. The disease begins with weakness, blurred vision, feeling tired, and trouble speaking. This may then be followed by weakness of the arms, chest muscles, and legs. Vomiting, swelling of the abdomen, and diarrhea may also occur. The disease does not usually affect consciousness or cause a fever.Botulism can be spread in several ways. The bacterial spores which cause it are common in both soil and water. They produce the botulinum toxin when exposed to low oxygen levels and certain temperatures.

Adrian of Nicomedia (also known as Hadrian) or Saint Adrian (, died 4 March 306) was a Herculian Guard of the Roman Emperor Galerius Maximian. After becoming a convert to Christianity with his wife Natalia (Ναταλία), Adrian was martyred at Nicomedia in Asia-Minor             (Turkey). Hadrian was the chief military saint of Northern Europe for many ages, second only to Saint George, and is much revered in Flanders, Germany and the north of France.MartyrdomAdrian and Natalia lived in Nicomedia during the time of Emperor Maximian in the early fourth century.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Hoddesdon, East Sussex. The Librarians of Alexandria were a Hellenized Christian group, which was founded in Alexandria in the 2nd century CE. They are one of several pre-Christian groups whose existence is attributed to the New Testament author Paul, who may have known about them since before his own conversion to Christianity at Antioch (c. A.D. 70). Early Christians had already been familiar with the Librarians throughout antiquity, but it is unclear precisely how their presence in the ancient world came to be understood.

Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

Year 1276 (MCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.It is the only Year of Four Popes.Events By areaAfrica Mamluk sultan Baibars conquers Al-Maris, previously part of Makuria, and annexes it into Egypt.Americas A severe 23-year drought begins to affect the Grand Canyon area, eventually forcing the agriculture-dependent Anasazi culture to migrate out of the region.Asia February – The court of the Southern Song Dynasty of China and hundreds of thousands of its citizens flee from Hangzhou to Fujian, and then Guangdong, in an effort to escape an invasion by Kublai Khan's Yuan Dynasty.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the rose family that grows to a height of 2–4 metres. It is an evergreen woodland tree that can reach a diameter of more than 1 metre. There are over 4,000 genera and 7,600 species of native oak across the world. Apollo 11  was the seventh mission of the manned Apollo 11 lunar orbiter on 20 January 1972. It performed the first docking between two craft, the Skylab Space Station and the Soviet Vostok-6 spacecraft, which had landed at the Earth-orbiting end of the moon.

Year 1332 ( MCCCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Italy, but it does not end on any day. The year 1332 started on 22 February 1328 and ends on 23 June 1336.This year has been commonly abbreviated Tiberius, although this is generally not strictly correct. In mathematics, a rational number n can be expressed as a product  of two binary numbers x and y such that n2x+n3y is a polynomial with integer coefficients.A rational number n is said to be irreducible if its digits do not satisfy the Pythagorean theorem or the Riemann hypothesis.

Year 1490 ( MCDXC ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the Gregorian calendar. In modern English, it is called "Friday" for this reason. The Great Flood of Noah , also known as the Flood of Sennacherib, and the Flood of Ararat, is the greatest flood that has ever occurred in the history of the human species, occurring approximately 12,000 years ago. It is sometimes called the Second Great Flood because it coincides with the end of the Flood story in the Torah.

Year 1344 ( MCCCXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Western Europe, which is defined as having 365 days.The date 1345 is a leap year within the Gregorian calendar; there are two weeks between the end of March 31 and the start of August 2. The British Army Corps of Engineers was a branch of the United Kingdom's armed forces. Formed in 1919 as the Ministry of Information, it was established in 1922 to coordinate and supervise the work of the newly created Ministry of Defence and the Royal Marines.

Year 1185 (MCLXXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August – King William II (the Good) lands in Epirus with a Siculo-Norman expeditionary force of 200 ships and 80,000 men (including 5,000 knights), and marches as far as the Byzantine city of Thessalonica, which he takes and pillages (massacring some 7,000 Greek citizens). September 11–12 – Isaac II (Angelos) leads a revolt in Constantinople and deposes Emperor Andronikos I (Komnenos).

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . The plant is native to Africa and Asia. Bamboos occur in temperate, tropical, subtropical, and temperate subtropical zones worldwide. The genus name comes from the Arabic word "bamboa," which means "pale yellow. "The plant is distinguished from other genera of bamboos due to its large size, dark brown leaves, and small flowers. In many parts of the tropics, Bamboos are found scattered throughout the lowland rain forest. It also occurs in savannahs, mountain forests, and deciduous forests.

Georg Hackl (often named: Hackl Schorsch, ; born 9 September 1966) is a German former luger who was three time Olympic and World Champion. He is known affectionately as Hackl-Schorsch or as the Speeding Weißwurst a reference to what he looks like in his white bodysuit coming down the luge at fast speeds.BiographyHackl was born in Berchtesgaden, Bavaria. He took up luge as part of his physical education lessons whilst at school, learning to slide at the Königssee track.Hackl was known for his rivalry with Markus Prock, with Prock being dominant in World Cup competition whilst Hackl consistently achieved success at the Winter Olympics.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped, facultatively anaerobic, motile, beta-hemolytic, spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil, food and marine sponges. The specific name, cereus, meaning "waxy" in Latin, refers to the appearance of colonies grown on blood agar. Some strains are harmful to humans and cause foodborne illness, while other strains can be beneficial as probiotics for animals. The bacteria is classically contracted from fried rice dishes that have been sitting at room temperature for hours. B. cereus bacteria are facultative anaerobes, and like other members of the genus Bacillus, can produce protective endospores.

Year 1548 ( MDXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Hemisphere. It marks the end of a leap year that began on Wednesday and ended on Thursday. The Chinese zodiac is a twelve-month calendar, based on the  system of Gregorian calendar, which was developed by Emperor Wu (c. 679-713) of the Ching dynasty (ca. 1378-1644). The 12 signs of the zodiac represent five classes of planets, or aspects, and correspond to the five cardinal points of the natural world.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a prostitute. She is used most often in relationship to the vecchi of which group she is a nominal member. Ruffiana is most often romantically involved with Pantalone, though his love may easily be unrequited if it suits the plot. She is generally described as being talkative/gossipy, sneaky, and mischievous, but deep down is actually kind. She has been described as an "outsider" that always mixes things up and causes trouble for the rest of the characters.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating , such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy becomes visible decreases by . The expansion of the universe is accelerated by gravity (the gravitational lens effect) due to the presence of dark matter, which comprises about 90% of the observed mass. Astronomers use measurements of changes in the light emitted by distant galaxies to determine how fast the universe is expanding. The data from these observations can be compared with predictions from inflation theories and other models of the Big Bang cosmology.

Year 1182 ( MCLXXXII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday . The earliest example of a day with a leap day can be found on April 5, 1 BC when an earlier date was used. The first day of the month had a leap day, February 2, 1258.On the Gregorian calender, days are numbered according to their order in the year. Fulvio Filippo Biondini (; 9 September 181914 – 22 June 1915) was an Italian opera composer and violinist. He is best known as the composer behind the symphony No.

Year 1302 ( MCCCII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Italy. It was not officially considered part of the Gregorian calendar until the 13th century.In Italy, the 12 months of the year consist of four months each with a short period of twelve or more days, and three months each with one or more days that do not correspond to any month of the current year.The term "Italian year" is usually used in general usage to mean a cycle of twelve months, but it can also refer specifically to the time periods between the beginning and end of a specific cycle.

Events  January–March  January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets. The ban is lifted after three months. January 12 – Scottish minister James Renwick, one of the Covenanters resisting the Scottish government's suppression of alternate religious views, publishes the Declaration of Lanark. January 21 – The Ottoman Empire army is mobilized in preparation for a war against Austria that culminates with the 1683 Battle of Vienna. January 24 – The first public theater in Brussels, the Opéra du Quai au Foin, is opened.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is, to distinguish or to inflect words. All verbal languages use pitch to express emotional and other paralinguistic information and to convey emphasis, contrast and other such features in what is called intonation, but not all languages use tones to distinguish words or their inflections, analogously to consonants and vowels. Languages that have this feature are called tonal languages; the distinctive tone patterns of such a language are sometimes called tonemes, by analogy with phoneme.

Year 1515 (MDXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – Francis I of France is crowned (r. until 1547). May 13 – Mary Tudor, Queen of France, and Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk, are officially married at Greenwich (near London). June 13 – Battle of Turnadag: The army of Ottoman sultan Selim I defeats the beylik of Dulkadir under Bozkurt of Dulkadir. July–December  July 2 – Manchester Grammar School is endowed by Hugh Oldham, the first free grammar school in England.

The National Botanic Gardens ( Irish : Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus ) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin , 5 miles north west of the city centre, on the outskirts of Dublin. It is owned by Dermot Gorton, an Irish businessman and member of the Hibernia group, which owns other large botanical gardens in Europe.Dermot Gorton has built a collection of almost 100,000 plants from around the world, mostly species that he found as part of his own research into plant development. John C. Maxwell  (born November 23, 1929) was an American science fiction author who co-created the X-Files, a Fox television series.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of an ordered collection.The set of all rationals has a cardinality (numbers in this set have n elements) of some number, where n equals its smallest integer. Every rational number has exactly two elements: the greatest integer which can be represented by the real numbers is called the positive integer, and the lesser integer which can represent the natural numbers is called the negative integer. The finite integers have non-trivial cardinality less than that of the rational numbers.

Eric Arthur Heiden (born June 14, 1958) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater, road cyclist and track cyclist. He won an unprecedented five individual gold medals, and set four Olympic records and one world record at the 1980 Winter Olympic Games. Heiden was the most successful athlete at those Olympic Games, single-handedly winning more gold medals than all nations except for the Soviet Union (10) and East Germany (9). He is the most successful Winter Olympian from a single edition of any Winter Olympics. He delivered the Athlete's Oath at those same 1980 Games.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state's military forces. The governor has a duty to enforce state laws, the power to either approve or veto bills passed by the Montana State Legislature, to convene the legislature at any time, and to grant pardons and reprieves.The current Montana Constitution, ratified in 1972, calls for a 4-year term for the governor, commencing on the first Monday in January following an election. The governor is term-limited to 8 years in any 16-year period. The constitution provides for the election of a lieutenant governor for the same term as the governor.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml) is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML with object-oriented features. OCaml was created in 1996 by Xavier Leroy, Jérôme Vouillon, Damien Doligez, Didier Rémy, Ascánder Suárez, and others.The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM). OCaml was initially developed in the context of automated theorem proving, and has an outsize presence in static analysis and formal methods software.

Donnybrook  is a district of Dublin, Ireland. It is situated on the southside of the city, in the Dublin 4 postal district, and is home to the Irish public service broadcaster Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ). It was once part of the Pembroke Township. Its neighbouring suburbs are Ballsbridge, Sandymount, Ranelagh and Clonskeagh.Donnybrook is also a civil parish mainly situated in the old barony of Dublin.HistoryDonnybrook Fair dates from a charter of King John of England in 1204 and was held annually until 1855. It began as a fair for livestock and agricultural produce but later declined, growing into more of a carnival and funfair.

The human leg , in the general word sense , is the entire lower limb of the human body , including the knee, hip, foot, fingers and toes. Its primary use as a support during walking has been largely superseded by the use of crutches and wheelchairs, but the leg still plays important roles in locomotion and for sports such as wheelchair basketball and wheelchair football.It is one of the most common joints of the human body, constituting two-thirds to three-quarters of the overall joint surface. In physics, a gravitational field is a collection of physical effects that influence or interact with each other.

John the Apostle ( ; ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the tradition of Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John. His birth is mentioned in Matthew 4:1-9, and he appears in several other passages of the Gospels as a child. Jacobs (Johannes, ; ) was an English chemist, physician, geologist and geophysicist who worked at the Royal Institution of Great Britain (now the Royal Astronomical Society). Born in London in 1587, Jacobs received a B.Sc. degree from the Royal College of Surgeons and an M.A.

Albert III  (9 November 141411 March 1486) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death, the third from the House of Hohenzollern. A member of the Order of the Swan, he received the cognomen Achilles  because of his knightly qualities and virtues. He also ruled in the Franconian principalities of Ansbach from 1440 and Kulmbach from 1464 (as Albrecht I).BiographyEarly lifeAlbert was born at the Brandenburg residence of Tangermünde as the third son of the Nuremberg burgrave Frederick I and his wife, the Wittelsbach princess Elisabeth of Bavaria-Landshut.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.Events890s BC  899 BC: The first year of King Yih of Zhou's reign is marked by a solar eclipse.

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus  of the family Pinaceae. Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. The Plant List compiled by the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and Missouri Botanical Garden accepts 126 species names of pines as current, together with 35 unresolved species and many more synonyms. The American Conifer Society (ACS) and the Royal Horticultural Society accept 121 species. Pine may also refer to the lumber derived from pine trees; pine is one of the more extensively used types of wood used as lumber.

Year 1140 ( MCXL ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of 1 March, 1279 CE. In the Christian tradition, Sunday became the day of Christ's burial and resurrection. The Bible is an ancient collection of books that contains the stories, teachings, and beliefs of the Abrahamic religions. It comprises about 1,400 books in over 60 different versions, including the Old Testament (the Bible) and the New Testament (Christian New Testament or NT). Some of the texts are known to have been composed in different languages, while others originated in different cultures.

Year 1162 (MCLXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 6 – German forces, led by Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), capture Milan; much of the city is destroyed three weeks later, on the emperor's orders. The fortifications are demolished, and the churches are destroyed. The population is dispersed, and the commune abolished. The fate of Milan leads to the submission of Brescia, Piacenza, and many other northern Italian cities.

Donnybrook is a district of Dublin , Ireland . It is situated on the southside of the city , in what was formerly Kildare.The district was first settled by the Irish Free State at the end of the 17th century when its population increased from just under 100,000 to more than 600,000 people in the 19th and 20th centuries. In the early 20th century, it became a predominantly Anglo-Irish area dominated by Protestant families who were largely established in the nearby town of Dunmanway. In astronomy, an asterism is a celestial body that has no star in its constellation but is otherwise identical with another object.

Year 1237 ( MCCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday 19 January 1237 AD.It was also known as the "Baptism of Peter" for this year and was followed by the celebration of the baptismal vows of all members of the Catholic Church following the reformation.The name is an ancient Greek word derived from the Proto-Indo-European roots  or  "birthday". The meaning "apostolic baptisms" is attested from the earliest records in the 1st c. BC, but no dates are known.

As of March 1 ( O.S . February 19 ) , where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the new Gregorian calendar established in the late 18th century. James J. Strickland  (; ; 29 January 1922 – 3 June 2003) was an American lawyer and politician. He served as secretary of health and human services from 1996 to 2001 under former President Bill Clinton, and was a member of the United States House of Representatives from 1993 to 1998. Strickland is widely known for his efforts on behalf of children with HIV/AIDS at the U.S. Children's AIDS Action Network (USCAAN).

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan, a former United States Representative from Nebraska, at the Democratic National Convention in Chicago on July 9, 1896. In the address, Bryan supported bimetallism or "free silver", which he believed would bring the nation prosperity. He decried the gold standard, concluding the speech, "you shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold". Bryan's address helped catapult him to the Democratic Party's presidential nomination; it is considered one of the greatest political speeches in American history.For twenty years, Americans had been bitterly divided over the nation's monetary standard.

Frederick James Prinze ( born Frederick Karl Pruetzel ; June 22 , 1954 – January 29 , 1977 ) was an American actor, known for the role in The Fugitive (1991) of Robert Mitchum. He is widely credited with establishing and characterizing the crime genre in popular entertainment.Prinze also directed several films, including Dead Men Don't Wear Plaid (1987), which won the Academy Award for Best Picture. Francisco Javier Castellanos (; December 20, 1930 – May 11, 2001) was an Argentine politician and former head of President Nestor Kirchner's administration.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and model. After performing as a singer in a folk band for several years, she joined the film industry when she was 19. Her first leading role was as Mrs. Stenzel in The Sound of Music, the film that made her internationally known.Her career spanned over five decades and took her places with such actors as Robert De Niro, Jean Harlow, Christopher Lee, Jack Lemmon, Marjorie Kinnan, John Hurt, George C. Scott, Richard Pryor, Tom Hanks, Sean Connery, and Peter Fonda.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC ( c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka), and was characterized by a rapid increase in agricultural productivity and a decrease in population size resulting in a dramatic drop in the population of most Middle Eastern populations. In computer science, an object oriented programming language is a programming language that computes its data representation as a set of instructions for executing a program written in the language. The use of object-oriented programming languages has long been one of the leading development trends in computer science, and they have become widely accepted within the field of artificial intelligence.

Panettone (, ;  ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia, the United States and Canada.It has a cupola shape, which extends from a cylindrical base and is usually about 12–15 cm high for a panettone weighing 1 kg. Other bases may be used, such as an octagon, or a frustum with a star section shape more common to pandoro. It is made during a long process that involves curing the dough, which is acidic, similar to sourdough.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum . The most serious symptom is vomiting and abdominal cramping, but these are usually mild. Chinaman , also sometimes known as Mohican, was an Indian colonialist of the United States government in the 18th century during the American Revolutionary War. Chinaman's role in the war may have been more significant than first thought, since many of the troops who participated in the struggle for independence had fought with him and his tribe before their departure from the East Indies to settle in New England.

Year 1236 ( MCCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Christian Gregorian calendar.It was used from 1582 until 1791. The year of the leap has varied over time, with the most commonly used year being 1454. In the first half of the eighteenth century it became popular again as an alternative to leap days.The term "Lunar New Year" and the month of July are also called "lunar cycles", while the term "Jubilee Year" is used for those that have not yet reached 30 years.

In art history, literature and cultural studies, Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world. These depictions are usually done by writers, designers, and artists from the Western world. In particular, Orientalist painting, depicting more specifically "the Middle East", was one of the many specialisms of 19th-century academic art, and the literature of Western countries took a similar interest in Oriental themes.Since the publication of Edward Said's Orientalism in 1978, much academic discourse has begun to use the term "Orientalism" to refer to a general patronizing Western attitude towards Middle Eastern, Asian, and North African societies.

Events  January–June  January 1 Colonel George Monck (with his regiment) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration. Samuel Pepys begins his diary. February 3 – George Monck and his regiment arrive in London. February 13 – Charles XI becomes king of Sweden at the age of five, upon the death of his father, Charles X Gustavus. February 27 – John Thurloe is reinstated as England's Secretary of State, having been deprived of his offices late in the previous year. March 16 – The Long Parliament disbands.

Year 1024 (MXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Basil II prepares a Byzantine expedition to invade Sicily. Governor Ahmed al-Akhal appeals to the Zirids of Ifriqiya for help. They dispatch a fleet, but these are caught up in a storm and destroyed near Pantelleria. Battle of Lemnos:  Kievan Viking raiders (800 men) sail through the straits at Abydos to the Aegean Sea. From there they make for the island of Lemnos, but are defeated by a Byzantine fleet of the Cibyrrhaeot Theme.

In probability theory , the central limit theorem ( CLT ) establishes that , in many situations , when independent random variables do not depend on each other. The CLT can be derived by extending the classical version of Bernoulli numbers to countably many parameters. The Collodion method is a computer graphics technique developed at Bell Labs, which uses light to simulate the interaction of light with matter. The technique was widely used in the early 1970s and has been adopted by other companies and universities around the world including Apple Inc., Microsoft Corporation, Philips Electronics, Digital Research, Epson Imaging, and Fujitsu Industrial Systems.

Tequila is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant , primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequilintla. It is said to have originated in the ancient Chichimeca civilization and was later popularized during the 16th and 17th centuries as a drink by Native Americans. Today, tequila has become one of Mexico's most highly recognized products, with its use being widespread throughout the country. It is widely sold at all Mexican restaurants, grocery stores and convenience stores across the country. Terminus  is an American horror anthology film written and directed by David Robert Mitchell and Steven Spielberg.

Year 1207 ( MCCVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( full calendar ) under the Julian calendar.Events In this year Henry I of England was crowned king of England for the eleventh time, ending the reign of Elizabeth I who had ruled Britain for almost six years until her death in 1483. The coronation took place at Westminster Abbey, where Henry's father was also buried. On 15 May, Henry married his half-brother Edmund Tudor, daughter of John of Gaunt, Duke of Norfolk and Catherine de'Medici, Countess of Brittany.

Year 1038 ( MXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic Latin calendar. There are two reasons for this: One, it is the first day of the New Year which occurs on the 1st January, and the other is the year's leap-year date. The Big Dipper  or "Triangle of the North" is the third most prominent astronomical object in the sky after the Earth and the Sun and the Milky Way Galaxy. It is a large oval-shaped spiral galaxy situated in the constellation Leo.

Year 1207 (MCCVII) was a common year starting on Monday (full calendar) under the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Siege of Attalia: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I besiege the city port of Attalia (modern-day Antalya) with siege machines. After a siege of more than 2 months, the city is captured, Kaykhusraw allows his forces 3-day looting and slaughtering. The capture of the port gives the Seljuk Turks a major path into the Mediterranean. September 4 – Battle of Messinopolis: Latin forces under Boniface of Montferrat are ambushed and defeated at Messinopolis.

Events  March 18 – Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake in Paris, France. April 4 – Exeter College, Oxford is founded in England by Walter de Stapledon, Bishop of Exeter. June 24 – Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish forces led by Robert the Bruce defeat Edward II of England, regaining Scotland's independence. August 31 – King Haakon V of Norway moves his capital from Bergen to Oslo, where he builds Akershus Fortress, from which Norway is ruled for the next 500 years.

Casimir IV ( in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon ; ; Lithuanian : ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1496), known as Casimir I, was King of Poland from 1462 until his accession to the Polish throne. He ascended to the Polish throne on 31 December 1472, becoming the first monarch to take the title of "Kraków", which meant "King of Poland". The Common Era is the era that preceded and followed the Roman civil wars. It is often contrasted with the Age of Heroes, a later period during which most major military conflicts between Rome and other peoples had occurred.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Panettone ( , ; ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan , usually prepared and enjoyed as a warm breakfast or snack.HistoryIn the late 19th to early 20th centuries, Bolognese was the most common place of residence for Italians in the U.K.
Chilean red pepper ( Chilo peppers ) is a member of the bell pepper family. It is native to North America and widely cultivated throughout Central and South America, including Chile, Ecuador, Paraguay, Peru, Bolivia, Argentina, Uruguay, Costa Rica, Jamaica, Cuba, Panama, Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Haiti, Nicaragua, Honduras, and Mexico.

Year 1317 ( MCCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian Calendar. The years 1318, 1410, 1431, 1457, 1525, 1532, 1563, 1643, 1650, 1677, and 1705 all began on Saturday. Calendula (; , ; also known as caldia) or Calendula ("calendar stone", from calendrum "calendar") is the name given to the Latin alphabet consisting of 24 diacritics used by Christians for the numbering of day-names. Calendula is derived from an ancient Hebrew word  that means "calendar" or "month".

Events January–June February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary , Queen of Scots. The execution order is dated 12 December 1546 and states that she is guilty of treason, murder, and other "high crimes and misdemeanours" and should die by her own hand.1 February – James I of Scotland becomes Earl of Orkney when his younger brother Henry succeeds him as King of Scotland.3 – The Treaty of Westphalia establishes the German Confederation (Königsteinerland) which includes the kingdom of Denmark, the duchy of Friesland, the cantons of Saxony and Thuringia, and the city of Wittenberg.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children 's game in which at least two players ( usually at least three ) conceal a single object. It has been played since before written history, but the earliest recorded play dates from 1882 in Germany by Johann Wolfgang Künstler . The term "game" is used here to include board games such as bridge, checkers, and kite-flying, along with many other games. In mathematics, an infinite set is one whose elements are no more than , where is cardinality of the set. In other words, there is no set in which cannot be made larger or smaller.

Howard Kingsbury Smith (May 12, 1914 – February 15, 2002) was an American journalist, radio reporter, television anchorman, political commentator, and film actor. He was one of the original members of the team of war correspondents known as the Murrow Boys.Early life and educationEarly career and CBS yearsWorld War IIUpon graduating, Smith worked for the New Orleans Item, with United Press in London, and with The New York Times. In January 1940, Smith was sent to Berlin, where he joined the Columbia Broadcasting System under Edward R. Murrow.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms. Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes (EPEC, ETEC etc.) can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls. The harmless strains are part of the normal microbiota of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K2, and preventing colonisation of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a mutualistic relationship.

Year 1556 (MDLVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 16 – Charles V, having already abdicated as Holy Roman Emperor, resigns the Kingdom of Spain in favour of his son, Philip II, and retires to a monastery. January 23 –  The Shaanxi earthquake, the deadliest earthquake in history, occurs with its epicenter in Shaanxi province, China; 830,000 people may have been killed. February 5 – Truce of Vaucelles: Fighting temporarily ends between France and Spain.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice . In most cases, they involve riding, running, swimming, skiing and ice skating.They are usually organized on a team basis with some level of competition. They are sometimes held in competitions such as the World Snowshoeing Championships.Winter sports may also include other activities such as ice skating, archery, rowing, rock climbing, skiing, snowmobiling, sled hockey and snowboarding.The International Olympic Committee (IOC) requires that all sports be included on the Games program to ensure a high level of participation by the majority of participants.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov (;  – 10 March 1940) was a Russian writer, medical doctor, and playwright active in the first half of the 20th century. He is best known for his novel The Master and Margarita, published posthumously, which has been called one of the masterpieces of the 20th century.He is also known for his novel The White Guard (also called Belaya gvardiya) , his plays Ivan Vasilievich, Flight (also called The Run) , The Days of the Turbins , and other works of the 1920s and 1930s.

Digital electronics is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use them for electronic functions. The field has become increasingly technical in recent years, with significant interest from both hobbyist and large-scale industrial uses.The field is associated with a wide range of research areas, with applications in communications, computer architecture, cryptography, digital signal processing, artificial intelligence, sensors, and many other fields.Electronic systems typically consist of semiconductor elements connected together as transistors or resistors. These elements can be arranged in a variety of ways to form functional circuits.

1499 (MCDXCIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany, in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII. May 19 – 13-year-old Catherine of Aragon, the future first wife of Henry VIII of England, is married by proxy to his brother, 12-year-old Arthur, Prince of Wales. July 22 – Battle of Dornach: The Swiss decisively defeat the army of Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor.

In cosmology , the cosmological constant ( usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda : Λ ) , alternatively known as the Lambda constant, is a non-constant constant in many physical and mathematical contexts. It was formulated by the British scientist Sir Arthur Eddington in the early 1800s to provide a way to calculate how large an astronomical object should be for the light from its surroundings to have had time to travel back through space to Earth.The value of the constant is given as a function of distance from the observer. Coffee has long been recognised as a drink that may promote weight loss and helps prevent cardiovascular disease (CVD).

Year 1342 (MCCCXLII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January 21–June 27 – An-Nasir Ahmad, Sultan of Egypt, rules prior to being deposed by his half-brother As-Salih Ismail. May 7 – Pope Clement VI succeeds Pope Benedict XII, as the 198th Pope. July 16 – Louis I becomes king of Hungary. July 18 – Battle of Zava: Mu'izz al-Din Husayn defeats the Sarbadars. July 22 – St. Mary Magdalene's flood is the worst such event on record for central Europe.

Year 1343 (MCCCXLIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 14 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last bishop of Prague and, subsequently, the first Archbishop of Prague. January 27 – Pope Clement VI issues his bull Unigenitus, defining the doctrine of "The Treasury of Merits" or "The Treasury of the Church" as the basis for the issuance of indulgences by the Catholic Church. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising begins in Estonia.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain (including the Isle of Wight, and parts of East Anglia). The Romans brought to Britain their distinctive culture and customs, including literacy in Latin, Greek, and Aramaic. However, they did not establish any significant administrative or religious authority over the inhabitants of Britain until the early first century AD. The Church of England is the Anglican Communion. Its membership is made up of the Anglican churches of England, Canada, Scotland, Ireland, Australia and New Zealand.

Events  January–June  January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan, known as the Ratio Studiorum, is issued. March 12 – Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex, is appointed Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, by Queen Elizabeth I of England. April 23 – The Earl of Essex arrives in Dublin at the head of 16,000 troops, the largest army ever seen in Ireland. May 16 – The Kalmar Bloodbath takes place in Kalmar, Sweden. May 29 – Essex takes Cahir Castle, supposedly the strongest in Ireland, after a short siege. June 20 – The Synod of Diamper is convened.

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an annual plant native to dry regions. The seeds of the plant are edible, but they have a bitter aftertaste. The French term  is derived from the Latin word *corax (carrion), which refers to the rotting body of animals, mostly birds, that have been caught, eaten, or used in traditional medicine. In France it has become a part of the local   vocabulary. In Greek mythology, Okeanos (in Greek: Ækeoi) was the god of the sea, son of Zeus and Aphrodite.

Events January–June January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas : The Portuguese beat the French under the leadership of Napoleon Bonaparte at the Battle of the Lines of Elvas (14 April–13 August 1798), which was fought to secure independence for Portugal and prevent French expansion south into the Spanish colonies. The Council of Nicaea (Latin: Council of Nicaea) was a council of the Church of Nicaea, or the "Council of the East". Its primary function was to determine the position of the Orthodox Christian Churches, particularly the Church of Rome, regarding questions of church doctrine and administration.

Andrew Stuart "Andy" Fastow (born December 22, 1961) is a convicted felon and former financier who was the chief financial officer of Enron Corporation, an energy trading company based in Houston, Texas, until he was fired shortly before the company declared bankruptcy. Fastow was one of the key figures behind the complex web of off-balance-sheet special purpose entities (limited partnerships which Enron controlled) used to conceal Enron's massive losses in their quarterly balance sheets. By unlawfully maintaining personal stakes in these ostensibly independent ghost-entities, he was able to defraud Enron out of tens of millions of dollars.

Acetic acid bacteria ( AAB ) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid, acetone, acetate, and propionate through oxidation reactions. Their primary use is as preservatives in foods, and they have also been used in many industrial processes. AABs can be grown in the laboratory by using a standard fermentation medium, but they do not thrive outside of such conditions. Amaryllis  is an evergreen conifer commonly found in the Western United States. It differs from other conifers in that it grows very tall, reaching above 20 feet on dry land and more than 40 feet at high altitudes.

"Coven"  usually refers to a group or gathering of witches. The word "coven" (from Anglo-Norman covent, cuvent, from Old French covent, from Latin conventum = convention) remained largely unused in English until 1921 when Margaret Murray promoted the idea that all witches across Europe met in groups of thirteen which they called "covens".NeopaganismIn Wicca and other similar forms of neopagan witchcraft, such as Stregheria and Feri, a coven is a gathering or community of witches, like an affinity group, engagement group, or small covenant group.

Otto III ( June/July 980 – 23 January 1002 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death. He is credited with the construction of the Gothic cathedrals, as well as the founding of the city of Aquileia and the Latin-speaking Empire of the West. He is considered by many historians as the first European ruler who laid the foundations of the state in the East. He was instrumental in establishing the Carolingian Order of the Knights Templar, a religious order established by Charlemagne, which became an important source of manpower for the Franks throughout the Middle Ages, especially during the conquest of Burgundy and England.

The term chat room, or chatroom (and sometimes group chat; abbreviated as GC), is primarily used to describe any form of synchronous conferencing, occasionally even asynchronous conferencing. The term can thus mean any technology ranging from real-time online chat and online interaction with strangers (e.g., online forums) to fully immersive graphical social environments.The primary use of a chat room is to share information via text with a group of other users. Generally speaking, the ability to converse with multiple people in the same conversation differentiates chat rooms from instant messaging programs, which are more typically designed for one-to-one communication.

Year 1489 (MCDLXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 14 – The Queen of Cyprus, Catherine Cornaro, sells her kingdom to the Republic of Venice. March 26 – The Treaty of Medina del Campo between England and Spain includes provision for a marriage between Arthur, the son of King Henry VII of England, and Princess Catherine of Aragon.June 29 – King James IV grants Andrew, Lord Gray, the lands and Barony of Lundie in Scotland. July 17 – Delhi Sultanate: Sikandar Lodi succeeds Bahlul Khan Lodi as sultan.

Year 1570 (MDLXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 8 – Ivan the Terrible begins the Massacre of Novgorod. January 23 – The assassination of Scottish regent James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, by James Hamilton (the first recorded assassination using a firearm in Europe), throws Scotland into civil war. February 8 – A magnitude 8.3 earthquake occurs in Concepción, Chile. February 15 – Venus occults Jupiter; this will next happen in 1818.

Stephen Arthur Cook,  (born December 14, 1939) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made major contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof complexity. He is a university professor at the University of Toronto, Department of Computer Science and Department of Mathematics.BiographyCook received his bachelor's degree in 1961 from the University of Michigan, and his master's degree and Ph.D. from Harvard University, respectively in 1962 and 1966, from the Mathematics Department. He joined the University of California, Berkeley, mathematics department in 1966 as an assistant professor, and stayed there until 1970 when he was denied reappointment.

Year 1217 ( MCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar of the Gregorian and Anglican systems of civil administration. It is considered to have been introduced by Henry IV, King of England on the occasion of his marriage to Katherine of Bohemia. The precise date of the birth of Anne Boleyn is not precisely known. A binary tree is a symmetric binary tree, which is equivalent to the graph of a bijection. Bifurcations occur at nodes of the tree with respect to other trees.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description , understanding and prediction of natural phenomena. The term "scientific study" is now used more widely than at any time in modern history to refer both to scientific fields, such as physics or biology, and to areas of inquiry which do not fall within this broad definition. The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) is a trade union for chemists who belong to IUPAC. It was formally established in 1919 and its first general congress took place in 1911.

Year 1395 (MCCCXCV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1395th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 395th year of the 2nd millennium, the 95th year of the 14th century, and the 6th year of the 1390s decade.Events  January–December  February 12 – The army led by Sigismund of Luxembourg is ambushed by Stephen I of Moldavia, on its way back after conquering Neamț Citadel, and the Hungarians must retreat empty handed.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married , especially in some Christian cultures. It was used in the Christian Church as a sign of faithfulness to the Church. The first known evidence of engagement rings appears in early medieval literature, when the Greek poet Pindar wrote that he had "an engagement ring upon my finger", but it would not be until well into the 18th century that English writers introduced the practice into their novels.Engagement rings are also commonly found on modern wedding rings.

Niihau ( Hawaiian : ) , anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in the state of Hawaii, situated in the middle of the Waianae-Waiʻāina  archipelago in the north-central part of the state. It lies on the west side of Hawaiʻi Harbor, south of Molokaʻi, and northeast of Iolani Air Force Base. The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) is an executive agency within the federal government responsible for managing the nation's food supply, including the prevention and mitigation of foodborne diseases and the conservation of farm and fisheries resources.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

Year 1131 ( MCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday. This year was the last one of the Roman calendar, which was adopted by Pope Gregory VI in 1087 and replaced the Julian calendar. The United Kingdom is a member of the European Union (EU), a political union consisting of 28 countries. It is a member of the Council of Europe and the Council of the European Union, as well as having an observer status at the G7 and G20.

Year 1412 (MCDXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) on the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 16 – The Medici Family are  made official bankers of the Papacy. January 25 – Ernest, Duke of Austria, marries Cymburgis of Masovia. July 24 – Behnam Hadloyo becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Mardin. October 5 – Emperor Go-Komatsu abdicates, and Emperor Shoko accedes to the throne of Japan. October 28 – Eric of Pomerania becomes sole ruler of the Kalmar Union (Sweden, Denmark and Norway), upon the death of Queen Margaret.

Mary Virginia Martin (December 1, 1913 – November 3, 1990) was an American actress and singer. A muse of Rodgers and Hammerstein, she originated many leading roles on stage over her career, including Nellie Forbush in South Pacific (1949), the title character in Peter Pan (1954), and Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959). She was named a Kennedy Center Honoree in 1989. She was the mother of actor Larry Hagman.Early life Martin was born in Weatherford, Texas. Her autobiography described her childhood as secure and happy.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a rigid body capable of rotating on a point on itself. On the basis of the locations of fulcrum, load and effort, the lever is divided into three types. Also, leverage is mechanical advantage gained in a system. It is one of the six simple machines identified by Renaissance scientists. A lever amplifies an input force to provide a greater output force, which is said to provide leverage.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts , in the state of New Jersey . It is the northernmost portion of the Cape Cod region, north of Cape Cod Bay , and south of South Sandwich  Island. Its coastline is primarily on Cape Cod Bay. Carolina ( ;  , or , ; c. 9 January 1602 – 30 June 1715), also known as  Carolina Devil  or  Carolina Moth , was the first person to be declared the Duke of York by the House of Lancaster. He was a cousin of the future King James I.

Year 1046 (MXLVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Autumn – King Henry III (the Black) travels to Italy to secure the imposition of Guido da Velate, archbishop of Milan, and other similarly loyal candidates in other sees (like Ravenna, Verona and Modena). Vatha Pagan Revolt: King Peter Orseolo (the Venetian) is overthrown after a 2-year reign. Bishops Gerard of Csanád and Bystrík (or Bestricus) are stoned to death in Budapest (Hungary).

Poltava ( , ; ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine . It is the capital of the Dnepropetrovsk oblast and the administrative center of the Donetsk region. Its name, which literally translates to "stone town", refers to its status as the only historical stone-built settlement in eastern Ukraine, built in the Neolithic era. Poltava was founded by Slavic tribes known as Volga Germans at about 2600 B.C. The People's Republic of China (official: 南方经译中国人台; : ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ) is a country in the world and the fifth largest country in the world.

Year 1456 (MCDLVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 18 – Second Battle of Oronichea (1456): Ottoman Forces of 15,000 are sent to capture Albania, but are met and swiftly defeated by Skanderbeg's smaller forces. June 9  – Halley's Comet makes an appearance, as noted by the humanist scholar Platina. July 7 – A retrial of Joan of Arc acquits her of heresy, 25 years after her execution. July 22 – Battle of Nándorfehérvár (Belgrade): The Hungarians under John Hunyadi rout the Turkish army of Sultan Mehmed II.

Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will display the current year) in every year of the Gregorian calendar. It marked the first appearance of the new Gregorian calendar, the basis for many modern calendars today. It was the first leap year to be added to the calendar during the 15th century. Although it was used from 1582 onward, it did not become part of the Roman calendar until 1792. Git is a version control system developed by the Git project.

Year 1302 (MCCCII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 10 – The first meeting of the Estates General of the Kingdom of France is convened by Philip IV of France, at the Notre-Dame in Paris.May 18 – Bruges Matins: The French garrison in Bruges is massacred at night, by members of the local Flemish militia. June 12 – Rakvere, Estonia, receives Lübeck city rights. July 11 – Battle of the Golden Spurs (also called the Battle of Courtrai): the County of Flanders gains a major victory over the Kingdom of France.

Year 1510 (MDX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Catherine of Aragon gives birth to her first child, a stillborn daughter. January 23 – An 18-year-old Henry VIII of England jousts anonymously at Richmond, Surrey and draws applause, before revealing his identity. February 27–November 25 – Portuguese conquest of Goa: Afonso de Albuquerque of Portugal conquers Goa. March 1 – Battle of Salt River: Indigenous ǃUriǁʼaekua decisively defeat sailors of the Portuguese Empire in South Africa.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. LASP is a research institute with over one hundred research scientists ranging in fields from solar influences, to Earth's and other planetary atmospherics processes, space weather, space plasma and dusty plasma physics. LASP has advanced technical capabilities specializing in designing, building, and operating spacecraft and spacecraft instruments.HistoryFounded after World War II, the first scientific instruments built at LASP were launched into space using captured German V-2 rockets. To this day LASP continues a suborbital rocket program through periodic calibration instrument flights from White Sands Missile Range.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire, sometimes reaching extravagant proportions.Typology and distributionPliny the Elder (23–79 AD) distinguished two kinds of villas near Rome: the villa urbana, a country seat that could easily be reached from Rome (or another city) for a night or two; and the villa rustica, the farmhouse estate permanently occupied by the servants who generally had charge of the estate. The Roman Empire contained many kinds of villas, not all of them lavishly appointed with mosaic floors and frescoes.

Year 1027 (MXXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 26 – Pope John XIX crowns Conrad II ("the Elder") and his wife Gisela of Swabia as Holy Roman Emperor and Empress, respectively, in Old St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Cnut the Great, King of Denmark and England, attends the coronation, proving his position as sole ruler of the Danish North Sea Empire. May 14 – King Robert II of France ("the Pious") sues for peace with his sons.

Year 1047 ( MXLVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of Year 1047 in the Gregorian calendar. This year was the fourth year of the reign of King Alfonso II of Spain, but not the fifth.It was the twelfth year of Queen Isabella, and the fifteenth since her father Philip II of Spain had succeeded to the throne following the death of his uncle, Edward I.
Aardvark  is a genus of the family Arctiidae. The name derives from Old Norse Äarðvær , meaning "aardwolf".

Year 1270 (MCCLXX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1270th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 270th year of the 2nd millennium, the 70th year of the 13th century, and the 1st year of the 1270s decade.Events  Africa  The Eighth Crusade Before August – King Louis IX of France launches the Eighth Crusade, in an attempt to recapture the Crusader States from the Mamluk sultan Baibars; the opening engagement is a siege of Tunis.

.Year 1134 (MCXXXIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place Asia  Count Hugh II (du Puiset), in alliance with the Egyptian city of Ashkelon, revolts against King Fulk V of Jerusalem, attempting to take Jaffa. Hugh submits to Fulk and is exiled for three years. While awaiting for a boat to Italy he is attacked by a Breton knight, but survives the attempted murder. Hugh retires to the Sicilian court of his cousin, King Roger II, who appoints him with the lordship of Gargano, where he dies soon afterwards.

Frederick II of Brandenburg ( 19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471 ) , nicknamed `` the Iron '' (from the Latin  ironia ), was the last king of the House of Brandenburg, an independent Kingdom of Germany and Prussia ruled by Frederick William III. His father, Frederick William III of Hesse-Hanover, succeeded his father as Regent in 1401 but did not live to see him abdicate in favor of his eldest son, Frederic III.In 1405 Frederick William resigned from his post as Regent and became Regent of Bavaria for the remainder of his reign.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC .
