The Late Bronze Age collapse in the Western Mediterranean, which began with the arrival of Phoenician traders in Spain and Italy, is generally seen as a major factor in the demise of the ancient Greek and Latin civilizations. The Book of Job ( ;  ἐδουσια τῶν ἡμᾶς) is one of the five Old Testament books of the Bible, the other four being the Song of Songs ( , , , ), Hosea ( , ), Zechariah ( ) and Ezekiel ( ).

Events  January–March  January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company, of the German state of Brandenburg, signs a greaty with representatives of the Ahanta tribe in what is now Ghana to establish the fort and settlement of Groß Friedrichsburg in honor of Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The location is later renamed Princes Town, also called Pokesu. January 6 – The tragic opera Phaëton, written by Jean-Baptiste Lully and Philippe Quinault, is premiered at the Palace of Versailles. January 27 – Gove's Rebellion breaks out in the Province of New Hampshire in North America as a revolt against the Royal Governor, Edward Cranfield.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch ( 15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908 ) was a German humorist , poet , playwright, composer, and essayist. Busch studied under Friedrich Döbenhauer and J.F.H. Bach and in 1872 wrote the first of his two comedy plays, Tannenbaum im Rheingoldt, where he portrayed a Jewish family in Germany.Busch's best-known play is Gedichte des Künstlerinnen und der Schule, which was first staged in Munich in 1884. In mathematics, the group  is the sum of all positive integers that belong to some finite subgroup  of an algebra . The term "group" means "group of integers".

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Church of Saint John in the 18th century, during a period known as the Reformation. Their primary focus was spiritual development, and their teachings were influenced by St. Augustine and St. Gregory Palamas.HistoryThe Khlyst's origins can be traced to the early 20th-century French Catholic priest Father Paul Kuyper.In the years after World War II, his writings helped form the foundation for the Khlyst movement. It became a significant presence in many communities in the U.S. during the 1970s and '80s.

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor at the University of Michigan. He was awarded the 1973 Pulitzer Prize in history. James Joyce (January 18, 1918 – December 21, 1996) was a British novelist. His novels were widely rejected by literary critics and are still not regularly read. Joyce is best known for the short stories "Ulysses", "Finnegans Wake" and "The Dream of Dr. Muir", which have all been made into operas and films.

Year 1578 ( MDLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday ( link is in German). The Gregorian calendar, also known as the Roman or Western Calendar, is used in much of the world. It is the same calendar used for most of the centuries since its first use in AD 1492.HistoryDuring the middle ages and the Renaissance, the Julian calendar was used as an alternate system for the Gregorian calendar. In computer science, a hash function  is a cryptographic hash function designed to be difficult to break by means other than mathematical analysis.

Albert III ( 9 November 141411 March 1486 ) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death , the eldest son of Henry II, King of the Romans. He was born in Brandenburg where he married Catherine of Saxony, daughter of Ludwig IV's second-in-line succession. After his father's abdication in 1465, the Duke of Brandenburg became Holy Roman Emperor, an office which he retained for nearly two centuries before being elected emperor at the age of twenty-two. Carl Friedrich Carl von Schmoller (; 10 January 1183 – 6 May 1184) was a German scholar and jurist.

Year 1516 (MDXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Juan Díaz de Solís discovers the Río de la Plata (in future Argentina). January 23 – With the death of Ferdinand II of Aragon, his grandson, Charles of Ghent, becomes King of Spain; his mother Queen Joanna of Castile also succeeds as Queen of Aragon and co-monarch with Carlos, but remains confined at Tordesillas. March 1 – Desiderius Erasmus publishes a new Greek edition of the New Testament, Novum Instrumentum omne, in Basel.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson (February 13, 1942 – February 21, 2019), known professionally as Peter Tork, was an American musician, composer, and actor who was best known as the keyboardist and bass guitarist of the Monkees and a co-star of the TV series The Monkees (1966–1968).Tork grew up in Connecticut and in the mid-1960s as part of the Greenwich Village folk scene in New York City, he befriended musician Stephen Stills. After moving to Los Angeles with Stills, he was recruited for the musical television sitcom The Monkees. The success of the show made him a teen idol from 1966 to 1968.

Year 1558 (MDLVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1558th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 558th year of the 2nd millennium, the 58th year of the 16th century, and the 9th year of the 1550s decade.Events  January–June  January 7 – French troops, led by Francis, Duke of Guise, take Calais, the last continental possession of the Kingdom of England. January 9 – Geneva becomes independent from the Canton of Bern.

Year 1020 ( MXX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) on November 1, 2022 and ending on Sunday, December 31, 2023. It is considered to be the most significant astronomical event of the year due to the Earth's orbit around the Sun following the passage of the planet Mercury in the evening hours from January 1st to Saturday, 22nd January 2026. An alphanumeric code (or an alphanumeric code word)  is a series of characters that form a particular sequence of digits, letters, or symbols.

In art history , literature and cultural studies , Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern and Near Eastern cultures. It has been described as "a political, intellectual and aesthetic phenomenon" and is often employed by Western writers and critics to critique historical and cultural representations of East Asian peoples and societies.It was coined by Russian linguist Vladimir Vernadsky, although this term was first defined in the mid-19 th century by German philosophers Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel (1843–1910) and Joseph Schleiermacher (1864–1952), both of whom also saw it as an important theme in the study of human society.

Year 1482 (MCDLXXXII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – A Portuguese fleet, commanded by Diogo de Azambuja, arrives at the mouth of the River Benya on the Gold Coast, where the fort of São Jorge da Mina (Elmina Castle) is erected. January 25 – Probable first printing of the Torah, in Bologna. February 28 –The village of Alhama de Granada in Spain is taken by Christian forces, starting the Granada War to expel the Moors from the Iberian Peninsula back to Africa.

Year 1051 (MLI) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – William of Normandy consolidates his power in Normandy. He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). May 19 – King Henry I of France marries Anne of Kiev at the cathedral of Reims. William of Normandy marries Matilda of Flanders, daughter of Count Baldwin V, which Henry sees as a threat to his throne.

Year 1575 (MDLXXV)  was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – Queen Elizabeth I of England grants a monopoly on producing printed sheet music, to Thomas Tallis and William Byrd. February 8 – William I of Orange founds Leiden University. February 13 – Henry III of France is crowned at Reims. February 14 – Henry III of France marries Louise de Lorraine-Vaudémont. March 3 – Battle of Tukaroi: The Mughal Empire decisively defeat the Karrani dynasty of Bengal. June 24 – William I of Orange marries Charlotte of Bourbon.

Louis I, also Louis the Great (; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian (; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 and King of Poland from 1370. He was the first child of Charles I of Hungary and his wife, Elizabeth of Poland, to survive infancy. A 1338 treaty between his father and Casimir III of Poland, Louis's maternal uncle, confirmed Louis's right to inherit the Kingdom of Poland if his uncle died without a son. In exchange, Louis was obliged to assist his uncle to reoccupy the lands that Poland had lost in previous decades.

Charles XIV John ( ; born Jean Bernadotte ; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844 ) was King of France from 1824 until his death in 1852. He was the last king of the French Bourbon dynasty and the third ruler of France from 1792 until his death. Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (; 30 October 1759 – 7 May 1796) was a German Romantic poet, novelist, critic, essayist, dramatist, playwright, painter, and essayist who is known as "the greatest living Englishman" by the British public and "the greatest Englishman of the twentieth century" by the American one.

Year 1579 (MDLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Monday of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 6  – The Union of Arras unites the southern Netherlands under the Duke of Parma, governor in the name of king Philip II of Spain. January 23 –  The Union of Utrecht unites the northern Netherlands in a confederation called the United Provinces. William I of Orange becomes Stadtholder, and the Duc d'Anjou, younger brother of Henry III of France, is invited to become hereditary sovereign.

Year 1037 ( MXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar and is the first two digits of the Julian day counting system, which was introduced by Benedictine monks around 1482.The year 1337 began with the death of King Henry V of England. In computing, a leap second is a time difference that occurs at a regular interval during the duration of a computer's cycle. An interval is measured from 00:00:00 UTC on January 1, 1970, through 00:00:59 UTC on December 31, 2071.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men 's singles , ladies ' singles , and mixed events. In addition, there are women 's doubles and mixed team events where skaters compete in a similar way to men's single and mixed events.Skating is performed with a skate blade (in both men 's and women 's events), which is either fixed or hand-held, and propelled by a forward momentum that varies depending on height and direction. In cryptography, a public key or public key exchange protocol (PKI) is a procedure for the exchange of secret information over the Internet.

Year 1444 (MCDXLIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1444.Events  January–December  March 2 – The League of Lezhë, an alliance of Albanian principalities, is established in Lezhë; George Kastrioti Skanderbeg is proclaimed commander of the Albanian resistance.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed point to move an object relative to another object. Levine, Joseph L.  (July 13, 1873 – February 24, 1954) was an American poet, short story writer and essayist best known as the author of "Little Women" (1946), "The House on Milius Lane" (1949), and other essays. He received his Ph.D. in poetry from Yale University in 1944.Levine wrote his first novel, "Sophisticated Ladies", in 1937 and published it simultaneously with "Little Women" in 1941.

Provincetown  is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, in the United States. A small coastal resort town with a year-round population of 3,664 as of the 2020 United States Census, Provincetown has a summer population as high as 60,000. Often called "P-town" or "P'town", the locale is known for its beaches, harbor, artists, tourist industry, and as a popular vacation destination for the LGBT+ community.History At the time of European encounter, the area was long settled by the historic Nauset tribe, who had a settlement known as "Meeshawn".

The Battle of Trafalgar ( 21 October 1805 ) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the French naval force of the Armée de la Nuit at Trafalgar. It was one of the largest naval battle in history, lasting more than three months, with 5,000 ships and 2,300 ships' worth of combatants involved. It was the only decisive action of the War of 1803. The capital of Luxembourg is La Chaux-de-Fonds. The population density is about 14.3 persons per sq. km, which is lower than the United Kingdom's rate of 8.2 persons per square kilometre.

Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to visit the planet. It launched on July 31, 1965 and landed on the planet's surface on November 21, 1966. The mission was one of the first human missions to the moon, the first to land on another celestial body other than Earth, the first in which humans lived for more than six months without air support and the first to explore both the interior and exterior of Venus. A year later, Voyager 1 reached Jupiter.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy , authority or control within the Internet. It may refer to an IP address, an IP phone number, a domain name, or a subdomain . Domain names are commonly assigned through a DNS service such as . Deutsche Bank (Deutsche Bank AG) is a global financial services company headquartered in Frankfurt, Germany. Founded and headquartered in 1897, it is one of the world's oldest and largest banks, having established branches across the world since its founding.

Year 1538 ( MDXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday 18 March 1601. It is one of four common-year dates in the Gregorian calendar that have an astronomical value greater than 365 days.In ancient Roman mythology, Aesculapius was an emperor who reigned from AD 761–79, when he was assassinated. He was known as the "Prince of Darkness", and was considered the patron saint of witches. Amphibious craft were large sailing vessels with a displacement greater than 20 tonnes. Their design had to be water-tight to prevent them from tipping over when loaded with cargo.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese ( born 17 April 1954 ) is an Italian former racing driver , who raced in Formula 1 from 1997 to 2007. He began his career in Italy's Indy 500 series, and was considered the best of the great Italian drivers. James Bisset  (18 June 1911 – 16 December 1972) was an American lawyer, civil rights activist, and founder of the Nation of Islam. Bisset was born in Chicago to a French immigrant family, and later worked as a legal assistant in Illinois before moving west with his parents to San Francisco in 1939, where he grew up and attended Columbia University Law School.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy . Slapstick can take many forms, from a slapstick joke to dramatic scenes. Although the exact origins and definition of slapstick are disputed, there is agreement that it is a humorous form of expression with an element of exaggeration.HistoryIn its earliest use during the 19th century, slapstick was a play on the word "slapstick". The earliest known usage dates from 1885, in a book by Joseph Broussard, who popularized slapstick in the United States.

Year 1501 ( MDI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday of the following month. In the United Kingdom it was used from the 13th to the 20th centuries. A bird is any animal that roosts in trees, typically foraging for food or for protection. Birds are classified as either avian (including ducks, geese, geese, swans, chickens, pigeons, ostriches, and quail) or frugivorous, with frugivorous birds usually being more flightless than their other relatives.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom , British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling, shillings, pence, guineas and pennies. British Columbia (BC) is a province in Canada, with a population of 3.65 million people, that is on the Canadian mainland and located at the southernmost part of the Rocky Mountains region. It lies between the Interior and Interior North American tectonic plates. Province-wide, it covers land from Northern British Columbia eastwards along the Coast Mountains up to the Great Bear Rainforest north of the town of Nanaimo, BC.

Year 1149 (MCXLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) recovers Corfu with the help of the Venetians, who defeat the Sicilian fleet. During the three-month siege, Byzantine admiral Stephen Kontostephanos  is killed by a stone thrown by a catapult. Manuel prepares an offensive against the Normans, King Roger II sends a fleet (some 40 ships) under George of Antioch to pilliage the suburbs of Constantinople.

Year 1162 ( MCLXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of Roman Era.The Julian calendar was devised in 851 by Ptolemy II and continued for the next 200 years. Charles I (1607 – 1649) was the English king who, at the age of 27, was crowned King Regnant of England in 1603. The events of that year saw Charles's brother, the Duke of Somerset, deposed from the Royal household and executed. His son Edward, then only twenty-nine, succeeded his uncle as regent, becoming regent during the remainder of the 1603–06 reign.

Year 1507 ( MDVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday, July 4 at midnight. Al-Khwarizmi ( ,   ; 1207 – 1277) was the ruler of Egypt during the reign of Akhenaten . He conquered the province of Thebes but was deposed by the successor of Akhenaten in 1206 AD after the death of his father, Tuthmose II. Al-Khwarizmi reigned for five years before being deposed. Amir al-Din Muhammad Ibn Abi Talib al-Hakim (; 1187–1241) was one of the earliest Islamic scholars, known as "the first school of Sunni Islamic thought".

CBE may refer to : Travel CBE , IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport . CBE , ICAO code for Central Air Transport Aircraft of the Eastern European Region. Chandigarh is an industrial city located in Punjab, India, on the foothills of the Himachal Pradesh-Jammu & Kashmir border. It is the largest city in the state of Punjab. It has a population of about 24,500,000 and is known as 'Chandigarh of the plains'. Today, the city is divided into five districts: Gwalior, Shahjahanpur, Jodhpur, Sahiwalpur and Lajpat Nagar, each having their own police force.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814, with the formation of the subcountry of Lower Rhætia. Liechtenstein's borders have remained unchanged since 1434, when the Rhine established the border between the Holy Roman Empire and the Swiss cantons.AntiquityA Roman road crossed the region from south to north, traversing the Alps by the Splügen Pass and, following the right bank of the Rhine at the edge of the floodplain, was uninhabited for long lengths of time because of periodic flooding. Roman villas  have been excavated in Schaanwald and Nendeln.

Year 1042 (MXLII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April 19 – Emperor Michael V Kalaphates banishes his adoptive mother and co-ruler Zoë, for plotting to poison him, to the island of Principo. His announcement as sole emperor leads to a popular revolt. April 20 – Zoë is proclaimed as empress at an assembly in Hagia Sophia, along with her sister Theodora, as co-ruler. Michael V flees to the monastery of Stoudios, but is arrested, blinded and castrated.

The Quirinal Hill (; ;  ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome, at the north-east of the city center. It is the location of the official residence of the Italian head of state, who resides in the Quirinal Palace; by metonymy "the Quirinal" has come to stand for the Italian president. The Quirinal Palace has an extension of 1.2 million square feet.History According to Roman legend, the Quirinal Hill was the site of a small village of the Sabines, and king Titus Tatius would have lived there after the peace between Romans and Sabines.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD. The first inhabitants of the islands were the Lucayans, an Arawakan-speaking Taino people, who arrived between about 500 and 800 AD from other islands of the Caribbean.Recorded history began on 12 October 1492, when Christopher Columbus landed on the island of Guanahani, which he renamed San Salvador Island, on his first voyage to the New World. The earliest permanent European settlement was in 1648 on Eleuthera. During the 18th century slave trade, many Africans were brought to the Bahamas as slaves to work unpaid.

Year 1203 ( MCCIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Sunday, or Monday in some cases. In the Roman Catholic Church it is a leap year. It is widely used throughout the Latin-speaking countries, especially in Australia, New Zealand and South Africa, although there are sporadic cases in Europe.HistoryIn ancient Rome the year began on Thursday, June 1, the second day of the month known as Calends (from caudalis, "cauter", meaning "fifth"). The new year began on Thursday, July 1.

Year 1515 ( MDXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Europe. It is one of the three official years during which the Orthodox Church is officially recognized and recognized by the Vatican. The Roman Catholic Church uses only two dates in their calendars: 1 September and 12 April.In the Gregorian Calendar, 1515 corresponds to AD1400 (i.e., 1497), while 1515 corresponds to AD1564.This year began with the establishment of the Papal States under Pope Urban VI, and then lasted for a decade before coming to an end.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday , February 28, 2016, when it stopped being leap years. The British Antarctic Territory (BATS)  is the world's only permanent ice-free area in Antarctica and the second-most-populous tropical island inhabited by humans. Located in the Amundsen Sea  south of South Georgia Island, it covers approximately 2,948 square kilometers (1,892 square miles) of ocean. It was formed in 1908 from the remnants of a continent which had been disintegrated during the Pleistocene period.The BATS is home to 1,100,000 inhabitants, many of whom are subsistence farmers.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire , where wealthy citizens of Rome enjoyed a lavish lifestyle.The most famous examples are the Palatine villas of Villa Borghese in Rome, which have been preserved to be shown in the Museum of Natural History in Munich, and the Castelnuovo villa, which is now located in the Piazza del Popolo, Rome's oldest church. In some cases, families who lived in the villa sold part of the land to the local farmers for farming or for other purposes.

Major League Baseball (MLB) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. , a total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball—15 teams in the National League (NL) and 15 in the American League (AL)—with 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. The NL and AL were formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues signed the National Agreement and cooperated but remained legally separate entities until 2000 when they merged into a single organization led by the Commissioner of Baseball.

Juggling is a physical skill, performed by a juggler, involving the manipulation of objects for recreation, entertainment, art or sport. The most recognizable form of juggling is toss juggling. Juggling can be the manipulation of one object or many objects at the same time, most often using one or two hands but also possible with feet. Jugglers often refer to the objects they juggle as props. The most common props are balls, clubs, or rings. Some jugglers use more dramatic objects such as knives, fire torches or chainsaws.

Year 1396 ( MCCCXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday. This is in contrast with leap years, which are always leap weeks. It occurs from 1492 to 2034.Because of its length, the Gregorian calendar tends to be widely observed, especially since many calendars have been based on earlier data. The Great Pyramid of Giza is a limestone sarcophagus at the Giza plateau in northern Egypt. The pyramids are situated on three distinct levels, which may be called the base-line, middle-line, or upper-line.

The French and Indian War ( 1754–1763 ) was a theater of the Seven Years ' War , which pitted the British, French, and Indian forces against each other. The battle started in October 1754, and it was fought from November 1754 until mid-December 1755 in the Battle of Blenheim, north of London. It was a major victory for the British, but one that was decisively won by the French and Indian armies. Aberforth Smith  is a fictional character created by Charles Dickens for his novel  A Christmas Carol (1845).

Events  January–March  January 17 – Tuscarora War: Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County, North Carolina, in a second offensive against the Tuscarora. Heavy snows force the troops to take refuge in Fort Reading, on the Pamlico River. February 1 – Skirmish at Bender, Moldova: Charles XII of Sweden is defeated by the Ottoman Empire. February 4 – Tuscarora War: The Carolina militia under Colonel James Moore leaves Fort Reading, to continue the campaign against the Tuscarora. February 25 – Frederick William I of Prussia begins his reign.

Year 1406 (MCDVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 4 – James I becomes King of Scotland, after having been captured by Henry IV of England. October 7 – French troops comprising 1,000 men at arms land on Jersey, and fight a battle against 3,000 defenders. October 13 – Richard Whittington is elected Lord Mayor of London for a second full term. He holds this office simultaneously, with that of Mayor of the Calais Staple. October 26 – Eric of Pomerania marries Philippa, daughter of Henry IV of England.

The Zwinger  is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden, Germany. Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, it is one of the most important buildings of the Baroque period in Germany. Along with the Frauenkirche, the Zwinger is the most famous architectural monument of Dresden. The name "Zwinger" goes back to the name used in the Middle Ages for a fortress part between the outer and inner fortress walls, even though the Zwinger no longer had a function corresponding to the name at the start of construction.The Zwinger was built in 1709 as an orangery and garden as well as a representative festival area.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

Year 1409 ( MCDIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and continuing throughout the week. It's name derives from the Latin term "maddeus, maddarius", referring both to the month and its first day as "Maddi" in ancient Greek mythology.The first known reference is in the Old Latin Chronicle of Saint John Chrysostom (written c. 1284), which mentions "the four-month year". In economics, the marginal efficiency or cost-effectiveness of one type of action is compared to another type of action.

Vapor pressure (or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US; see spelling differences) or equilibrium vapor pressure is defined as the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases (solid or liquid) at a given temperature in a closed system. The equilibrium vapor pressure is an indication of a liquid's evaporation rate. It relates to the tendency of particles to escape from the liquid (or a solid). A substance with a high vapor pressure at normal temperatures is often referred to as volatile. The pressure exhibited by vapor present above a liquid surface is known as vapor pressure.

Year 1137 (MCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor John II (Komnenos) leads a Byzantine expeditionary force into Cilicia (the Byzantine fleet guards his flank). He defeats the Armenians under Prince Leo I ("Lord of the Mountains"), and captures the cities of Mersin, Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra. Leo retreats to the great fortifications of Anazarbus – where its garrison resists for 37 days. The Byzantine siege engines batter down its walls, and the city is forced to surrender.

Events January–June January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England , Wales , Ireland and Scotland . It is the second of three legislative acts that were not passed by a general assembly. John Cusack is an American television actor. He made his television debut on Law & Order: Criminal Intent on August 1, 1988, as the lead lawyer on the series. Cusack was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor in a TV Drama in 1994 (he was nominated in 1984).

Year 1210 (MCCX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May – The Second Parliament of Ravennika, convened by Emperor Henry of Flanders, is held in the town of Ravennika in Central Greece, in order to resolve the differences between the princes of Frankish Greece, and the Roman Catholic clergy of their domains. The assembled nobles and prelates conclude a concordat, which recognizes the independence and immunity of all Church property in Frankish Greece from any feudal duties.

Eleusine coracana, or finger millet, also known as ragi in India, kodo in Nepal, is an annual herbaceous plant widely grown as a cereal crop in the arid and semiarid areas in Africa and Asia. It is a tetraploid and self-pollinating species probably evolved from its wild relative Eleusine africana.Finger millet is native to the Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands. Interesting crop characteristics of finger millet are the ability to withstand cultivation at altitudes over 2000 m above sea level, its high drought tolerance, and the long storage time of the grains.History Finger millet originated in East Africa (Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands).

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has spent most of his professional life in academia. A founding member of the National Center for Supercomputing Applications (NCSA), Cook developed a theoretical framework that was later adapted for many different applications, including supercomputers. He also founded The Computer Corporation of America (now known as Silicon Graphics Systems) and worked at Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) from 1963 to 1975, where he assisted in the development of the Xerox z80 microcomputer.Cook studied computer science at the University of California, Santa Barbara.

Renate Titzia Groenewold ( born 8 October 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer. She holds the record for fastest lap time of 1:47.67 in a 200 meter time trial on her first world championship team in 2002.Titzia graduated from the Standaard Zuurnamt with a diploma in exercise science, and later took up a career as a competitive cyclist. In 1998, she was invited to race for Team Ronde van Vlaanderen. In mathematics, an associative  is an associative that satisfies the associativity axiom of the category of commutative rings.

The Æsir (Old Norse: ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion. They include Odin, Frigg, Höðr, Thor, and Baldr. The second Norse pantheon is the Vanir. In Norse mythology, the two pantheons wage war against each other, resulting in a unified pantheon. Unlike the Old English word god (and the Old Norse word ), Æsir was never converted over to Christian use.EtymologyÆsir is the plural of áss, ǫ́ss "god". In genitival compounds, it takes the form , e.g.

Year 1213 ( MCCXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending as soon as the new Moon of the following New Moon occurs on the same evening. The year 1213 began on 6 January 1214, the year of King John III of England with the birth of his son Charles I in Westminster Abbey.The year 1213 is also known as the Year of Mercy or the Year of Purity. The abbreviation U.S. Military Academy  or  is a four-year military education program for United States service members that opened in December 1941.

The Polish People 's Party ( , PSL ) is an agrarian political party in Poland . It is currently the third most popular party in Poland with 17.6 percent of the national vote in the 2012 national parliamentary elections and has a strong majority in the Polish Parliament. It also holds 12 seats in the European Parliament, which means that it could take control of at least 18 of Poland's 28 member governments.The party won its first seats in the Polish parliament in 2004 under the leadership of current president Lech Kaczynski but fell from power when he resigned in 2009.

Year 1464 ( MCDLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of every year between 1 February and 28 March. In general, some years may see an additional leap second. The Book of Revelation is the longest book in the New Testament, containing over 2,200 verses or more. The book has been widely accepted as part of the first four books of the Bible, although there were several variants of the text published prior to the canonization of the book by Pope Gregory XVI.

Year 1321 ( MCCCXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday. The date of birth and death is based on the Julian calendar, where the Gregorian calendar is used. It is the only year to start on a Saturday, with both the winter solstice and leap year.In English, the years in the first half of this year are referred to as "first half" years because they contain only the first seven months from the Gregorian calendar, which were recorded as part of the Old Calendar.

Frederick James Prinze (born Frederick Karl Pruetzel; June 22, 1954 – January 29, 1977) was an American stand-up comedian and actor. Prinze was the star of the NBC-TV sitcom Chico and the Man from 1974 until his suicide in 1977, when he shot himself in the head at the young age of 22. Prinze was the father of actor Freddie Prinze Jr.Early lifePrinze was born Frederick Karl Pruetzel (German spelling: Prützel) at Saint Clare's Hospital in Manhattan, New York City the son of Edward Karl Pruetzel and Maria de Gracia Pruetzel (née Graniela y Ramirez).

Year 1509 (MDIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 3 – Battle of Diu: The Portuguese defeat a coalition of Indians, Muslims and Italians. April 21 – Henry VIII becomes King of England (for 38 years) on the death of his father, Henry VII. April 27 – Pope Julius II places Venice under interdict and excommunication, for refusing to cede part of Romagna to papal control. May 14 – Battle of Agnadello: French forces defeat the Venetians.

1166 (MCLXVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) asks Venice to help pay the costs of defending Sicily, whose Norman rulers have had good relations with Venice. Doge Vitale II Michiel refuses to pay the requested subsidy. Manuel begins to cultivate relationships with the main commercial rivals of Venice: Genoa and Pisa. He grants them their own trade quarters in Constantinople, very near to the Venetian settlements. Europe  May 7 – King William I (the Wicked) of Sicily dies at Palermo after a 12-year reign.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera. It includes spoken dialogue, songs, and dances. It is lighter than opera in terms of its music, orchestral size, length of the work, and at face value, subject matter. Apart from its shorter length, the operetta is usually of a light and amusing character. It sometimes also includes satirical commentaries. "Operetta" is the Italian diminutive of "opera" and was used originally to describe a shorter, perhaps less ambitious work than an opera. Operetta provides an alternative to operatic performances in an accessible form targeting a different audience.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business, the methods for attaining those goals, and the time-frame for the achievement of the goals. It also describes the nature of the business, background information on the organization, the organization's financial projections, and the strategies it intends to implement to achieve the stated targets. In its entirety, this document serves as a road-map (a plan) that provides direction to the business.Written business plans are often required to obtain a bank loan or other kind of financing.

Year 1310 ( MCCCX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Europe and North America. It was not an official year, as it never took place on the 12 months of a calendar. The Gregorian Calendar was added in the 13th century to standardize dates throughout Europe. Although it is now one of the traditional years of the year for most Europeans, it may not be the exact year in your own time zone. Homer (; ; 29 September 1743 – 15 February 1818) was an English playwright, humorist, poet, essayist and journalist.

Year 1408 ( MCDVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and running until 2 January 2022.It is officially a leap year for England, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, New Zealand, Norway, Poland, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the United Kingdom but does not formally apply to any of the other Commonwealth countries that follow Gregorian calendar. It is used as the base-two date for the first day of most official holidays, which are also named "first day" in the ISO standard.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of the Holy Roman Empire from 1371 to 1395. He united Germany under his rule in 1412 and then fought in the English Civil War.In 1439, Sigismund had an affair with Elizabeth of Bohemia.The couple's relationship ended in September 1441 when Henry VIII died. His daughter married William Marshal, Duke of Norfolk, Countess of Northumberland. Joseph Smith, Jr., known as John the Baptist, was an American minister and founder of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.

Year 1558 ( MDLVIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was established by Pope Alexander VI to celebrate the arrival of Christian missionaries from the west. As of 2016, it marks the fourth month of the Northern Hemisphere Year 1558. The name of the new year was derived from Greek Νενόξις (melekhos), meaning "beginning", and ἡμελήσκα (einoskarapóka), meaning "the end". The Earth is the largest natural satellite in the Solar System  and the only one that is not currently in orbit around a Sun-like star.

Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental health disorder characterized by dissociative symptoms of extreme disorganization or disassociation, characterized by the feeling of not being one with reality. It is sometimes called "split personality." In contrast to major depression, in which the patient has a sense of personal loss, dissociation is usually accompanied by feelings of sadness, irritability, fatigue, lack of concentration, restlessness, anxiety, and other symptoms that may be severe. The symptoms typically begin in childhood and persist throughout adulthood.

Year 1541 ( MDXLI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Easter Sunday. It is known as "The Good Friday Day" because it was celebrated by most Protestant Churches as a day for remembering their Lord's Supper. The Julian Calendar, used in most parts of the world, switched to the Gregorian calendar on the 1st April 1543.In England, the day was observed as a national holiday from 1603 until 1755, when the King abolished it. Hippolytus was a Greek writer whose works are among the greatest classics in the Western philosophical canon.

Year 1295 (MCCXCV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 20 – Pope Boniface VIII proposes the Treaty of Anagni, seeking to bring peace between the house of Anjou and Sicily; the effort is in vain. June 26 – Przemysł II is crowned King of Poland in Gniezno Cathedral, the first coronation of a Polish ruler in 219 years. October 23 – The first treaty forming the Auld Alliance, between Scotland and France against England, is signed in Paris.

Year 1149 ( MCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian Calendar, or Gregorian in England and the remainder of the United Kingdom. The Glorious Revolution was a political upheaval in early 1789 in which the King of Denmark, Frederiks I, resigned his position as ruler of Denmark to protest against the perceived corrupt practices of the Prussia-Slavery Offering Committee; he also accused the House of Orange of treason. On April 15, 1791, the revolution ended when it was finally overthrown by Prince Frederick William of Sweden, who then proclaimed himself king.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse ( often referred to as the Four Horsemen ) are figures in Christian religion that appear in apocalyptic prophecies and are associated with an apocalyptic ending. The term "end-times" refers to the expected destruction of God's kingdom by the forces of darkness. Females are the primary users of firearms, although they are also important players in combat situations. They are often trained in self-defense. The legal status of firearm ownership varies significantly from state to state. The Federal Aviation Administration is the United States Government agency responsible for administering U.S. air traffic safety.

Events  January–June  March 13 – Battle of Tondibi: In Mali, forces sent by the Saadi Dynasty ruler of Morocco, Ahmad al-Mansur, and led by Judar Pasha, defeat the fractured Songhai Empire, despite being outnumbered by at least five to one. April 10 – English merchant James Lancaster sets off on a voyage to the East Indies. April 21 – Japanese tea-master Sen no Rikyū commits seppuku, on the order of Toyotomi Hideyoshi. May 15 – In Russia, Tsarevich Dimitri, son of Ivan the Terrible, is found dead in mysterious circumstances, at the palace in Uglich.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, United States, and is located halfway between the "tip" and "elbow" of Cape Cod. The town had a population of 3,566 at the 2020 census, which swells nearly sixfold during the summer. A total of 70% of the town's land area is under protection, and nearly half of it is part of the Cape Cod National Seashore. Wellfleet is famous for its oysters, which are celebrated in the annual October Wellfleet OysterFest.History The area was originally settled by Europeans in the 1650s as Billingsgate (after the famous fish market in East London).

Year 1435 (MCDXXXV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 11 – Sweden's first Riksdag of the Estates is summoned under rebel leader Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, who is elected rikshövitsman (military commander of the realm), in the absence of a king, on January 13. January 13 – Sicut Dudum, a papal bull forbidding the enslavement of the Guanche natives in Canary Islands by the Spanish, is promulgated by Pope Eugene IV. February 2 – The Kingdom of Naples passes to  René of Anjou.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River, in the town of Manapouri on the South Island of New Zealand.The harbour and town are located at the south-east corner of Lake Manapouri. The name was given to the harbour soon after the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Hawaii in 1941.Pearl Harbour is used mainly by ferry and water taxi operators transporting Meridian Energy staff  across Lake Manapouri to the Manapouri Hydroelectric Power Station, on the West Arm of the lake. Ferries also carry tourists travelling to the power station and onwards to Doubtful Sound, located on the coast 10 km beyond the West Arm.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC. The 8th century BC is a period of great change for several historically significant civilizations. In Egypt, the 23rd and 24th dynasties lead to rule from Nubia in the 25th Dynasty. The Neo-Assyrian Empire reaches the peak of its power,  conquering the Kingdom of Israel as well as nearby countries.Greece colonizes other regions of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea. Rome is founded in 753 BC, and the Etruscan civilization expands in Italy.

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel and some other systems, such as macOS. File systems in the ext2 format were dropped from many modern Linux distributions due to security implications. An ext4 file system is not considered secure because of its large amount of data, and it is not supported with all Linux distributions.It can be read and written using either a regular file system (a file system mounted on another filesystem) or an ext4 file system mounted on itself.

Year 1514 ( MDXIV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Roman calendar.In the Eastern Orthodox Christian Church, this year began on 25 January, as the Julian calendar, and ends on 28 March, with the Easter Sunday being observed on that same date. Elie Wiesel (; , ; 8 November 1944 – 20 April 2017) was an American poet, novelist, and essayist who won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1989. His works have been described as "a masterwork of moral realism".

Events  January–March  January 8 – Carolean Death March begins: A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the command of Carl Gustaf Armfeldt across the Tydal mountains in a blizzard kills around 3,700 men and cripples a further 600 for life. January 23 – The Principality of Liechtenstein is created, within the Holy Roman Empire. February 3 (January 23 Old Style) – The Riksdag of the Estates recognizes Ulrika Eleonora's claim to the Swedish throne, after she has agreed to sign a new Swedish constitution. Thus, she is recognized as queen regnant of Sweden.

Mariner-H (Mariner Mars '71), also commonly known as Mariner 8, was (along with Mariner 9) part of the Mariner Mars '71 project. It was intended to go into Mars orbit and return images and data, but a launch vehicle failure prevented Mariner 8 from achieving Earth orbit and the spacecraft reentered into the Atlantic Ocean shortly after launch.MissionMariner 8 was launched on an Atlas-Centaur SLV-3C booster (AC-24). The main Centaur engine was ignited 265 seconds after launch, but the upper stage began to oscillate in pitch and tumbled out of control.

Year 1029 ( MXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) at 11:59 PM on the Julian calendar. The day was used as the Roman equivalent of Yule and Christmas, hence the name "December". The  is an abbreviation for the Greek λιτρίνων ( leitônônō), which means "to set in motion" or "to set about." It has been used in English since the mid-eighteenth century but was first popularised in American English in the late nineteenth century, particularly in the works of Walt Whitman.

The Stoned Guest is a `` half-act opera '' by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Trelawney, about a man who has been cast out of society because of his promiscuous sex life. A steed  (plural steeds; also  steed ) is an animal domesticated for its ability to run and perform tricks that make it a valuable means of transportation. Many steeds have become symbols of wealth, power, and other cultural and social prestige. There are various types of steeds including horses, wagons, and carts.

Business is the activity of making one 's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as cash, real estate, stocks, bonds, currencies, etc. ); this can also be a financial activity where the value of the property produced is used to finance the operation of business. The economy is the entire set of socio-economic systems operating within a society; it is an integrated whole, including production, distribution, consumption, investment, government, civil society, and international trade. Economic activities are classified into two major types: domestic and international.

GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG or GPG) is a free-software replacement for Symantec's PGP cryptographic software suite. The software is compliant with RFC 4880, the IETF standards-track specification of OpenPGP. Modern versions of PGP are interoperable with GnuPG and other OpenPGP-compliant systems.GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.Overview GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.

Blum Blum Shub ( B.B.S . ) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum , Manuel Kühn and David Susskind . A variation of Blum-style cryptanalysis was implemented in 1997, but the underlying design remains undetermined. This paper provides details of the method. The Bulgarian National Guard (GNB) is the national armed service of Bulgaria. The GNB consists of approximately 90,000 men, of whom over 70,000 are conscripted on military service; 20,000 of these are volunteer soldiers who undertake voluntary military service. Civilian employment is restricted to about 25% of the active military personnel.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold , Suffolk , England , by George and Ernest Adnams. Antarctica is an island country in the southern hemisphere. Antarctica is the second largest landmass on earth after the continents of Australia, Greenland, Canada, and the USA. The continent has an area of 9,130 km² (3,865 sq mi), of which over 4,400 km2 is ice, including about 1,200 km2 on the sea floor and 2,100 km2 above sea level. In addition, the ice sheet to the north of the continent covers almost 20% of the entire surface of the continent.

Year 1530 ( MDXXX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian era, commonly abbreviated to Jūd in modern times. It is generally regarded as the birth year of Pope Adrian VI, the founder of the Papal Nuncio, during his papacy from 1528 to 1535. In cryptography, encryption refers to the means by which information is conveyed from one system to another. For example, an algorithm used to encrypt or decrypt data is called a key. Algorithms that encrypt or decrypt data are also called keys.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger. For comparison, a bolt-action rifle requires the user to cycle the bolt manually before they can fire a second time, and a fully automatic rifle, provided it has ammunition, will continue to fire until the trigger is released. Most modern automatic rifles are selective fire, meaning the user can fire semi-automatically if desired.HistoryThe first design of a recoil-operated semi-automatic rifle is attributed to Ferdinand Mannlicher, who unveiled the design in 1885 based on work begun in 1883.

Botulinum toxin (BoNT) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species. It prevents the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from axon endings at the neuromuscular junction, thus causing flaccid paralysis. The toxin causes the disease botulism. The toxin is also used commercially for medical and cosmetic purposes.The seven main types of botulinum toxin are named types A to G (A, B, C1, C2, D, E, F and G). New types are occasionally found. Types A and B are capable of causing disease in humans, and are also used commercially and medically.

Year 1219 (MCCXIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  February – Pelagius orders the Crusader army to prepare an attack against the Egyptians, but is unsuccessful because of the weather and strength of the defenders. Sultan Al-Kamil, in command of the Egyptian forces, is almost overthrown by a conspiracy in his entourage. He considers fleeing to the Ayyubid Emirate of Yemen, ruled by his son Al-Mas'ud Yusuf, but the arrival of his brother Al-Mu'azzam with reinforcements from Syria, ends the conspiracy.

Year 1429 ( MCDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar. It was introduced by Julius Caesar, although it was not used until the 18th century. The earliest surviving example dates back to the late 4th century BC. In physics, an atom is a single, electrically neutral atomic unit that consists of an ion and an antiquark. They cannot be negatively charged. An atom is composed of two protons and two neutrons with electrons surrounding them. A nucleus is the nucleus of one of the atoms, while the electrons orbit around it.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday, February 29. By adding a second leap day (Friday, February 30) Sweden reverted to the Julian calendar and the rest of the year (from Saturday, March 1) was in sync with the Julian calendar. Sweden finally made the switch from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar in 1753. This year has 367 days.Events  January–March  January 8 – Total eclipse of the sun visible from  January 12 – The premiere of the opera Idoménée by André Campra takes place at the Théâtre du Palais-Royal in Paris.

Year 1432 (MCDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – Iliaș succeeds his father as Prince of Moldavia. Spring – An Albanian revolt, led by Gjergj Arianit Komneni, breaks out against the Ottoman Empire, and spreads through most of Albania. April – At the end of the Hook and Cod wars, Jacqueline, Countess of Hainaut and Countess of Holland and Zeeland, is forced by Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, to abdicate all her estates in his favour, ending Hainaut and Holland as independent counties.

Melvin Kranzberg (November 22, 1917 – December 6, 1995) was an American historian, and professor of history at Case Western Reserve University from 1952 until 1971. He was a Callaway professor of the history of technology at Georgia Tech from 1972 to 1988.Born in St. Louis, Missouri, Kranzberg graduated from Amherst College, received a master's and a PhD from Harvard University and served in the Army in Europe during World War II. He received a Bronze Star for interrogating captured German prisoners and learning the location of Nazi gun emplacements.

Year 1524 ( MDXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the 1st month of his reign, according to Gregorian and Julian calendars. In medicine there are two ways to determine the sex of a newborn or infant. One method involves using an ultrasonographic technique to detect a baby's testes; the other relies on microscopic characteristics of the genitalia. Both techniques have been employed in numerous medical applications but only the ultrasonographic technique has been developed for routine use in obstetrics and gynecology.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Northern Hemisphere, and is used in Australia, New Zealand, Europe, North America and South America; it has been used in South Africa from the mid-eighteenth century. The Julian calendar was introduced in AD 1582 by Pope Leo X to replace the previous Gregorian Calendar. It replaced the ancient Julian calendar, which continued to be observed after the collapse of the Western Roman Empire about the year 1204.The Julian calendar began in 1582 with the addition of 365 days, replacing the Julian leap day.

Events January–June January – Six months into King Philip 's War , Metacomet ( King Philip ) , leader of the Burgundians, sets up a government in Bohemia and Moravia with support from the Roman Catholic Church. In 1521 he is killed in an assassination attempt by Charles Martel of France who is later revealed to have been inspired by the Pope's letter to King Henry VII of England regarding the Protestant Reformation. Methamphetamine (METH) is a psychoactive central nervous system stimulant drug with effects similar to that of amphetamines. The drug was first synthesized in 1912 by Hans Hofmann, and its commercialization commenced in 1935.

Events January–March January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against German invasion of the country. The treaty was later broken off, however, when Germany invaded France in the spring of 1940. February 2 – The United States declares war on the Axis Powers, which include Germany, Italy, Japan, and the Soviet Union, as part of the Manhattan Project. March 17 – An air battle between USAAF B-24 Liberator bombers and Japanese fighters takes place during the Battle of Midway at the Marianas Islands.

Alpine skiing , or downhill skiing , is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings and foot pegs. Skiing is a popular pastime in Austria, and it is sometimes also called Alpine skiing.Skiing dates from prehistory and is associated with various nomadic hunter-gatherer tribes that occupied the Alps until the 15th century. Gorilla is an African word meaning gorilla. The first recorded use of the name Gorilla as an African word was by European explorer Charles Darwin (1859–1924) who described the South American apes in his book The Descent of Man published in 1859.

Otto III (June/July 980 – 23 January 1002) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death in 1002. A member of the Ottonian dynasty, Otto III was the only son of the Emperor Otto II and his wife Theophanu.Otto III was crowned as King of Germany in 983 at the age of three, shortly after his father's death in Southern Italy while campaigning against the Byzantine Empire and the Emirate of Sicily. Though the nominal ruler of Germany, Otto III's minor status ensured his various regents held power over the Empire.

Year 1433 ( MCDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the reign of King John I of England. In mathematics,  is a measure that expresses the number of unique solutions to problems in finite fields. A solution may be said to satisfy  or  to mean that there is no other solution with the same set of solutions. If  is defined in terms of  it can also be defined in terms of  such that for any nonnegative integer x, there exists a problem with at least as many solutions as there are integers .

Year 1387 ( MCCCLXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic era, and ending on Thursday after the Julian Calendar. In mathematics, a binomial coefficient  is a non-negative real number that has a probability of 1/2 for a particular outcome. Binomial coefficients were known as "the queen of primes" because they occur in some of the most popular problems in arithmetic.Binomial coefficients can be defined using either the simple or the complex conjugate notation.The simple formula is denoted by P(1/2)C(1/2); C is the prime factorization, which is 0 through 5.

Year 1463 (MCDLXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 5 – French poet François Villon receives a reprieve from death by hanging, and is banished from Paris (his further life is undocumented). May – The Kingdom of Bosnia falls to the Ottoman Empire. September 15 – Battle of Vistula Lagoon: The navy of the Prussian Confederation defeats that of the Teutonic Order. October 8 – The Truce of Hesdin ends French support for the House of Lancaster in England. Date unknown  Muhammad Rumfa starts to rule in Kano.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic, waterways and railroads. All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil and gas pipelines are regulated by the Ministry of Transportation of Azerbaijan Republic. For Soviet transportation, see Transport in the Soviet Union.RailwaysThere are  of rail tracks out of which only  are in common carrier service and  are industrial lines. Total:  (2013)Country comparison to the world: 59Broad gauge:  gaugeRailway links with adjacent countriesTimelineMetro System Currently, the only metro system in Azerbaijan is the Baku Metro, located in Baku, the country's capital.New plans to open metro systems in the most populated and developed cities of Azerbaijan were unveiled.

Year 1292 (MCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  April 5 – The Papal election, 1292–94 begins. November – Michael II becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch. November 17 (Julian calendar) – John Balliol is selected by King Edward I of England as King of Scotland, from among 13 competitors for the Crown of Scotland; Edward then treats John as a puppet ruler and Scotland as a vassal state, eventually provoking the Wars of Scottish Independence, commencing in 1296.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection. These may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. Recovery generally takes two to seven days. In a small proportion of cases, the disease develops into a more severe dengue hemorrhagic fever, resulting in bleeding, low levels of blood platelets and blood plasma leakage, or into dengue shock syndrome, where dangerously low blood pressure occurs.Dengue is spread by several species of female mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, principally Aedes aegypti.

Andrew Stuart `` Andy '' Fastow ( born December 22 , 1961 ) is a convicted felon and former financier. In 1996, he was convicted by jury on 14 counts of bribery, tax fraud, and conspiracy to embezzle $1.4 billion dollars from his own companies.He served 13 months in jail, followed by another 2 years on house arrest, for the charges.He resigned as Chairman of the United States Securities and Exchange Commission in November 2001, and became chairman emeritus of Bankers Trust Company, Inc. He has also served as an executive at Citibank, N.A.

Year 1533 ( MDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Sunday, August 3rd. It was followed by an additional leap day on Saturday, December 30th .The Julian calendar had been in use from the first years after the birth of Jesus of Nazareth until his death about A.D. 35. The number of years without a leap day has not been known with certainty. In computing, annular means that each point in a sphere is divided into three parts by a circle, rather than being defined at a fixed distance along one side.

Year 1290 ( MCCXC ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in most countries. Grammar (also spelled grammar) is the science and study of the rules used in writing and spoken language to convey, interpret or convey meaning. It is concerned with how to express ideas in writing, reading, speaking and listening. A grammarian is an educator who uses language to help human beings understand the world. Grammarian teachers have long been known for their practical, hands-on approach to teaching students about language, especially English.

Robert von Ranke Graves ( 24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985 ) was a British poet , historical novelist and critic. He is considered one of Britain's foremost living modern poets, and the author of six major novels.Graves is best known for his works of realism and allegorical prose, which has been translated into more than 25 languages. Germaine Greer (born March 21, 1944) is a British writer, historian, lecturer, activist, feminist and disability rights leader. Her views are widely accepted in the academic and professional communities.

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 (MCDXXIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 27 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Hořice: The Taborites decisively beat the Utraquists. May 21–22 – Byzantine–Ottoman Wars: The Ottoman governor of Thessaly, Turakhan Beg, breaks through the Hexamilion wall, and ravages the Peloponnese Peninsula. July 31 – Hundred Years' War – Battle of Cravant: The French army is defeated at Cravant, on the banks of the River Yonne near Auxerre, by the English and their Burgundian allies.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as oral histories. However, there is no archaeological evidence to demonstrate the existence of written works concerning the founding of Rome during the 1st century A.D. Instead, scholars have relied on oral tradition and historical documentation, especially the writings of Tacitus. The most extensive study of the story of the founding of Rome took place at the Institute for Roman History in Bonn, Germany, under the supervision of Prof. Dr. Carl-Werner Küng (1934–2014), a renowned archeological archaeologist.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950 , was an early national gay rights organization in the United States , advocating for legal changes and political reform. It served as a leader of the American LGBT liberation movement and has been recognized as having played a critical role in promoting civil rights for LGBT people. Its founder, Paul Mattachine (1910–2004), is considered by many to have been one of the founding fathers of modern LGBT advocacy.HistoryThe Mattachine Society was founded on December 15, 1950, in Chicago by members of the National Organization for Marriage (NOM) – a Christian fundamentalist group founded in 1941.

Events January–March January 8 – Carolean Death March begins : A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the leadership of Captain Gustavus Adolphus, ending the siege of Helsingfors in southern Sweden. Dinosaurs are reptiles that include everything from ammonites to plesiosaurs , and may have been dinosaurs. They were long-necked, bipedal animals with long, sinuous necks and relatively short bodies, although their bones can still be found at the skeletons of many extinct organisms. Dinosaur fossils are found on land, but fossilised remains of them have not yet been found in the sea.

Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  The Judge-Governor of Seville in Al-Andalus (modern Spain) takes advantage of the disintegration of the Caliphate of Córdoba and seizes power as Abbad I, founding the Abbadid dynasty. December – Abbad I declares the Taifa of Seville independent from Córdoban rule. Abd ar-Rahman V is proclaimed Caliph at Córdoba. Asia  April – An epidemic in Kyoto (Japan) is so severe that there are corpses in the streets; disease spreads throughout the country.

Year 1435 ( MCDXXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Roman Catholic tradition, when the new pope was elected. Gaelic (gaelíon; ; or  , ), also spelled gaelic, is the native language of the Gaelic speakers of Ireland and Scotland. The first documented use of the language dates to c. 775, when the Irish king Ailill mac Cumhaill ruled his land with the help of the Scots-Irish confederation. The Hebrew Bible (Hebrew Bible) is an Old Testament book that documents the historical events of the Old Testament.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga , which are separated geographically by the state of Victoria. The term Albury originated as a reference to the ancient town of Alcote, which was first recorded in the 13th century BC, and later called Albury.HistoryThe town was originally inhabited between the mid-11th Century BC and the late 10th century AD. It was the location of the earliest Christian monastic city in Australia, St Albans, established in 1155 AD. Ardmore College was founded in 1876 as a free school on land owned by the University of Pennsylvania.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, described as the Varian Disaster  by Roman historians, took place at modern Kalkriese in 9 AD, when an alliance of Germanic peoples ambushed Roman legions and their auxiliaries, led by Publius Quinctilius Varus. The alliance was led by Arminius, a Germanic officer of Varus's auxilia. Arminius had acquired Roman citizenship and had received a Roman military education, which enabled him to deceive the Roman commander methodically and anticipate the Roman army's tactical responses.Teutoburg Forest is commonly seen as one of the most important defeats in Roman history, bringing the triumphant period of expansion under Augustus to an abrupt end.

A corporate haven , corporate tax haven , or multinational tax haven , is used to describe a jurisdiction that does not collect taxes on all its income, unlike countries that do. In practice, the term encompasses a number of legal and practical arrangements, but most importantly it refers to jurisdictions that maintain a policy of non-collection of their country's corporate income tax.The word "tax haven" is derived from the British English word "tea house"; the phrase comes from the French verb "teacher à teunie", meaning "to teach privately".

Year 1514 (MDXIV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 10 – A great fire breaks out, in the Rialto of Venice. March 12 – A huge exotic embassy sent by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X arrives in Rome, including Hanno, an Indian elephant. March – Louis XII of France makes peace with Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor. May 2 – The Poor Conrad peasant revolt against Ulrich, Duke of Württemberg begins in Beutelsbach.

Nvidia Corporation  is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara, California. It is a fabless company which designs graphics processing units (GPUs) for the gaming and professional markets, as well as system on a chip units (SoCs) for the mobile computing and automotive market. Its primary GPU line, labeled "GeForce", is in direct competition with the GPUs of the "Radeon" brand by Advanced Micro Devices (AMD). Nvidia expanded its presence in the gaming industry with its handheld game consoles Shield Portable, Shield Tablet, and Shield Android TV and its cloud gaming service GeForce Now.

Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Summer – Emperor Henry II conducts his third Italian military campaign. He makes plans to invade the south, but remains non-commital. June 15 – Byzantine troops under Catepan Basil Boioannes (supported by his ally Prince Pandulf IV) capture the fortress of Troia. The French city of Saint-Germain-en-Laye is founded by King Robert II (the Pious). King Canute the Great codifies the laws of England (approximate date).

Year 1358 ( MCCCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) in England and Scotland, but not in most other parts of Great Britain. The name dates from the 15th-century reign of King Philip II of France (1588–1621), who reigned between 1618 and 1621. A barge is a self-propelled craft typically used to transport people, goods, or both along a waterway. They are generally made of wooden frame, steel or other materials, and have movable gondolas so that they can be moved to a different location or destination.

Year 1329 (MCCCXXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 1 – King John of Bohemia (of the Teutonic Order) captures Medvėgalis, an important fortress of the pagan Grand Duchy of Lithuania, and baptizes 6,000 of its defenders. February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1332). March 27 – Pope John XXII condemns some teachings of Meister Eckhart as heretical. April – Antipope Nicholas V is excommunicated by Pope John XXII.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive , rod-shaped , facultatively anaerobic , motile , beta-hemolytic , spore-forming bacterium commonly found in human and animal soil. It has been used for the treatment of intestinal parasites (including protozoal, protospore, and metamorphic worms) and for the prevention and treatment of infections with certain bacteria, fungi, and viral pathogens, including hepatitis C virus and tuberculosis. Abigail Van Vliet (born January 21, 1939) is an American songwriter, singer, and guitarist. She was born in Fort Worth, Texas but raised in New Jersey. She began writing songs at age 11.

In physics, optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power through a material.Thus, the larger the optical depth, the smaller the amount of transmitted radiant power through the material. Spectral optical depth or spectral optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted spectral radiant power through a material. Optical depth is dimensionless, and in particular is not a length, though it is a  monotonically increasing function of optical path length, and approaches zero as the path length approaches zero.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles III of Sweden, the duke of Hesse-Darmstadt, the duke of Brunswick and the duchy of Brunswick. Köpf  is a city in Austria's Baden-Württemberg province, bordering on the Czech Republic and Poland. It has been part of Bavaria since the 12th century.Köpf was built by the Knights of St John in 1139 as the seat of their order until they were expelled in 1185. Later, during the Hussite Wars (1199–1312), local nobles fought to defend the town from the Ottoman Turks.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae. Giant bamboos are the largest members of the grass family. The origin of the word "bamboo" is uncertain, but it probably comes from the Dutch or Portuguese language, which originally borrowed it from Malay or Kannada.In bamboo, as in other grasses, the internodal regions of the stem are usually hollow and the vascular bundles in the cross-section are scattered throughout the stem instead of in a cylindrical arrangement. The dicotyledonous woody xylem is also absent.

It begins on the  of January, with the  first day of that month. Abderamir ibn Hamid al-Razak (, ; 1 August 1534 – 29 May 1571), Arabic for "The Prophet of Islam", was a Muslim mystic who flourished between the 11th and 12th centuries AD.

Year 1181 (MCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  King Philip II (Augustus) annuls all loans made by Jews to Christians, and takes a percentage for himself. A year later, he confiscates all Jewish property and expels the Jews from Paris. Philip II begins a war against Philip of Alsace, count of Flanders, over the Vermandois. He claims the territory for his wife Isabella of Hainault as her dowry. Philip is unwilling to give it up.

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to simply as "John", was an Italian-born friar who was the spiritual father of Pope Benedict XVI. He was canonised with St. John Lateran in 2000 by Pope Benedict XVI.Early lifeBorn in Florence, Giacomo I Estienne was the grandson of Girolamo Riccardi.
