Hannibal (, from Latin HANNIBAL – literally, "the cannibal") was an eighteenth century English playwright, best known for his The Cannibals: A History of the Human Race (1739–1611).

Year 1511 (MDXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 26 - The 1511 Idrija earthquake occurs, with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme). The epicenter is around the town of Idrija in present-day Slovenia, although some place it some 15-20 kilometers to the west, between Gemona and Pulfero in Friulian Slovenia. The earthquake affects a large territory between Carinthia, Friuli, present-day Slovenia and Croatia. April 9 St John's College, Cambridge, England, founded by Lady Margaret Beaufort, receives its charter.The Şahkulu Rebellion breaks out in Anatolia.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus (; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 500 extant species of oaks. The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably Lithocarpus (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as Grevillea robusta (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). The genus Quercus is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa.

Year 1208 ( MCCVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday, November 20th. The Julian Calendar is the only known valid calendar used by all countries, except in the case of Australia and New Zealand, who follow the Gregorian calendars, which are not recognized as valid by either nation's Government.HistoryIn 1066, Pope Gregory I declared the year 1066 to be Year 1301 in order to increase the number of days in the summer solstice for the Catholic Church. However, he was forced to abandon this decision after widespread public protest.

Year 1032 ( MXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) on the Gregorian calendar that began in AD 1 and extended from November 25, 564 AD until December 31, 581 AD. Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (February 14, 1809 – August 15, 1895) was an Austrian-Jewish philosopher, novelist, historian, theologian, and social reformer whose work has influenced numerous other German and foreign writers, artists, musicians and thinkers. He is best known for his epic poem "The Sorrows of Young Werther" (1797–1800).

Year 1171 ( MCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in English-speaking Britain. It is an official year in many of the other parts of the world that observe the Gregorian calendar, including most of the Commonwealth countries, South America, and part of Australia, New Zealand, Indonesia, Taiwan and the Philippines.The year 991 AD marked the foundation of the Roman Empire as the Western Roman Empire, which was founded under the emperor Titus Flavius Domitian during the year 963. The year 1193 AD marked the beginning of the Hundred Years' War, which lasted from 1329 to 1346.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series premiered on September 16, 1975. It ran from October 12, 1975 to April 4, 1976. It is one of the longest-running scripted television programs in TV history, with the original run spanning eight seasons. The Middle Ages (; ; , ) is a period that includes the medieval period, the early modern era, the Renaissance, and the Enlightenment. From the 14th to the 17th centuries, Europe experienced a period of political upheaval, religious unrest, and social instability.

Year 1174 ( MCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar. It was later replaced by January 1st in the Julian calendar.The year 1174 was named after Alexander the Great's conquest of the city of Pella in 1154, when he became the first Greek to conquer the entire island of Sicily. The name of the year is derived from the Greek word for "city" – Κατεῖν . In English, an  is a noun or adjective formed from an initial vowel and added consonant sounds.

Year 1185 ( MCLXXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Wednesday, according to Gregorian calendar . The Julian calendar introduced in AD 1283 continued the Gregorian calendar with an 8-year cycle from AD 1273 through AD 1582. A leap year occurs every other year unless a leap second is added during the following year. Julia Annas (born April 24, 1940) is an American movie actress, singer, and dancer. Julia Annas began modeling at the age of twelve. Her first film appearance came in 1963 when she played a role in the short-lived television series Glamour Bikini Girls.

Abolitionism, or the abolitionist movement, was the movement to end slavery. In Western Europe and the Americas, abolitionism was a historic movement that sought to end the Atlantic slave trade and liberate the enslaved people.The British abolitionist movement started in the late 18th century when English and American Quakers began to question the morality of slavery. James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament, and eventually encouraging his friends Granville Sharp and Hannah More to vigorously pursue the cause.

Year 1569 (MDLXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 11–May 6 – The first recorded lottery in England is performed nonstop, at the west door of St Paul's Cathedral. Each share costs ten shillings, and proceeds are used to repair harbours, and for other public works. March 13 – Battle of Jarnac: Royalist troops under Marshal Gaspard de Tavannes surprise and defeat the Huguenots under the Prince of Condé, who is captured and murdered. A substantial proportion of the Huguenot army manages to escape, under Gaspard de Coligny.

Year 1270 ( MCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Southern United States. It is often used as an unofficial national holiday in many states but it is not formally recognised in most other countries.The exact meaning of the year 1270 remains unknown, though most modern scholars think that it referred to the period of the first three centuries after Christ and before he ascended into heaven. As a result, it has sometimes been referred to simply as the Year of Light. A barber is a specialist in hair removal.

Year 1525 (MDXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is born when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother on Neustadt-Gasse, Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union. February 24 – Battle of Pavia: German and Spanish forces under Charles de Lannoy and the Marquis of Pescara defeat the French army, and capture Francis I of France, after his horse is wounded by Cesare Hercolani.

Events  January–March  January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake: Mount Etna erupts, causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of Sicily and Malta. February 8 – The College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia is granted a Royal charter. March 27 – Bozoklu Mustafa Pasha becomes the new Grand Vizier of the Ottoman Empire, after Sultan Ahmed II appoints him as the successor of Çalık Ali Pasha. April–June  April 4 – Anne Palles becomes the last accused witch to be executed for witchcraft in Denmark, after having been convicted of using powers of sorcery.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children's game in which at least two players (usually at least three) conceal themselves in a set environment, to be found by one or more seekers. The game is played by one chosen player (designated as being "it") counting to a predetermined number with eyes closed while the other players hide. After reaching this number, the player who is "it" calls "Ready or not, here I come!" or "Coming, ready or not!" and then attempts to locate all concealed players.The game can end in one of several ways.

Year 996 (CMXCVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  February - Chotoku Incident: Fujiwara no Korechika and Takaie shoot an arrow at Retired Emperor Kazan 2 March: Emperor Ichijo orders the imperial police to raid Korechika’s residence - Empress Teishi (sister of Korechika) cuts her hair because of the humiliation - Takaie is arrested, Korechika is absent  5 March: Korechika returns with his head shaven and attired as a monk Europe  Spring – King Otto III starts his first expedition to Italy from Regensburg, and proceeds over the Brenner Pass.

Year 1427 ( MCDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in most countries in Europe, including Britain, and later in some parts of Asia, including Korea, China, Japan, Russia, and South Korea. The Gregorian calendar is used to define the date using astronomical observations made after January 1, 1582. In many countries, it is used only as part of a leap day during the year.HistoryIn ancient times, the first recorded years of the Gregorian calendar are not known; it is not clear how they ended up being calculated.

Year 1148 (MCXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Second Crusade  January 1 – The French crusaders under King Louis VII defeat a Turkish ambush next to the Meander River. Three days later they arrive at Laodicea – passing the spot where the German contingent led by Otto of Freising has been so disastrously ambushed (see 1147). The Crusaders are badly mauled as they cross Mount Cadmus (around January 8) before reaching Adalia on January 20.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine (sometimes referred to as St. John's and also nicknamed St. John the Unfinished) is the cathedral of the Episcopal Diocese of New York. It is at 1047 Amsterdam Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City, between West 110th Street (also known as Cathedral Parkway) and West 113th Street.The cathedral is an unfinished building, with only two-thirds of the proposed building completed, due to several major stylistic changes and work interruptions. The original design, in the Byzantine Revival and Romanesque Revival styles, began construction in 1892.

Sigismund of Luxembourg (15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary and Croatia from 1387, king of Germany from 1411, king of Bohemia from 1419, and Holy Roman Emperor from 1433 until his death in 1437, as well as prince-elector of Brandenburg (1378–1388 and 1411–1415). He was the last male member of the House of Luxembourg.Sigismund was born in Nuremberg, the son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV and Elizabeth of Pomerania. He married Queen Mary of Hungary in 1385 and was crowned King of Hungary soon after.

Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell (also called electrotransfer). In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used.

Year 1022 (MXXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Battle of Svindax: The Byzantine army under Emperor Basil II defeats the Georgians at Svindax (modern Turkey). King George I is forced to negotiate a peace treaty, ending the Byzantine–Georgian wars. Summer – Nikephoros Phokas (Barytrachelos) conspires with the Byzantine general Nikephoros Xiphias against Basil II. The rebellion collapses and Xiphias assassinates Phokas. Europe  Spring – Emperor Henry II divides his army into three columns and descends through Rome onto Capua.

Year 1510 ( MDX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar, and ending on the first Wednesday in January after an extra leap year. It is derived from the Julian calendar, where it became the last of the years to use the Julian year. In addition, it is not a leap-year—it only uses the previous year as its starting point. The year 1510 was officially recognised by the United States government in 1789.The year 1510 was the first year for which the new English Calendar was officially adopted.

William Makepeace Thackeray ( ; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863 ) was a British novelist , author and essayist who is best known for the novels The Adventure of the Princess Diaries and A Tale of Two Cities. In the latter, Thackeray set out on a literary journey during his life, travelling extensively to explore the Americas and the world beyond it. His first major work, The Old Vic Theatre, appeared in 1838, while he continued to write poetry and essays throughout his life. An anaphylactic reaction is an allergic reaction triggered by contact with a food that causes severe swelling of the eyes resulting in blindness.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was King of Poland from December 1419 until his death in January 1421. His reign witnessed many major political developments, such as the Polish–Lithuanian War that started on 29 November 1396 and ended on 1 May 1420. A bistable  is a piece of metal or stone with an internal surface that has a characteristic surface tension, such as flat or smooth. In most cases, the internal surface tension can vary between small and large values.

Year 1434 ( MCDXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday (link can be clicked to load a PDF of the year). It means "king of kings", a title first attested in the early 16th century.It was also commonly used by the Puritans in the 17th and 18th centuries.Early historyThe earliest references to the surname date from the early 11th century when it referred to the son of Richard, who succeeded his uncle, King Henry II, as regent during the reign of Richard III.

Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

Year 1056 ( MLVI ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and finishing on Thursday, January 12. It is the last of the traditional leap years and the first of the new-year leap years. The Roman Catholic Church uses it as an alternative to leap years that begin in March. Albert Einstein (; 31 December 1897 – 29 February 1919) was an Austrian-born theoretical physicist, mathematician, philosopher, and writer. At the height of his fame in the late 1920s and 1930s he was regarded as one of the most important scientists in the 20th century.

Events January–June January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought . January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath , every member of the Swiss army pledges to fight as if it were in war with the Netherlands. It is believed that during the course of the civil war, at least some members of the Swiss army renounced their loyalty to the crown and joined the Dutch armies.January 7 – The Burgomaster of Trier abdicates his office, and the Elector of Bavaria becomes ruler of the country.January 11 – The Council of Constance annuls the Peace of Utrecht signed on November 15, 1605.

Kazimierz Funk ( ; February 23 , 1884 – November 19 , 1967 ) , commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was an Austrian painter and printmaker best known for creating a range of figurative abstract-style painting and sculpture.Funk's career spanned more than half a century, from the mid-1920s until his death in 1967. His works have been shown widely in museums, including the Kunstkammer der Rätsel (Göttingen: Kunsthistorisches Museum; Frankfurt: Musee d'Art Nouveau; 2010–2018), the Kunsthaler Koninklijke Kommission (Vienna: Kunsthistorisches Museum; 2007–2010), and the National Museum of Art, Rome (Rome: Musée della Sede Apostolica; 2005–2009).

Events January–June March 13 – Battle of Tondibi : In Mali , forces sent by the Saadi Dynasty ruler of Mali are defeated at Tondibi. The French claim to have been present in the area but they do not give evidence of being in actual combat, leaving it up to the Maliis to determine who actually attacked them. A book is a physical medium that records information or conveys data, usually in some form, in order to make sense of it (usually through its own use) or to disseminate it. A printed volume includes a number of pages.

Year 1419 (MCDXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Hundred Years' War: Rouen surrenders to Henry V of England, which brings Normandy under the control of England. June 20 – The Ōei Invasion of Tsushima Island, Japan by Joseon Korea begins. July 30 – The first Defenestration of Prague occurs in Bohemia. August – Siege of Ceuta: The Portuguese successfully defend off the invading Moroccans who attempt to retake the city of Ceuta. September 10 – John the Fearless, Duke of Burgundy is assassinated by adherents of the Dauphin.

King Andrew II of Hungary arrives with his army in Split, in Dalmatia. He is joined by German forces, led by Duke Leopold VI (the Glorious). At the end of July, Pope Honorius III orders the crusaders assembled in Italy and Sicily to proceed to Cyprus, but there is no transport provided by the Italian city-states, Venice, Genoa and Pisa.

Year 1327 (MCCCXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 25 – The 14-year-old Edward III is proclaimed King of England, after his mother Isabella has engineered the abdication of his imprisoned father Edward II of England, on January 20, effective January 25. Isabella and her lover Roger Mortimer rule as regents (the coronation takes place February 1). April 6 (Good Friday) – Tuscan writer Petrarch sees a woman he names Laura in the church of Sainte-Claire d'Avignon, which awakes in him a lasting passion.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics , at Utah Olympic Park . The competition took place between February 7 and 15, 2002 and ended on February 17. In mathematics (and related disciplines), a function is defined as a function whose values are independent of its argument. If two different functions have similar values, then the values of their arguments are the same.For example, consider f(x) : f(x) = -x2 + y2y + z2z2 = 0. In this case, x2 and y2 are both zero.

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction, New Hampshire in 1992. The company's name was chosen from the words "newcomen" and "digital", which have been used interchangeably since the early 1990s to refer to digital electronics. A dual-core CPU can operate at a frequency that is equal to or higher than its maximum frequency. A dual-core CPU is defined by two sets of registers, one for instruction and one for control. There are usually four registers in a dual-core machine, each with a set of 16 bits of memory.

Year 1373 ( MCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar. It has been observed as the 14th, 15th, 17th, 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st, and 22nd months of the Julian calendar. The Chinese writing system  is an ideographic script, which is characterized by a phonetic system and a set of consonant symbols to represent words. The alphabet consists of nine characters in each glyph representing a basic sound unit. These characters can be further divided into three categories: consonant symbols, vowel symbols and diphthongs.

Year 1455 ( MCDLV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, 20 January 2015. In the Roman calendar it is the 4th month of the Gregorian calendar.It began with a leap day in the Gregorian calendar, 12 October 1582, and then followed a two-year period of annual leap years. An archaism ( Greek  αρχαίος ), literally meaning 'hidden word' is an archaic word that may be used to describe anything which is not directly mentioned or expressed as part of a text, but is otherwise understood as true.

Year 1430 ( MCDXXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar. The year began on Sunday 28th of April 1533 AD and ends on Monday 20th of December 1579 AD.The exact date varies between years, depending on the Julian calendar being used at the time.Historical figuresBorn: 13 February 1215-13 September 1295ADBirthday: 9 March 1278-22 January 1307ADDied: 23 June 1388AD
Henry IV ( , ;  ;  ), known by variously as Henry III, Henry V or Henry VI, was King of England from 5 August 1483 until his death on 11 February 1536.

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891 . It is used as a radio frequency (RF) transmitter or amplifier for radio and television transmissions. The coils use a magnetic field to move the metal conducting rods that form the transducer's outer shell, thus amplifying the signal transmitted. The coils are powered by batteries or other electrical energy sources and can be used at distances of up to 1,000 km (621 mi).The term 'Tesla Coil' comes from the name of his patented invention, developed during his working days at a company known as Edison Co., Ltd.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles V and Queen Isabella of Castile, King Henry IV of England and King William III of France. He inherited the imperial throne after his father's death, and in 1361 assumed the title Duke of Parma, becoming the first English king to hold this position since the Norman conquest of 1066. An abridgement of the Bible is a work of translation based on ancient texts that have been translated into English by modern biblical translators; however, they do not reflect the original texts' literal content.

Events June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary , Queen of Scots , recognizes Philip II of Spain as her sovereign. This is the first occasion in modern times when a queen of the Netherlands recognized a ruler from another European country. Aberdeen ( ; or ; ; ; ) is a city-county in the East of Scotland, and part of Greater Manchester. It is one of three cities in the United Kingdom that are on the Isle of Skye. It lies along the southern coast of the Bay of Strathclyde, about 100 miles west of Edinburgh.

Year 1472 (MCDLXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 20 – Orkney and Shetland are returned by Norway to Scotland, as a result of a defaulted dowry payment. December 31 – The city council of Amsterdam prohibits snowball fights: "Neymant en moet met sneecluyten werpen nocht maecht noch wijf noch manspersoon." ("No one shall throw with snowballs, neither men nor (unmarried) women.") Date unknown  The first printed edition of Dante Alighieri's Divine Comedy is published in Foligno.

A mace is a blunt weapon, a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to deliver powerful strikes. A mace typically consists of a strong, heavy, wooden or metal shaft, often reinforced with metal, featuring a head made of stone, bone, copper, bronze, iron, or steel.The head of a military mace can be shaped with flanges or knobs to allow greater penetration of plate armour. The length of maces can vary considerably. The maces of foot soldiers were usually quite short (two or three feet, or sixty to ninety centimetres).

Events  January–June  January 18 – François, Duke of Anjou, attacks Antwerp. February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg, newly converted to Calvinism, formally marries Agnes von Mansfeld-Eisleben, a former canoness of Gerresheim, while retaining his position as Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. March 10 – The Queen Elizabeth's Men troupe of actors is ordered to be founded in England. May – Battle of Shizugatake in Japan: Shibata Katsuie is defeated by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who goes on to commence construction of Osaka Castle. May 22 – Ernest of Bavaria is elected as Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cologne, in opposition to Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus . Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection, with fever, headache, body aches, and conjunctivitis . The incubation period ranges from two to 10 days. An estimated 5–10 percent of cases will have symptoms that progress to more severe illnesses or death.Dengue is spread through direct contact with blood and bodily fluid from an infected person or animal; saliva and tears are common carriers.In addition to humans, this disease is transmitted by birds, mosquitoes, ticks, and other arthropods, including fleas and sand flies.

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Year 1355 (MCCCLV) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 6 – Charles IV of Bohemia is crowned with the Iron Crown of Lombardy as King of Italy in Milan. January 7 – King Alphonso IV of Portugal sends three men who kill Inês de Castro, beloved of his son Peter, who revolts and incites a civil war. February 10 – St Scholastica Day riot in Oxford, England, breaks out, leaving 63 scholars and perhaps 30 locals dead in two days.

In geometry, two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size, or if one has the same shape and size as the mirror image of the other.More formally, two sets of  points are called congruent if, and only if, one can be transformed into the other by an isometry, i.e., a combination of rigid motions, namely a translation, a rotation, and a reflection. This means that either object can be repositioned and reflected (but not resized) so as to coincide precisely with the other object.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken ( June 7 , 1896 – October 31 , 1986 ) was an American physicist and chemist. He is considered by many as one of the fathers of string theory, and he also developed quantum mechanics and electromagnetism during his career.He received his doctorate from the University of Minnesota in 1942, then returned to the University of Chicago after World War II for a number of years.From 1948 to 1952 he was Associate Professor of Mathematics at the University of Chicago. His most famous contribution was the development of the first general-relativity theory that incorporated Einstein's theory of special and general relativity in its equations.

Year 1301 ( MCCCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian Calendar. It was traditionally counted from the day after Easter to the day after Whitsunday and is now used as a base for years with more than one day.The name "MCCCI" was also used as a nickname for the Gregorian Calendar during its early use. A macron ( , plural macrons) is a straight unit of length used in many different areas of mathematics. Its name derives from its shape: A macron is always a whole number larger than two.

Year 1145 ( MCXLV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of 9 March 1247. It marked the start of Queen Mary I's rule over England and Scotland, which lasted for the first half of the 13th century. The Civil War (also known as the Revolutionary War or the War Between the States) was a series of civil disturbances in the United States after the conclusion of the American Revolution, which resulted in the adoption of the Constitution of the United States on 14 May 1777 by the newly established United States of America.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.

Year 1474 (MCDLXXIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  February – The Treaty of Utrecht puts an end to the Anglo-Hanseatic War. March 19 – The Senate of the Republic of Venice enacts the Venetian Patent Statute, one of the earliest patent systems in the world. New and inventive devices, once put into practice, have to be communicated to the Republic to obtain the right to prevent others from using them. This is considered the first modern patent system.

Events January–June January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England . It is known as the 'Royal African Company', which is used in later annals. Arthur Conan Doyle, or Arthur Conan Doyle Jr (; , ; 9 April 1892 – 26 November 1965),  was an English author, journalist and biographer. As a popular science writer throughout his career, he published widely in short stories, novellas, novels, and short story collections. His work has influenced writers such as Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, Jules Verne, Aldous Huxley, Isaac Asimov, and Raymond Chandler.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe . It was published by Sierra from 1990 to 1993 and continued until its cancellation on April 30, 1994. [1]The first two installments of the series, Larry's Big Sports Adventure and Larry's Pool Buddies, were produced in 1990 and 1992 respectively. The first game was released on August 30, 1990, while the other games were released a month later.Sierra initially considered several possible sequels but ultimately rejected any attempt to include a third installment before the end of their tenure.

Events January–June January 7 – The Westminster Assembly begins debating the biblical proof texts , to support the new Confession of Faith as the official document of the church. February 17 – The Synod of Orange convenes for the purpose of confirming the Catholic Church's stance on papal authority; it does so by reaffirming that the Roman Pontiff may not interpret scripture in such a way as to interfere with the teachings of Jesus' apostles. Cheryl Mills was an American actress, singer and model. She was born on October 15, 1934 in Los Angeles, California.

A horoscope ( or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart , astrological chart , and celsus ) tells you a person's current stage of life and where they should go. It may also be used as part of a medical diagnosis, to find out more about someone's illnesses or injuries, or to find out what is good for them. Hippocampus (;  Latin: habens) is a structure in both animals and plants that acts as a storage and retrieval centre for long-term memories. The hippocampus, along with other areas in the brain, is responsible for short-term memory.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

Events  January–December  February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna, ending the da Polenta Dynasty. February 12 – King's College, Cambridge, is founded by King Henry VI of England. March 1 – Battle of Samobor: The army of Ulrich II, Count of Celje, defeats the army of Stjepan Banić at Samobor, Croatia in union with Hungary. November 10 – Alfonso V of Aragon lays siege to Naples. November 20 – The Peace of Cremona (1441) ends the war between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan.

Year 1409 (MCDIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Welsh surrender Harlech Castle to the English. March 25 – The Council of Pisa opens. On June 5 it deposes Pope Gregory XII and Antipope Benedict XIII, and on June 26 crowns Petros Philargos as Pope Alexander V; he is subsequently regarded as an antipope. July – Martin I of Aragon succeeds his own son, as King of Sicily. August 7 – The Council of Pisa closes. December 2 – The University of Leipzig opens.

Events  January–June  January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim: The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg. January 29 – John Sassamon, an English-educated Native American Christian, dies at Assawampsett Pond, an event which will trigger a year-long war between the English American colonists of New England, and the Algonquian Native American tribes. March 30 – The guild organisation Maîtresses couturières is founded in Paris. April – English merchant Anthony de la Roché, blown off course after rounding Cape Horn eastabout, makes the first discovery of land south of the Antarctic Convergence, landing on South Georgia and (probably) Gough Island.

Events  January–June  January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland, replacing the Book of Common Prayer (1559). Holy Days (other than Sundays) are not to be observed. January 10 – Archbishop of Canterbury William Laud is executed for treason on Tower Hill, London. January 14 – English Civil War: Fairfax is appointed Commander-in-Chief. January 29 – English Civil War: Armistice talks open at Uxbridge. February 2 – Battle of Inverlochy: The Covenanters are defeated by Montrose.

Greyhound racing is an organized , competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track . There are two main classes of race: Greyhounds and Shepherds, and both are governed by the racing industry. The breed is recognised by the Kennel Club of Australia (KCA) and the Greyhound Racing Association (GRA), but there is no central body to administer the sport. John Paul Jones III (January 29, 1944 – January 19, 2011; April 18, 2012) was a US marine who served in World War II with the 101st Airborne Division of the United States Army Air Corps.

Year 1273 (MCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  January 22 – Muhammad II becomes Sultan of the Emirate of Granada after the death of his father, Muhammad I, in a riding accident. September 29 – Rudolph I of Germany is elected King of Germany over rival candidate King Otakar II of Bohemia, ending the Interregnum; Otakar refuses to acknowledge Rudolph as the new king, leading to the outbreak of war in 1276. Rudolph is the first of many Habsburgs to hold the throne.

Spiro Theodore Agnew ( November 9 , 1918 – September 17 , 1996 ) was the 39th vice president of the United States. He was the only vice president who served more years in office than did his predecessor. Agnew resigned as vice president on March 11, 1992, when President George H.W. Bush appointed him secretary of state. Al Qaeda (also referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood or the Islamic Jihad Group) is an al-Qaeda splinter group that has emerged in North Africa since the early 1990s. Al Qaeda was formerly led by Sheikh Abu Musab al-Zarqawi.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the northwest to the town of Hadley, on Cape Cod's east end. It forms part of the New England Seaboard Long-Branford Canal, also known as the Atlantic City-Middlesex Canal. Its design was modified in 1885 to improve safety and reduce construction costs, which had already reached $4 million. The Chateau D'Antibes  is a 13th-century castle and fortress in the French Alps, located near the town of Chateau-du-Rôtie.It was built during the early 11th century under the protection of the Counts d'Antibes from the Knights Templars of the Crusades.

OS-9 is a family of real-time, process-based, multitasking, multi-user operating systems, developed in the 1980s, originally by Microware Systems Corporation for the Motorola 6809 microprocessor. It was purchased by Radisys Corp in 2001, and was purchased again in 2013 by its current owner Microware LP.The OS-9 family was popular for general-purpose computing and remains in use in commercial embedded systems and amongst hobbyists. Today, OS-9 is a product name used by both a Motorola 68000-series machine language OS and a portable (PowerPC, x86, ARM, MIPS, SH4, etc.)

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis from a specially designed curved ramp. Along with jump length, competitor's aerial style and other factors also affect the final score. Ski jumping was first contested in Norway in the late 19th century, and later spread through Europe and North America in the early 20th century. Along with cross-country skiing, it constitutes the traditional group of Nordic skiing disciplines.The ski jumping venue, commonly referred to as a hill, consists of the jumping ramp (in-run), take-off table, and a landing hill.

Palermo ( , ; , locally also or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy located on the Gulf of Naples, south of Venice and north-east of Milan. It is the provincial capital of the Ligurian Principality of Piedmont and the largest city in Sicilia. It is a major center of the Mediterranean Sea trade route and has a large port, which was the first to be built for Italian shipping in Europe, serving as the base for the trans-Sicilian steamship trade with the rest of Europe.HistoryThe oldest inhabitants of the city were the Carthaginians, who lived here between the fifth and fourth centuries BC.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye ,  (literally, `play of') and the Latin quæstionum which means ``playhouse''. More specifically, the term refers to a dwelling or space used as a stage for performances. It is also used in other cultures, such as Ancient Greek, Latin, and Chinese to refer to an area where performers take part in plays. Dietary fats (FAs) are lipid hydrocarbons found in plant and animal tissues. The structural formula of a FAs is C7H14N6O4 .

Frederick Barbarossa (1122 – 10 June 1190), also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 until his death 35 years later. He was elected King of Germany at Frankfurt on 4 March 1152 and crowned in Aachen on 9 March 1152. He was crowned King of Italy on 24 April 1155 in Pavia and emperor by Pope Adrian IV on 18 June 1155 in Rome. Two years later, the term  ("holy") first appeared in a document in connection with his empire. He was later formally crowned King of Burgundy, at Arles on 30 June 1178.

Year 1527 (MDXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June January 1 – Croatian nobles elect Ferdinand I of Austria as King of Croatia in the Parliament on Cetin. January 5 – Felix Manz, co-founder of the Swiss Anabaptists, is drowned in the Limmat in Zürich by the Zürich Reformed state church. March 17 – Battle of Khanwa: Babur defeats Rajput ruler Rana Sanga. This and two other major Moghul victories lead to their domination of northern India. Dhaulpur fort is taken by Babur.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

`` Coven '' usually refers to a group or gathering of witches . The word `` coven '' ( from the Latin cunnus, meaning "fool") has been used in England and America as well as Scotland and Australia for several centuries.Covens are traditionally established within a community, but it is often a voluntary organization. Cork City Council (; ) is the regional government governing Cork City, Ireland. It comprises 13 council boroughs and two town councils. The area covers the entire city of Cork city and its surrounding areas.

In computational complexity theory , PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine. Charles Darwin  (1809 – 1862), better known by his pen name Charles Babbage, was an American mathematician who pioneered the field of mechanical reproduction in the late 19th century. He made many contributions to computer science during his lifetime and died in 1862 at the age of 46.Babbage wrote a series of papers between 1856 and 1859 outlining a theoretical model of the transmission of information between machines through the use of logic gates.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus of the family Pinaceae . Pinus is the most widely cultivated and widely distributed tropical evergreen tree in the world with a high biomass and large, well-drained wood. Pioneer B-26 Mitchell (B-26) was a U.S. Army reconnaissance biplane built by United Aircraft Corporation as part of the Strategic Air Force program. It became the first combat aircraft to land on the North Sea coast of Scotland on 5 April 1943. It was designated "B-26E" at the suggestion of then-Secretary of War Henry Stimson.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate : genetic and environmental. For example, most people with severe mental retardation have been considered to have been "nurtured" rather than "self-generated". While some scientists argue that genes are the main cause of mental impairment, others say that genetics alone cannot account for this. Chromosome (;  ; IPA: [ˈkˌsʊliōm]) is an elementary building block of all living cells. It consists of DNA, which encodes nucleic acids, proteins and other chemical constituents.

Events  January–June  January – Six months into King Philip's War, Metacomet (King Philip), leader of the Algonquian tribe known as the Wampanoag, travels westward to the Mohawk nation, seeking an alliance with the Mohawks against the English colonists of New England; his efforts in creating such an alliance are a failure. January 29 – Feodor III becomes Tsar of Russia. January 31 – University of San Carlos of Guatemala, the oldest institution of higher education in Central America, was founded. February 10 – After the Nipmuc tribe attacks Lancaster, Massachusetts, colonist Mary Rowlandson is taken captive, and lives with the Indians until May.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga, which are separated geographically by the Murray River and politically by a state border: Albury on the north of the river is part of New South Wales, while Wodonga on the south bank is in Victoria.History Albury-Wodonga is located on the lands of the Dyinningmiddhang people of the Dhudhuroa language group.In the early 1970s Albury–Wodonga was selected as the primary focus of the Whitlam Federal Labor government's scheme to arrest the uncontrolled growth of Australia's large metropolitan areas (in particular Sydney and Melbourne) by encouraging decentralisation.

Year 1463 ( MCDLXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Wednesday (link will display the traditional abbreviated calendar) in Roman Catholic Western Europe. It was traditionally used to replace the Julian calendar, as well as the Gregorian calendar, which was first introduced by Pope Gregory X in 1582 and is still in use in many countries today. A cat is an exoskeletal carnivorous mammal of the order Catarrhinae, which includes all members of the family Felidae, as well as some other small mammals.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces . The basic ideas are found in many different branches of mathematics, such as vector calculus and combinatorics. In physics, a scalar field is a physical property of a material (usually solid). In this article, we define a scalar field using the concept of a "tensor". We will now discuss the different types of torsions that we can describe. A quantum theory  is a description of how the microscopic universe interacts with the larger universe by describing the interactions between two or more particles.

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) for most parts of Europe, and used throughout the rest of the world in both the Julian and Gregorian Calendar. In the Northern Hemisphere, New Year's Day came on December 24th; in the Southern Hemisphere, the first Monday in March would fall on December 26th. The Church of England (C of E) is an Anglican Christian Church which is governed as an ecumenical church by the Roman Catholic Church. It is the only major branch of the Roman Catholic Church to hold its own elected diaconate.

Events January–March January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets . The Great Pyrenees (; or, ;  ) is a region in northeastern France, separating the Pyrenees mountains from the Pyrenees Peninsula. It is bounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the south, by the Pyrenees Mountains to the east, by the Alps to the north, and the Apennines to the west.Historically, it was a major trading center along with the Iberian Peninsula during the Roman and medieval eras. Today, its population is estimated to number around 2.6 million.

As of March 1 (O.S. February 19), where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, the Julian calendar fell one day further behind, bringing the difference to 11 days until February 28 (O.S. February 17), 1800.In Sweden, the year started in the Julian calendar and remained so until February 28. Then, by skipping the leap day, the Swedish calendar was introduced, letting February 28 be followed by March 1, giving the entire year the same pattern as a common year starting on Monday.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating. In competitions, multiple skaters (typically between four and six) skate on an oval ice track with a length of . The rink itself is  long by  wide, which is the same size as an Olympic-sized figure skating rink and an international-sized ice hockey rink. Related sports include long track speed skating and inline speed skating.HistoryShort-track skating developed from speed skating events that were held with mass starts. This form of speed skating was mainly practised in the United States and Canada, as opposed to the international form, where athletes skated in pairs.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets. The series originated as two pilot episodes produced by Henson for ABC in 1974 and 1975. While neither episode was moved forward as a series and other networks in the United States rejected Henson's proposals, British producer Lew Grade expressed enthusiasm for the project and agreed to co-produce The Muppet Show for the British channel  ATV. Five seasons, totalling 120 episodes, were broadcast on ATV and other ITV franchises in the United Kingdom and in later first-run syndication in the US from 1976 to 1981.

Year 1160 ( MCLX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending in Sunday ( link will display the last 12 weeks of a year ). Leap years are observed around the world by the Gregorian calendar. They are also observed as the anniversary of Christ's death on Good Friday, when He was laid to rest on the third day after his Crucifixion.The exact length of the year varies by several months, but is usually based on 365.25 days rounded up to an integer number of days.

Year 1145 (MCXLV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Seljuk forces led by Imad al-Din Zengi capture Saruj, the second great Crusader fortress east of the Euphrates. They advance to Birejik and besiege the city, but the garrison puts up a stiff resistance. Meanwhile, Queen-Regent Melisende of Jerusalem joins forces with Joscelin II, count of Edessa and approaches the city. Zengi raises the siege after hearing rumours of trouble in Mosul. He rushes back with his army to take control.

A killer is someone or something that kills, such as a murderer or a serial killer. Killer or The Killer may also refer to:Arts, entertainment, and mediaFictional characters Killer (Home and Away), a character from Home and Away Killer Kane, the villain of the 1939 Buck Rogers film serial Ghostface (Scream), aka "The Killer" - the murderer in the Scream movie seriesFilms The Killer (1921 film), an American western film directed by and starring Jack Conway (filmmaker) The Killer (1953 film), a Turkish adventure film Killer!

All figure skating events in 2002 Winter Olympics were held at the Salt Lake Ice Center.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsResultsMenMedals awarded Thursday, Jan. 9 to David Lappas for silver and Patrick McLean-McNally for bronze. David Lappas (; February 17, 1940 – December 15, 2004) was an American model, entrepreneur, philanthropist, and businessman. He is credited with revolutionizing the beauty industry in the United States and the world through his work in hair and beauty product design, advertising, and public relations. Lappas was a founding member of the California International Beauty Contest (CAIB).

Events  January–June  January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy, the millones. March – Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange, takes Breda, by concealing 68 of his best men in a peat-boat, to get through the impregnable defences. March 14 – Battle of Ivry: Henry IV of France again defeats the forces of the Catholic League, under Charles, Duke of Mayenne. May–August – Henry IV of France unsuccessfully attempts to besiege Paris. Henry is forced to raise the siege, when Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma comes to its rescue with a Spanish army.

A horoscope (or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart, astrological chart, astro-chart, celestial map, sky-map, star-chart, cosmogram, vitasphere, radical chart, radix, chart wheel or simply chart) is an astrological chart or diagram representing the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets, astrological aspects and sensitive angles at the time of an event, such as the moment of a person's birth. The word horoscope is derived from the Greek words ōra and scopos meaning "time" and "observer" (horoskopos, pl.

Year 1404 (MCDIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April or May – Battle of Blackpool Sands: Local English forces defeat an attempted raid from Saint-Malo on the port of Dartmouth, Devon; the French commander, William du Chastel, is killed. June 14 – Rebel leader Owain Glyndŵr, having declared himself Prince of Wales, allies with the French against the English. He later begins holding parliamentary assemblies. October 17 – Pope Innocent VII succeeds Pope Boniface IX, as the 204th pope.

The Duchy of Anjou (, ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire. Its capital was Angers and it was roughly coextensive with the diocese of Angers. Anjou was bordered by Brittany to the west, Maine to the north, Touraine to the east and Poitou to the south. The adjectival form is Angevin, and inhabitants of Anjou are known as Angevins. In 1482, the duchy became part of the Kingdom of France, and from then remained a province of the Kingdom under the name of the Duchy of Anjou.

Year 1361 ( MCCCLXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of every year in England and Wales until 1485.The date of Mary's birth is uncertain because, as a baby, she would have had no access to baptismal records. If she was baptised after her birthdate, she may not have been able to be officially registered as the mother of King Edward VI until 1486. The first written mention of Mary's birth appears in Henry VIII's Annales, dated November 1369. The  (also called) is the Roman Catholic Latin name for the Virgin Mary.

Year 1468 (MCDLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December June 30 – Catherine Cornaro is married by proxy to James II of Cyprus, beginning the Venetian conquest of Cyprus. August 26 – Baeda Maryam succeeds his father Zara Yaqob, as Emperor of Ethiopia. October 14 – The Treaty of Péronne is signed by Charles the Bold, Duke of Burgundy, and Louis XI of France. Date unknown  The Lancastrians surrender Harlech Castle to King Edward IV of England after a seven-year siege.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray , which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Bedwyr, three young women who are engaged to marry each other, but decide to keep their engagement secret. The novel was first published as a play in 1851, and adapted for the stage several times before its final production in 1898. It received numerous awards and accolades during its lifetime. The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)  is the broadcasting arm of the UK government, which operates over 4,000 radio and television stations in over 50 countries.

Year 990 (CMXC) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Al-Mansur, de facto ruler of Al-Andalus, conquers the Castle of Montemor-o-Velho (modern Portugal), expanding the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba. The city of Lund, Sweden is founded, during the reign of the Danish king Sweyn Forkbeard (approximate date). Africa  The Ghana Empire takes the Berber town of Aoudaghost (modern Mauritania) as the West African nation makes further gains. Construction of the Al-Hakim Mosque by orders of the Fatimid vizier Gawar Al-Siqilli begins in Cairo (modern Egypt).

Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.

1581 (MDLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) in the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Thursday (link will display full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  March 18 – The Parliament of England's Act against Reconciliation to Rome imposes heavy fines, for practising Roman Catholicism. March 25 – Iberian Union: Philip II of Spain is crowned Philip I of Portugal. April 4 – Following his circumnavigation of the world, Francis Drake is knighted by Elizabeth I of England. July–December  July 14 – English Jesuit Edmund Campion is arrested.

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater who won the 1976 Olympic 100-meter dash, the 1976 US Olympic team pursuit gold medal, the 1976 world championships, and the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles. He also won several individual sprint events and two relay gold medals. He currently serves as the director of the Sports Trauma Institute at University Hospitals for Children in Cincinnati, Ohio.Early yearsHiddink was born in East Hanover, New Jersey, the fourth of five children. Helium is a substance that is produced naturally in the Earth's crust.

Year 1290 (MCCXC) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Year without winter – Exceptionally rare instance of uninterrupted transition, from autumn 1289 to the following spring, in Great Britain and mainland western Europe. March 1 – The University of Coimbra is founded in Lisbon, Portugal by King Denis of Portugal; it moves to Coimbra in 1308. July 10 – Ladislaus IV of Hungary is assassinated by three Cumans (Árbóc, Törtel and Kemence), at the castle of Körösszeg (modern-day Cheresig) in Romania.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson ( February 13 , 1942 – February 21 , 2019 ) , known professionally as Peter Tork (born August 15, 1952) was an American voice actor and voice coach. He was a member of the popular comedy group The Carpenters from 1975 to 1996 when he left to become a stand-up comic and television host.He has also written and performed on stage since the mid-1960s.Thorkelson worked in various radio roles, most notably voicing several characters on the TV program "The Bob Newhart Show".In the 1980s, Thorkelson became interested in voice acting.

The term chat room , or chatroom ( and sometimes group chat ; abbreviated as GC ) , is primarily used to describe an area in a computer network for exchanging information. In a chat room, users participate in conversations that range over a large number of topics without restriction on who can participate. This allows for more direct communication with members of a particular group. The term originated with the early Internet and World Wide Web, and was introduced into the English lexicon by the late American computer scientist and computer game developer Bill Joy.

Year 1216(MCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  Spring – First Barons' War: The English army, led by King John (Lackland), sacks the town of Berwick-on-Tweed (or Berwick), and raids southern Scotland. John pushes up towards Edinburgh over a ten-day period. On his return, he puts down a revolt in East Anglia. On March 24, King John arrives at Hertford, to deal with the challenge of a coming French invasion.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain, situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford in Kent, south eastern England. The villa was occupied over various periods within the Romano-British period, but after its destruction, it is only thought to have been reoccupied during the Medieval Times.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics ( LASP ) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. Its mission is to develop innovative technologies that will improve the safety and efficiency of human space flight. The lab is also working to improve the ability of future humans to make long-range, deep-space trips into deep space or other places beyond our own solar system. Lithium-ion batteries are used in modern electronic devices such as cell phones, laptops, tablets and smartphones. In their simplest form, they consist of a single electrode in a metal container with a positive electrode on one side and negative electrode on the other side.

Year 1491 ( MCDXCI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the reign of John VIII of England. Beginning with the introduction of decimal fractions for years earlier than 1499, the year 1491 marked the beginning of the decimal millennium.The next leap year to become a common date was 1568. A computer program is an executable instructions or data stored by software which is designed to be executed by a computer processor. Computer programs are compiled down from source code that can be loaded into memory and executed by other computers.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name comes from Greek means "leech" (from 'propion' = "to suck") and refers to the fact that sifaks lack teeth; they have a fleshy mouthparts that feed off blood during feeding. The United Nations Development Program (UNDP), which has offices in Afghanistan, Pakistan, India, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen, provides humanitarian assistance to over 1.4 billion people globally.

The Zwinger is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden , Germany . Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann , the Zwinger was completed in 1879. Its location on the Ruhr canal is typical of many modern-style mansions. The main building is surrounded by an open-air courtyard that provides an opportunity to view the garden. Cerebellum (; also known as cerebellum or cerebellic reflex) is a group of brain structures and processes related to motor learning and coordination, language, memory, attention, executive function, reasoning, and emotions. Among the most common are the cerebellum and the hippocampus, which are both located in the cerebral hemisphere.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( ( Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov ) , , born on 27 July 1946 ) is a retired Turkish actor. He began acting professionally during the late 1960s.He has portrayed many popular roles and characters in both film and television.His most notable role was in the film Büyük Görüş (1972), which was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film of 1973. Armenian is a Turkic language spoken by approximately one million people in Turkey, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Armenia, Russia, Iran, Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, Afghanistan, Iraq, and Turkey.

Year 1567 ( MDLXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Europe. An annulus or annulet is a small semicircle of wood that is cut from a tree, and is carved into an object such as a cask or vessel. Its use has changed over time, but its most commonly employed design is to have a central cross at one end and several smaller circular arcs at the ends; it is often ornamented with beads, leaves, ornaments, or other elements.Annuls are a type of  decoration.In general, annuli are decorative pieces that decorate and serve as decorations.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Charles XII of Sweden invades Russia, by crossing the frozen Vistula River with 40,000 men. January 12 – Shahu I becomes the fifth Chhatrapati of the Maratha Empire in the Indian subcontinent. February 26 – HMS Falmouth, a 50-gun fourth-rate ship of the line built at Woolwich Dockyard for the Royal Navy, is launched. March 11 – Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.

Year 1446 ( MCDXLVI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Northern Hemisphere. The Julian calendar, which began to use this year in 1582, was used until 1753. The Chinese language is a variant of Mandarin that consists of three syllables and five vowels. The word for 'language' in English is written with a diaeresis (or circumflex), rather than a soft or hard stylus as in most other languages. As well as being an emicolony of languages, some Chinese dialects are also phonetically distinct; thus, they share some vowel patterns with other languages.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Samuel de Champlain ( ; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635 ) was a French colonist , navigator and mathematician, who served as governor of the colony of Newfoundland during the French and Indian War from 1602 until his death in 1605. He is considered to be one of the founders of the modern world of geography.Born on Saint Bartholomew's Day in Quebec, Champlain studied mathematics at the Académie des Sciences du Québec under Louis Riel. He also spent time in England studying ancient geography.Champlain became a naturalized Canadian when he arrived in the New World in 1604.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

In mathematics, a binary tree structure is a set with two or more leaves each having at most one node: a left child , and a right child . If an unordered binary tree is defined, its left-hand side is the list of all nodes whose root has children .

Year 1174 (MCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1174th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 174th year of the 2nd millennium, the 74th year of the 12th century, and the 5th year of the 1170s decade.Events  By place  England  July 13 – Battle of Alnwick: King William I (the Lion) supported by Flemish mercenaries invades England to help fight in the baronial rebellion against King Henry II. The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis. Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising seawater.CommunitiesPopulationNeolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.

January 18 – Sir James Montgomery of Scotland, who had been arrested on January 11 for conspiracy to restore King James to the throne, escapes with the aid of the two persons guarding him and flees to France, arriving in Paris on February 15. Year 1526 ( MDXXVI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and lasting until Thursday 21 February 1539. The last days of winter began at midnight, when the length of the night had been doubled, to make the day 20 hours longer than the night.In England, the new year began on 1 December 1527 with the English Parliament passing the Act of Union that created a new Holy Roman Emperor. The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC . It is named after the town of Tel Aviv, Israel, located on the coast in the eastern Mediterranean Sea. This was later renamed to Jerusalem (8th century BCE).HistoryIn 732 BCE, the city of Tel Abyad was attacked by the Assyrians for control of the region. After this, the city would become known as Tel Aharoni. The Romans conquered much of the region between 733 and 766 CE and established the province of Judea ("Israel").

Year 1335 (MCCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 2 – Otto the Merry, Duke of Austria, becomes Duke of Carinthia. December 1 – Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan dies, a victim of the plague that ravages the Ilkhanate. This is an early outbreak of the Black Death.

Year 1184 (MCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May 20 – Diet of Pentecost: Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa) organises a conference in Mainz. June 15 – Battle of Fimreite: King Sverre of Norway defeats and kills his rival, Magnus V (Erlingsson) near Fimreite. Sverre takes the throne and becomes sole ruler of Norway (until 1202).

In the performing arts , a scenario ( , ; from Italian : `` that which is pinned to the stage '') is a play or narrative in which the principal actors perform an action or situation. The title character of a scenario typically acts out the action or situation in a manner that relates it to the story, and may be accompanied by music and sound effects. Scenarios have traditionally been designed for theatrical presentations at large venues and are generally produced in two or more acts. As a group, scenarios are often performed as groups, with the main characters performing the parts of each role.

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India . It was formed by the Kottayam tribe in the 3rd century AD.It is known for its historical and cultural importance as one of the two oldest towns in India to survive the Indus River period, established around 4,900-4,700 BC, and the second oldest urban center after Pune, with a population of around 2,000. The town was famous for its kalakan, a type of ceremonial mausoleum, from the 1st century BC. Kalyani (; ), or Kalyanikana, is a Hindu spiritual and holy river in India.
