The year 1000 was also known as the Thousand and One Nights because this was the first year in which any individual could have witnessed the events of the biblical Book of Genesis.The year 1000 was the first year that all major Christian countries began using the Gregorian calendar, along with England and Northern Ireland; it took place in 998. This year was followed by several years of intercalary time.

Year 1408 (MCDVIII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 19 – Battle of Bramham Moor: A royalist army defeats the last remnants of the Percy Rebellion. September – Henry, Prince of Wales (later Henry V of England) retakes Aberystwyth from Owain Glyndŵr. September 16 – Thorstein Olafssøn marries Sigrid Bjørnsdatter in Hvalsey Church, in the last recorded event of the Norse history of Greenland. December 5 – Emir Edigu of Golden Horde reaches Moscow. December 13 – The Order of the Dragon is founded under King Sigismund of Hungary.

In computational complexity theory, PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.Formal definition If we denote by SPACE(t(n)), the set of all problems that can be solved by Turing machines using O(t(n)) space for some function t of the input size n, then we can define PSPACE formally asPSPACE is a strict superset of the set of context-sensitive languages.It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.

Year 1033 (MXXXIII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 2 – Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) holds an assembly at the Abbey of Payerne and is crowned King of Burgundy. He claims dominion over the Kingdom of Burgundy which is incorporated into the Holy Roman Empire. Treaty of Merseburg: Conrad II attends a Hoftag at Merseburg and signs an agreement with King Mieszko II. He divides Poland in three parts with Mieszko designated as supreme ruler, in exchange for Conrad's support.

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples . Foreign relations are conducted through the framework of the Intergovernmental Agreement (IA) between Albania and the United Nations in which Albania is a non-member state. At present, Albania is also a participant in the World Bank's International Finance Corporation (IFC). Albert Einstein (; ; 5 September 1897 – 28 January 1955) was an Austrian-born Jewish German-Jewish physicist and mathematician. A Nobel Laureate in Physics in 1921, he was awarded the 1922 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine "for his discovery of special relativity".

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde (born 30 November 1971) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in sprinting. He won an Olympic gold medal in 2002.BiographyVan Velde was considered the best Dutch sprinter during the early 1990s, but did not manage to win a medal in either the 1992 or 1994 Winter Olympics. The 1992 Games were particularly frustrating, as he missed a bronze medal by only one-hundredth of a second.During the late 1990s, clap skates became standard in Olympic competition. Van Velde had such difficulty adjusting to the techniques required with these new skates that he retired from skating and became a car salesman.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

Robert von Ranke Graves (24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985) was a British poet, historical novelist and critic. His father was Alfred Perceval Graves, a celebrated Irish poet and figure in the Gaelic revival; they were both Celticists and students of Irish mythology. Graves produced more than 140 works in his lifetime. His poems, his translations and innovative analysis of the Greek myths, his memoir of his early life—including his role in World War I—Good-Bye to All That, and his speculative study of poetic inspiration The White Goddess have never been out of print.

Year 1474 ( MCDLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday (link will display the abbreviated timekeeping). The Gregorian calendar is the official one used in France, Germany, Italy, Spain, Turkey, the United Kingdom, and most other western European countries.In England, it is the first Monday in April. ( , British English) is the ninth-century Roman emperor who became the first to rule over the Christians in Western Christendom, following the death of Emperor Julian in 754.

Georg Hackl ( often named : Hackl Schorsch , ; born 9 September 1966 ) is a German former luger who was the winner of 12 Tour de France titles, including two victories in the 1992 Tour. He made his Grand Tour debut in 1993 but was excluded due to a failed drugs test on the same occasion. His career ended prematurely in 1995 when he crashed out in the second stage of the 1996 Tour de France. In 2000, he was reinstated into the WorldTour.CyclingQuotes Born and raised in Munich, Hackl started racing as a junior road race cyclist in 1972.

Year 996 ( CMXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of December 6, 1897. Leap years are calculated using Gregorian Calendar. Lisbon in Portuguese means "land of freedom", or "city of freedom". The city was originally part of the Portuguese Empire until it was re-admitted as a province of France in the early 17th century. The city had long been a trading centre and a place of pilgrimage, popular with Portuguese pilgrims visiting the country. It is also the oldest settlement in Portugal, having existed from at least 100 BC.

In physics, quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy, more precisely a scalar field, postulated  as an explanation of the observation  of an accelerating rate of expansion of the universe. The first example of this scenario was proposed by Ratra and Peebles (1988). The concept was expanded to more general types of time-varying dark energy and the term "quintessence" was first introduced in a 1998 paper by Robert R. Caldwell, Rahul Dave and Paul Steinhardt. It has been proposed by some physicists to be a fifth fundamental force.

Year 1029 (MXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Prince Pandulf IV of Capua becomes the de facto ruler of southern Italy – holding Capua and Naples himself – this in support with his powerful allies Amalfi, Salerno and Benevento. Only the Duchy of Gaeta remains out of his grasp. Rainulf Drengot, head of a mercenary band of Norman knights, is approached by Duke John V of Gaeta and is persuaded to change sides. With Norman help, Duke Sergius IV recovers Naples from Capuan occupation.

Events January–March January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York , Maine , United States , were taken to the New York City-area hospital, Elmira General Hospital, by ambulance. Eugenics (from Greek  eidōs and  geōnēs , "life form") was a scientific and political movement that promoted the preservation of the genetic material of living things by breeding people who would be different in some way from everyone else. The term was first used by the German sociologist, philosopher, anthropologist, and social theorist Wilhelm Reich, who coined it in 1937.

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Wednesday, the Feast of the Assumption. It is commonly regarded as the last month of the Roman Gregorian calendar. The Julian calendar uses a 365-day year, but in modern times most years are reckoned from the end of the year 1 A.D., with one exception. The International Monetary Fund (IMF) is the United Nations agency that oversees international monetary policy. It is the executive arm of the United Nations, which it serves as an independent intergovernmental organization.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and entrepreneur who designed and built key technologies for the United States nuclear weapons program in the 1950s. He is generally credited with discovering radioactivity and its practical applications.Lawrence was born into a prominent naval family. He was one of five children of Robert Lawrence and Elisabeth A. Ethel Lawrence.Early LifeAs a boy, Ernest Lawrence was raised by his great-uncle, Charles W. Lawrence. After he graduated high school, he received an offer to go to the University of Iowa, where he majored in physics.

Margaret (, ; March or April 1283 – September 1290), known as the Maid of Norway, was the queen-designate of Scotland from 1286 until her death. As she was never inaugurated, her status as monarch is uncertain and has been debated by historians.Margaret was the daughter of King Eric II of Norway and Margaret of Scotland. By the end of the reign of her maternal grandfather, King Alexander III of Scotland, she was his only surviving descendant and recognized heir presumptive. Alexander III died in 1286, his posthumous child was stillborn, and Margaret inherited the crown.

Year 1401 (MCDI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Rupert, King of Germany, is crowned King of the Romans at Cologne. March 2 – William Sawtrey, a Lollard, is the first person to be burned at the stake at Smithfield, London. March 13 – The Samogitians, supported by Grand Duke Vytautas of Lithuania, rebel against the Teutonic knights and burn two castles. Vytautas is granted increased autonomy by King Jogaila of the Poland–Lithuania union. March 17 – Turko-Mongol emperor Timur sacks Damascus.

Year 1391 ( MCCCXCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display full calendar ) of the year 1396 AD. In English history, the year 1492 is the last year of the Hundred Years War between England and Scotland, in which King James I's father, Queen Mary, took part. In some documents, the date 1492 has been placed at the beginning of the War of the Roses, although this is not consistent with the other dates.1492 was the last year of the Anglo-French war of independence, which had lasted roughly from 1066 to 1189.

Year 1378 (MCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, visits his nephew Charles V of France in Paris, to celebrate publicly the friendship between their two nations. January 13 – Balša II succeeds his brother, Durađ I, as ruler of Lower Zeta (modern-day Montenegro). March – In England, John Wycliffe tries to promote his ideas for Catholic reform by laying his theses before Parliament, and making them public in a tract.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry of fortifications, especially walls.Modern battering rams are much more sophisticated and effective than earlier versions, although they still need a battering ram to penetrate hardened walls. They have been used since ancient times for defensive purposes, such as when fighting off attackers during siege warfare. Their most recent usage began with the introduction of the Chinese Siege Engine (CSE).Battering rams were developed during the late 19th century by French engineer Pierre de Brouwer and his German student Hermann Zink.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating . In competitions , multiple skaters ( typically between one to nine ) compete in an event that they are called " the Short-track Speed Skating competition ", or simply short-track speed skating, and are divided into groups based on their respective skill levels. The science fiction writer Isaac Asimov famously coined the term "the Big Bang" to refer to the origin of the universe, for the first time positing a starting point which was so unimaginably massive that space would have become empty at its core.

Sigismund ( 26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496 ) , a member of the House of Habsburg , was one of those most prominent figures in the life of Ludwig II of Bavaria. In the mid-1390s, he was the governor of the Papal States, and at the time of his brother's coronation as King of Italy in 1412, he was the second most powerful politician in Europe after Philip IV of Spain. Sir Isaac Newton  (November 29, 1542 – May 22, 1643) was an English philosopher, mathematician, scientist, and mathematician.

Year 1529 (MDXXIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 2 – The Örebro Synod provides the theological foundation of the Swedish Reformation, following the economic foundation of it, after the Reduction of Gustav I of Sweden. March –  Battle of Shimbra Kure: Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, with 200 men armed with matchlocks, defeats the army of Dawit II, Emperor of Ethiopia. March 25 – Blood libel against the Jewish community of Bosen (formerly in Hungary, today in Slovakia), on the first day of Passover.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola, released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It fixes several small flaws in the 68000, and adds a few features.The 68010 is pin-compatible with the 68000, but is not 100% software compatible. Some of the differences were: The MOVE from SR instruction is now privileged (it may only be executed in supervisor mode). This means that the 68010 meets Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements. Because the 68000 offers an unprivileged MOVE from SR, it does not meet them.

Year 1298 (MCCXCVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAsia August 28 – Emperor Go-Fushimi succeeds Emperor Fushimi on the throne of Japan. John Tarchaneiotes is appointed governor of the southern portions of Byzantine Anatolia.Europe April 20 – Rintfleisch-Pogrom: The Jews of Röttingen are burned en masse; other Jewish communities are destroyed later in the year. June 1 – Battle of Turaida: Residents of Riga and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania defeat the Livonian Order. July 2 – Battle of Göllheim: Albert I of Habsburg defeats and kills Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg.

Events  January–June  March – The Synod of Jerusalem brings together bishops and representatives from the whole of Eastern Orthodox Christendom, to discuss Orthodox dogma against the challenge of Protestantism. March 15 – Charles II of England issues the Royal Declaration of Indulgence, suspending execution of Penal Laws against Protestant nonconformists and Roman Catholics in his realms; this will be withdrawn the following year under pressure from the Parliament of England. March 17 – Third Anglo-Dutch War: The Kingdom of England declares war on the Dutch Republic. April 8 – France declares war on the Dutch Republic, invading the country on April 29.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken  (June 7, 1896 – October 31, 1986) was an American physicist and chemist, primarily responsible for the early development of molecular orbital theory, i.e. the elaboration of the molecular orbital method of computing the structure of molecules. Mulliken received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 and the Priestley Medal in 1983.Early yearsRobert Mulliken was born in Newburyport, Massachusetts. His father, Samuel Parsons Mulliken, was a professor of organic chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. As a child, Robert Mulliken learned the name and botanical classification of plants and, in general, had an excellent, but selective, memory.

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov ( ; – 10 March 1940 ) was a Russian writer , medical doctor , and playwright . In the late 1940s and early 1950s he lived in Moscow. His work is regarded as among the finest examples of nineteenth-century Russian literature.BiographyEarly lifeAs a child, Bulgakov spent most of his days reading and taking part in theater. When he grew up, his family moved from the city to Leningrad, where he continued his artistic and literary pursuits. The Bulgarian National Army (BNA) is one of the five main military forces of Bulgaria.

Year 1434 (MCDXXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The foundation stone of Nantes Cathedral in Nantes, France, is laid. May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

Year 1439 (MCDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 4 – Battle of Grotnik: Władysław III's royal army defeats the Hussite movement in Poland. June 29 – Date of Venerable Macarius' Miracle of the Moose, according to Russian hagiographers. July 6 – Pope Eugene IV issues the Bull of Union with the Greeks, proclaiming the end of the East–West Schism, which was repudiated by most eastern bishops shortly thereafter. September 8 – Cardinal Giovanni Vitelleschi captures Foligno, ending Trinci's signoria.

Botulinum toxin ( BoNT ) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species . It is the toxin in the most commonly used botulism treatment regimens, but its pathogenesis is unknown. The toxin acts on both nerve cells and muscle cells in the central nervous system.BoNT can kill by causing tissue destruction, or by interfering with the functioning of the cell. There are several ways it can be induced in humans. One method involves the application of high concentrations of an antiseptic solution to the skin, although the precise mechanism is not fully understood.

Events  January–December  February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed. April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of Denmark. April – Murad II lays siege to Belgrade. The city is heavily damaged, but the defenders' use of artillery prevents the Turks from capturing the city. September 13 – Breton knight Gilles de Rais is taken into custody, upon an accusation brought against him by the Bishop of Nantes. September – The term of Regent of Sweden Karl Knutsson Bonde ends, as newly elected king of Denmark Christopher of Bavaria is also elected king of Sweden.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. Its basic idea is that people are capable of achieving happiness through their individual actions and attitudes. However, it does not include ethics, which would have been an important topic to address in the philosophical tradition.The word "cure" derives from the root curethes (Greek: ἡδετής), which can also mean "recover or restore". Edgar Allen Poe  (; October 26, 1809 – April 20, 1936) was an American poet, essayist, novelist, journalist, and playwright.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. The twelfth tropical cyclone and eleventh named storm of the well below-average 2013 Atlantic hurricane season, Karen originated from a tropical wave that departed from the west coast of Africa on September 16. After passing south of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands, the storm became a tropical cyclone to the northeast of the Yucatán Peninsula. The storm peaked shortly afterward, with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (100 km/h).

Year 1317 (MCCCXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  December  December 10–11 – King Birger of Sweden has his brothers, Dukes Eric and Valdemar, captured and thrown into a dungeon during the Nyköping Banquet, as a revenge for their imprisonment of him in the Håtuna games in 1306. As the dukes soon starve to death in the dungeon, their followers rebel against the king, throwing Sweden into civil war, in which the king is deposed in 1318. Date unknown  The Great Famine of 1315-1317 comes to an end.

Year 1527 ( MDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, the 21st of October, marking the beginning of Lent. It is commonly considered to be the most sacred day of the year in Catholic Christian liturgy, being celebrated by the faithful as a commemoration of Christ's crucifixion and Resurrection.HistorySabbaths in ancient Jewish law were typically counted once per year, usually after the Jews had completed the Passover. The custom became popular in early Christianity, and it is also mentioned in the New Testament.

Year 1486 ( MCDLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full Julian calendar, see Calendar page for further details). It is the most common year of the Gregorian calendar; other years have their dates slightly later in the month. Korea (사이도; "Land of the Shining Mountains"), or Korea (제프; "Rising Sun") as well as Korean-speaking peoples, is a country in North East Asia comprising the Republic of Korea and North Korea. It is one of the six member states of the South-South Cooperation Council.

Greyhound racing is an organized, competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track. There are two forms of greyhound racing, track racing (normally around an oval track) and coursing, the latter is now banned in most countries. Track racing uses an artificial lure (usually a form of windsock) that travels ahead of the greyhounds on a rail until the greyhounds cross the finish line. As with horse racing, greyhound races often allow the public to bet on the outcome.In many countries greyhound racing is purely amateur and solely for enjoyment.

McLean Hospital ( formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum ) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont , Massachusetts, United States. It is the oldest of the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs facilities and the largest state-operated health care provider in Massachusetts. Its primary purpose is treatment of mental disorders. It also serves as a teaching hospital.The hospital's history stretches back to 1882, when an outbreak of influenza broke out among soldiers suffering from trench fever. Over the years, it has been the site for many different military medical experiments. In the 1960s, the building was renovated and expanded to house a new psychiatric unit.

Year 1529 ( MDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar, used by most European countries.It was also used in some areas as a "holiday" during which many public celebrations were held. However, it was rarely used beyond the borders of its traditional area.The date for the 16th day of the first month (January 1) was not selected until the late 16th century by Pope Leo IX, who wanted to have the feast of the Nativity of the Holy Virgin Mary on the same day as the Easter celebration that marked the end of Passover.

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814 , with the formation of the German Confederation. The Kingdom of Liechtenstein was formally established on 19 August 834 as an autonomous principality under the administration of the Grand Prince and Queen of Württemberg, who had already succeeded his brother Otto as Duke of Saxony. Liechtenstein is an independent kingdom of Germany, a member of the European Community and a member of the NATO collective defence system. It is located in the middle of the Baltic Sea, north-west of Germany. It has no land borders with neighboring countries.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive , Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed until 1989, when it was sold to Microsoft as part of its Windows 3.0 license agreement with the company. Microsystems (founded by Ken Thompson, Paul Allen and Steve Jobs), also known as Microcomputer Systems or Microsoft, was a semiconductor and integrated circuit design firm founded by Bill Gates and Steve Jobs. It was founded on August 26, 1976, at the University of Washington, which was later renamed Seattle University. In 1982, Microsoft purchased the company for US$2.1 billion.

Acetic acid bacteria (AAB) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid during fermentation. The acetic acid bacteria consist of 10 genera in the family Acetobacteraceae. Several species of acetic acid bacteria are used in industry for production of certain foods and chemicals.DescriptionAll acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes. Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature. They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars. They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one gets a difference quotient. The approximation of derivatives by finite differences plays a central role in finite difference methods for the numerical solution of differential equations, especially boundary value problems.The difference operator, commonly denoted  is the operator that maps a function  to the function  defined byA difference equation is a functional equation that involves the finite difference operator in the same way as a differential equation involves derivatives. There are many similarities between difference equations and differential equations, specially in the solving methods.

Year 1131 (MCXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  August 21 – King Baldwin II falls seriously ill, after his return from Antioch. He is moved to the patriarch's residence near the Holy Sepulchre, where he bequeaths the kingdom to his daughter Melisende, her husband Fulk and their infant son, Baldwin. He takes monastic vows, and dies soon after. Baldwin is buried in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, at Jerusalem.

Roger Williams ( 21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683 ) was a Puritan minister , theologian , chemist, lawyer, mathematician and physicist in the seventeenth-century United Provinces of New Netherland and South Holland.Early lifeWilliams was born in the village of Leyden in the Dutch county of Zwolle on the borders of present-day Namur, the same area where William Shakespeare's father had settled his family. His early education was interrupted by an illness. He was educated at the University of Amsterdam, where he graduated as a law student in 1616.

1166 ( MCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Christian era. It was the seventh year after the Gregorian date 12 March 1453. The Gregorian calendar was introduced in 1582 as part of Pope Gregory XI's reform program to improve the accuracy of calendars by moving the leap years from 360 to 366 and adding several months of extra days each year. The Golden Dawn, formerly known as the Golden Dawn Order or Golden Dawn International, is an esoteric occult cult based in Scotland that originated in England.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene, outsider, wild human, an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. Besides appearing in many works of fiction and philosophy, the stereotype was also heavily employed in early anthropological works.In English, the phrase first appeared in the 17th century in John Dryden's heroic play The Conquest of Granada (1672), wherein it was used in reference to newly created man. "Savage" at that time could mean "wild beast" as well as "wild man".

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate: environment (nurture) and genetics (nature). The alliterative expression "nature and nurture" in English has been in use since at least the Elizabethan period and goes back to medieval French.The complementary combination of the two concepts is an ancient concept . Nature is what people think of as pre-wiring and is influenced by genetic inheritance and other biological factors. Nurture is generally taken as the influence of external factors after conception e.g.

Year 1370 ( MCCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Western Europe and North America. Algebra (Latin: algōs , or  Latin:  algo sī , Latin:   alchēs ), also called elementary geometry, is one of the branches of mathematics and related to trigonometry, calculus, and mechanics. It deals with relationships between groups of different types, their algebraic operations, and geometric constructions such as conics and spheres. Algebra consists of two fundamental topics—the theory of groups and the theory of equations.

Year 1390 (MCCCXC) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – The Treaty of Lyck confirms an alliance between Vytautas and the Teutonic Knights, in the Lithuanian Civil War against Vytautas's cousin, Jogaila. April 14 – John VII Palaiologos overthrows his grandfather, John V Palaiologos, as Byzantine Emperor. April 19 – Robert III succeeds his father, Robert II, as King of Scotland. May 26 – Lithuanian Civil War: The Treaty of Königsberg is signed in Königsberg, between Samogitian nobles and representatives of the Teutonic Knights.

Year 1310 (MCCCX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January –  Forces of the Kingdom of Castile retreat from the Siege of Algeciras, after enduring severe losses, and secure a peace treaty. March – Muhammed III, former Sultan of the Emirate of Granada, is blinded and found dead in a pool, after an attempted coup to retake his throne from his brother Nasr. May 11 – In France, 54 members of the Knights Templar are burned at the stake for heresy.Date unknown  Abu al-Fida becomes governor of Hama.

Year 1516 ( MDXVI ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar in use across Europe, North and South America and Australia.The Julian Calendar, named after 12th-century astronomer and mathematician John Jannatus, is an alternative method of computing years based on lunar cycles. The Department of Finance (DoF) administers all aspects of Ireland's economy, primarily through two bodies: the Minister for Finance and the DoF Secretariat. The DoF provides the central authority for Irish government policy, including monetary policy, taxation, social welfare, foreign affairs, public administration and defence.

Events  January–June  February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary, Queen of Scots, after Mary has been implicated in a plot to murder Elizabeth. Seven days later, on the orders of Elizabeth's privy council, Mary is beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle. February 12–24 – Period of exceptionally severe cold in western Europe. April 29 – Singeing the King of Spain's Beard: On an expedition against Spain, English privateer Sir Francis Drake leads a raid in the Bay of Cádiz, sinking at least 23 ships of the Spanish fleet.

Year 1235 ( MCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday, December 31, 1235 AD.It is the second-longest day of the year, being 365.25 days long, and has 366 days to an annulo-decade, making it among the longest calendars of the last two millennia.The year 1235 AD is one of the oldest in the Gregorian Julian calendar. It is also known by the abbreviation AEDH (Ancient and Early Christian Heresy) or simply AED, the English initials of the Latin alphabet with a Roman numeral after it.

Aloysius Lilius (c. 1510 – 1576), also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio, Luigi Giglio, was an Italian doctor, astronomer, philosopher and chronologist, and also the "primary author" who provided the proposal that (after modifications) became the basis of the Gregorian Calendar reform of 1582.The crater Lilius on the Moon is named after him, as is the asteroid 2346 Lilio. In computer science, the Lilian date is the number of days since the adoption of the Gregorian calendar on 15 October 1582.Life and workNot much is known about the early life of Lilius/Lilio/Giglio.

English Renaissance theatre, also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre, refers to the theatre of England between 1558 and 1642.This is the style of the plays of William Shakespeare, Christopher Marlowe and Ben Jonson.BackgroundThe term English Renaissance theatre encompasses the period between 1562—following a performance of Gorboduc, the first English play using blank verse, at the Inner Temple during the Christmas season of 1561—and the ban on theatrical plays enacted by the English Parliament in 1642.The phrase Elizabethan theatre is sometimes improperly used to mean English Renaissance theatre, although in a strict sense "Elizabethan" only refers to the period of Queen Elizabeth's reign (1558–1603).

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml ) is a general-purpose , multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of OCaml, using its standard type system for representing objects, classes, and protocols. The language was developed by Andrzej Sapkowski from 1978 to 1984, and is published under an Open Source license. It is one of the core languages in the OCaml ecosystem, along with ML and Haskell . An audio synthesizer is a digital synthesis device that can be used as a standalone sound generator or used to produce a wide variety of different tones.

Frederick II of Brandenburg  (19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471), nicknamed "the Iron" (der Eiserne) and sometimes "Irontooth" (Eisenzahn), was a Prince-elector of the Margraviate of Brandenburg from 1440 until his abdication in 1470, and was a member of the House of Hohenzollern.BiographyFrederick II was born at Tangermünde Castle (German: Burg Tangermünde), when Tangermünde was within the Margraviate of Brandenburg, to Frederick I, Brandenburg's first Hohenzollern ruler, and his wife Elizabeth, daughter of Frederick, Duke of Bavaria-Landshut, and Maddalena Visconti.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday 12 January 1453. It is also called the Gregorian feast of the Baptism of the Holy Cross, as it took place in the year before the canonisation of St Peter and St Paul by Pope Gregory XIII in 1453. The feast was named to honour the saint whose birth it coincided with.This feast is the seventh in a series known as the Seven Days of Christmas.The feast is commonly celebrated on Christmas Eve, usually during the week after Christmas, although some celebrate it earlier or later.

John Bunyan (; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress, which also became an influential literary model. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons.Bunyan came from the village of Elstow, near Bedford. He had some schooling and at the age of sixteen joined the Parliamentary Army during the first stage of the English Civil War. After three years in the  army he returned to Elstow and took up the trade of tinker, which he had learned from his father.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. February 7 – Edward of Caernarvon (later King Edward II of England) becomes the first Prince of Wales. March 3 – Emperor Go-Nijō succeeds Emperor Go-Fushimi on the throne of Japan.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

Events January–March January 17 – Tuscarora War : Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County , North Carolina, after a series of attacks by the Creeks and Tugaloo Indians on their settlements in Cumberland County . A bloody battle is fought near the town of Monterey. The Book of Mormon is a book of Latter-day Saint scripture and religious beliefs. It was first written in 1830 as an apologetic for the Christian religion. The Book of Mormon, often referred to as the "Book of Mormon" or "New Testament", is one of the five sacred scriptures of the LDS Church.

Year 1383 ( MCCCLXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman calendar. Anabaptist movement is an evangelical Protestant religious movement among American Christians led by the Reformed Baptist pastor John MacArthur.The movement originated in the 1970s, when it coalesced around the charismatic preacher Billy Graham, who helped spread the word that the Bible was God's message to humankind. In the early 2000s, this movement gained new adherents in Africa, Europe, the United States, and Asia, with a strong emphasis on evangelism.

Mary Virginia Martin ( December 1 , 1913 – November 3 , 1990 ) was an American actress and singer. In the 1970s, she was widely considered one of the greatest vocalists in the United States, winning three Grammy Awards for Best Pop Vocal Album and four for Best Female Vocalist. A pioneer of the "girl power" movement, she was often compared to the late country music icon Patsy Cline.Early lifeCynthia Elizabeth Martin was born to a wealthy white family in Richmond, Virginia, but her family's fortunes did not last.

The Hubble Space Telescope (often referred to as HST or Hubble) is a space telescope that was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990  and remains in operation. It was not the first space telescope, but it is one of the largest and most versatile, renowned both as a vital research tool and as a public relations boon for astronomy. The Hubble telescope is named after astronomer Edwin Hubble and is one of NASA's Great Observatories, along with the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory (1991–2000), the Chandra X-ray Observatory (1999–present), and the Spitzer Space Telescope (2003–2020).

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

Year 1208 (MCCVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place  Asia  April 15 – A fire breaks out in the Song Chinese capital city of Hangzhou, raging for four days and nights, destroying 58,097 houses over an area of more than , killing 59 people, and an unrecorded number of other people, who are trampled while attempting to flee. The government provides temporary lodging for 5,345 people, in nearby Buddhist and Taoist monasteries. The collective victims of the disaster are given 160,000 strings of cash, along with 400 tons of rice.

Year 1271 (MCCLXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 2 – Kings Otakar II of Bohemia and Stephen V of Hungary sign the first Peace of Pressburg, settling territorial claims, following the failed invasion of Hungary by Otakar II. September 1 – Pope Gregory X succeeds Pope Clement IV as the 184th pope, as the compromise candidate between French and Italian cardinals, ending a three-year conclave, the longest ever. The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

Events March 18 – Jacques de Molay , the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar , is murdered in his Paris home during the early morning hours. Jacques Baudoin (; 27 September 1759 – 12 December 1799) was a French poet, critic and author. He was the author of more than fifty books, some of them best-known works, such as Le Voyageur du monde ouvrages (1774), La Tour d'Thebes (1775), et l'Eau de Beaumont (1776) and Le Voyage des Îles du Régiment (1777).Baudoin's poetic output is generally divided into two eras: pre-revolutionary and post-revolutionary.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States , and is located halfway between the ``New England coast'' and Cape Cod Bay . It is bordered on one side by Cambridge, Massachusetts to the south, and Worcester, Massachusetts to the north. George Washington  (; December 28, 1797 – April 25, 1809) was the seventh President of the United States and the 19th Commander-in-Chief of the Continental Navy. He served as Secretary of State from February 4, 1793, to January 1, 1794. He was born in Yorktown, Virginia and was the son of George Washington and Martha Washington.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, a set that has at least two elements with different real values—there can be open sets whose members have the same interval. For example, if the interval [1, 2] is open, and there is an open subset of the interval [2, 1), then there exists an open subset of (which is not necessarily distinct) that is also open. The Bible is a collection of books written between the 7th and 11th centuries B.C.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East, spanning modern-day Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Palestine, Israel, Jordan, and Northern Egypt, together with the northern region of Kuwait, southeastern region of Turkey and the western portion of Iran. Some authors also include Cyprus.The region is one of the cradles of civilization because it is one location where settled farming first emerged as people started the process of clearance and modification of natural vegetation to grow newly domesticated plants as crops. Early human civilizations such as Sumer in Mesopotamia flourished as a result.

Wenceslaus IV (also Wenceslas; ; , nicknamed "the Idle"; 26 February 136116 August 1419), also known as Wenceslaus of Luxembourg, was King of Bohemia from 1378 until his death and King of Germany from 1376 until he was deposed in 1400. As  he belonged to the House of Luxembourg, he was also Duke of Luxembourg from 1383 to 1388.BiographyWenceslaus was born in the Imperial city of Nuremberg, the son of Emperor Charles IV by his third wife Anna von Schweidnitz, a scion of the Silesian Piasts, and baptized at St. Sebaldus Church.

In category theory, a branch of mathematics, the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of universal constructions such as products, pullbacks and inverse limits. The dual notion of a colimit generalizes constructions such as disjoint unions, direct sums, coproducts, pushouts and direct limits.Limits and colimits, like the strongly related notions of universal properties and adjoint functors, exist at a high level of abstraction. In order to understand them, it is helpful to first study the specific examples these concepts are meant to generalize.Definition Limits and colimits in a category  are defined by means of diagrams in .

Events  January–March  January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York, Maine, United States, are killed in the Candlemas Massacre, carried out by French soldiers led by missionary Louis-Pierre Thury, along with a larger force of Abenaki and Penobscot Indians under the command of Penobscot Chief Madockawando during King William's War, between the French colonists and their indigenous allies, against the English colonists. At least 112 English survivors are captured and taken from the Maine District of the  Province of Massachusetts Bay and forced to walk to French Canada, where they are held until Massachusetts captain John Alden pays a ransom.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human. In the modern western sense, an "outlaw" is any person or group that engages in unlawful activity, such as armed robbery or vandalism. Arthur C. Clarke (born August 16, 1943) is an American author and science fiction writer. He is best known as the author of two seminal works of science fiction, 2001: A Space Odyssey and 2010: Odyssey Three. He is one of the few writers to have written more novels than screenplays, having published twenty-seven novels.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

Year 1035 ( MXXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the reign of Philip II of France.The year has six months, which are followed by eleven days of non-consecutive weeks and two days of double days.The twelve months are in the Gregorian calendar.The 12 months of the year generally correspond to the lunar cycle; however, there is one exception, when the months of the year overlap. In this case, the start of the new year may occur on either the first or second day of the previously observed month.

EventsJanuary–March January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar , son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb , initiates a civil war in Iran that results in the expulsion of the Abbasid Caliph Abd al-Malik (1523–1536) for refusing to renounce his Islamic rule. Korea (;  ) is a country in the Republic of Korea and the constituent unit of the Socialist Federation of Korea. It has a population of approximately 5.5 million and is divided into two areas: North Korea and South Korea. Korea is bordered to the south by China and to the east by Japan.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 16 – Francesco Morosini , the Doge of Venice since 1688 , dies after he was found dead in his room, surrounded by his papers. Greeks are among the most populous countries in Europe, with a population of more than 300 million. They have the largest land area of any European country, and the second-largest in the world, after Russia. In 2016, Greece's population is estimated to have grown by 6.2% compared with 2013, owing largely to migration, especially from the Middle East and North Africa.

Year 1321 (MCCCXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December c. May–June – Leper scare: Rumours that lepers (acting on the orders of Jews bribed by Moors) are attempting to poison the Christian population spread throughout southern France. August 14 – King Edward II of England reluctantly agrees to demands from his barons to send Hugh le Despenser, 1st Earl of Winchester, and his son Hugh Despenser the Younger into exile. October 29 – King Stephen Uroš II Milutin of Serbia dies.

Year 1212 ( MCCXII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending when the new Gregorian calendar (the Julian calendar) became officially accepted in 1652. Leap years are used to represent the number of days since the start of one year in an astronomical year. James I (; 10 December 1315 – 11 April 1383) was King of England from 1324 until his death in 1348. His reign saw the first English conquest of continental Europe, leading to the Treaty of Westphalia, which resulted in the creation of the newly formed Kingdom of France.

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

Year 1559 ( MDLIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar. The English language has been derived from Celtic languages. The earliest written traces of English dates to the 5th century AD, and it is said to date to the 10th century BC, although some authors suggest that the language had existed as early as 6000 BC, and perhaps as early as 5000 BC. It is the official language of England (and Wales) today, but there are numerous dialects, including East Anglian, Old English, and various dialects of Scots Gaelic.

Year 1198 ( MCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Medieval Europe, but the first day of the month was normally observed as Sunday. It is still commonly referred to as "Sunday". The date was usually observed from Friday to Saturday, except in England and Wales. Alphabetic Greek ( Αφλήνος ;  αλιπτώνος; ) was the written language of most Hellenes living in the northern part of the Iberian peninsula until Roman times when it began to split off from Latin-based classical Greek.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the establishment of the city of Canterbury to the death of Harold Godwinson  in 1185. The Wright brothers' first aircraft was a two-seater biplane powered by three piston engines. In February 1917, after an eight-year and $1.6 million design and development phase, the first fully functional prototype was completed in November 1918. However, with the onset of the First World War, the plane's limited performance made it too expensive for war time use. Wessex County  is a county in the Greater London region of England.

Moore 's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit ( IC ) doubles with the square of the area. This phenomenon was also known as Moore's law, because Intel engineer Gordon Moore first described it during his keynote speech at the Computer and Communications Industry Symposium (CCCIS) in 1972. A computer is a set of digital electronic circuits designed to perform tasks. A computer typically contains a central processing unit (CPU) and associated memory (ROM), together with a large storage device, usually called a disk drive, for storing and accessing data.

Year 1193 ( MCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) to August 11, 1229 AD. It was also used as the first day of the week.In early Christian calendars that do not distinguish between solstices and equinoxes, the date in August is regarded as December 21 or December 22. The Gregorian Calendar uses the Julian Day numbering system which marks the month by the number of days since the last day of the preceding year. James II (January 6, 1625–May 9, 1691) was the eldest son of the King James I and Queen Matilda.

Charles XIV John (; born Jean Bernadotte; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844) was King of Sweden and Norway from 1818 until his death. In modern Norwegian lists of kings he is called Charles III John . He was the first monarch of the Bernadotte dynasty.Born in Pau in southern France, Bernadotte joined the French Royal Army in 1780. Following the outbreak of the French Revolution, he exhibited great military talent, rapidly rising through the ranks, and was made a brigadier general by 1794. He served with distinction in Italy and Germany, and was briefly Minister of War.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates. In its simplest form, a battering ram is just a large, heavy log carried by several people and propelled with force against an obstacle; the ram would be sufficient to damage the target if the log were massive enough and/or it were moved quickly enough (that is, if it had enough momentum). Later rams encased the log in an arrow-proof, fire-resistant canopy mounted on wheels. Inside the canopy, the log was swung from suspensory chains or ropes.

Year 1032 (MXXXII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Romanos III (Argyros) sends a Byzantine expeditionary army under General Michael Protospatharios, which includes Western auxiliaries and elite troops of Asia Minor, to reinforce the Byzantine position in Calabria (Southern Italy). Europe  September 6 – King Rudolph III dies without any heirs. He bequeaths his entire dominions to Emperor Conrad II (the Elder), dispatching to him the Holy Lance and ring of St. Maurice, symbols of Burgundian investiture.

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 ( MCDXXIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the day/month) and ending on Sunday ( link will display the day of the week).The first English calendar introduced in 1325 was based on the Gregorian calendar, which continued in use until 1782. The Gregorian calendar was based on observation of the Moon's annual orbit around Earth. Gibraltar is an island territory located in the western Atlantic Ocean, 1,5 miles (2 kilometers) north of mainland Spain. Gibraltar has a population of around 2,500, mostly of Spanish and Portuguese ancestry.

Year 1443 (MCDXLIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  July 22 – Battle of St. Jakob an der Sihl (Old Zürich War): The forces of the city of Zürich are defeated, but the Swiss Confederacy have insufficient strength to besiege and take the city. November 8 – Battle of Niš: John Hunyadi and the army of the Crusade of Varna defeat three armies of the Ottoman Empire, and capture the city of Niš in modern-day Serbia; Skanderbeg deserts the Ottoman camp and goes to Albania.

Year 1420 ( MCDXX ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday at 5:52 am, January 1, 2018. It has been marked for nearly three millennia as an auspicious event in Roman culture. It is celebrated as one of the most important days of the year, since it represents the beginning of winter and the beginnings of autumn. In computer science, an operating system (OS) is a basic software component that provides common functionality and user interfaces across a variety of computers.

Year 1031 (MXXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 20 – King Robert II (the Pious) dies at Melun, after a 35-year reign. He is succeeded by his 23-year-old son, Henry I, who becomes the sole ruler of France. Henry's mother, Queen dowager Constance of Arles, prefers her third son, Robert, as heir to the throne and, with the help of Count Odo II, begins a war against Henry.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

Year 1361 (MCCCLXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 17 – An-Nasir Hasan, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, is killed by one of his own mamluks, Yalbugha al-Umari, who, with the senior Mamluk emirs, has al-Mansur Muhammad installed as the new sultan. April 13 – The University of Pavia is founded, on the Italian Peninsula. July 27 – Battle of Visby: King Valdemar IV of Denmark conquers the city of Visby by defeating his peasant army. This allows Lübeck to become the new leading city of the Hanseatic League.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 November 1380), was a German general in the Spanish War of Succession. He fought alongside the Duke of Orleans under the leadership of Philip II, the King of Spain. Louis was the nephew of the Emperor Charles V and the younger brother of the Holy Roman emperor Joseph II. Ludwig Wittgenstein  (; 27 January 1889 – 24 May 1993) was a German-Jewish philosopher and linguist who is regarded as one of the leading philosophers of the twentieth century.

Year 1231 ( MCCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian Calendar, which started with the Julian Calendar and ended on Monday 7 February 2117 BC. The name "MCC XXXI" comes from the Latin root of the word 'mid', meaning 'between', and is also used to denote the second month after the New Moon, the first week in January. A middeck  or midden is a pit dug under a roof for storing food and other personal possessions.

In metaphysics , extension signifies both 'stretching out ' ( Latin : extensio ) as well as later 'taking up' (also: filling in) (see ). Fritz Ederle (; 17 July 1871  – 28 October 1963) was a German physicist. He is known for his interest in the structure of elementary particles and how atoms behave under certain conditions.Ederle is best known for his research on the interaction between protons and neutrons.Early life Fritz Ederle, born in Hamburg, studied chemistry with Johann Ludwig Feynmann, who would later become Einstein's professor at the university where he earned his doctorate.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River , in the town of Manapouri on the north shore of the main island of Hawaii Island. Pearl Harbour is a popular tourist destination with about 1.6 million visitors during the month of December every year. It is situated about 10 kilometers south of Oahu, and about 25 kilometers east of Hilo (the two islands).The town is situated on a promontory close to the Waiau Valley. The water level is slightly higher than normal, and there are sandbanks rising from the river bottom.

Year 1043 ( MXLIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It began in 887 AD and continued until the early 17th century. The current date, November 21, 2019, is set by the Leap Day Abbreviation ( LDA ) mechanism used in most Western calendars. Aldo Moro was a Roman general who fought for Emperor Honorius. He was born in Cagliari, Italy, and became an important ally of Rome against the Vandals. His actions during this time have been well documented.He is known for his many battles with the Etruscan people.

The picometre ( international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures ; SI symbol : pm), also sometimes called "millimetre", is a unit of length, usually in terms of millimetres, but also measured in metres. It was defined by the International Organisation of Standardization ( ISO ) in 1972 to be equal to one meter (or 1 foot) when expressed in metric measurement units.It has been the preferred unit of length internationally since at least 1945, when it was made part of the IOM standard definition.

Dyson's eternal intelligence concept (the Dyson Scenario), proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979, proposes a means by which an immortal society of intelligent beings in an open universe may escape the prospect of the heat death of the universe by extending subjective time to infinity even though expending only a finite amount of energy.Bremermann's limit can be invoked to deduce that the amount of time to perform a computation on 1 bit is inversely proportional to the change in energy in the system. As a result, the amount of computations that can be performed grows over time.

Events  June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary, Queen of Scots, recognizes Philip II of Spain as her heir. July 6 – The Treaty of Berwick is signed between Queen Elizabeth I of England and King James VI of Scotland. July 21 – English explorer Thomas Cavendish begins the first deliberately planned circumnavigation of the globe. September 20–21 – Execution of the Babington Plotters: The 14 men convicted of a plot (uncovered on July 17) to murder Queen Elizabeth and replace her with Mary, Queen of Scots, are hanged, drawn and quartered (the first seven being disembowelled before death) in St Giles Field, London.

Year 1532 (MDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 22 – São Vicente is established as the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. March 18 – The English Parliament bans payment by the English Church to Rome. April – Battle of Quipaipan in Peru: Atahualpa wins the civil war in the Inca Empire, defeating his brother Huáscar. May 13 – Francisco Pizarro lands on the northern coast of Peru. May 16 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist who served as Chief of the Los Alamos nuclear weapons project, President of the American Physical Society, and director of the Los Alamos Laboratory from 1945 to 1951. As a Princeton graduate student in 1919, he worked on the development of the electron-microscopic spectrometer that would be used to study the structure of atoms and nuclei. James M. McPherson  (; August 28, 1920 – January 7, 2002) was an American economist and public servant.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891. It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, high frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla experimented with a number of different configurations consisting of two, or sometimes three, coupled resonant electric circuits.Tesla used these circuits to conduct innovative experiments in electrical lighting, phosphorescence, X-ray generation, high frequency alternating current phenomena, electrotherapy, and the transmission of electrical energy without wires. Tesla coil circuits were used commercially in sparkgap radio transmitters for wireless telegraphy until the 1920s, and in medical equipment such as electrotherapy and violet ray devices.

Proline ( symbol Pro or P ) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid ( used in peptides and small molecules ). The chemical formula is CH 3 -NH 2 O, where H is hydrogen and O is oxygen. It is a protonated aliphatic hydrocarbon derived from the condensation of the hydroxyl group on phenylalanine with o-hydroxyalkyl phosphate. The British Museum is the largest museum in the UK, and also the oldest museum in the world. Located at the corner of Regent's Canal and Piccadilly, it was constructed by William IV, King of England in the 1550s.

Year 1342 ( MCCCXLII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in France and ending Thursday, January 12. In the Julian calendar, 1343 would have been a calender year.It is the third year in a succession of years that began on the same day as each other, i.e. December 21, 1453. It is also the last of seven years that began at the same hour: December 6, 1607, December 7, 1609, December 10, 1615, and December 11, 1617.

Year 1442 (MCDXLII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 18–25 – Battle of Hermannstadt: John Hunyadi defeats an army of the Ottoman Empire 80,000 strong, led by Mesid Bey of Vidin, near Sibiu in Transylvania. June 2 – Alfonso of Aragon proclaims himself King of Naples. September – John Hunyadi defeats another army of the Ottoman Empire (70,000 strong), led by Hadım Şehabeddin, Beylerbey (or governor) of Rumelia, near the Ialomița River. Following this, he places Basarab II as ruler of Wallachia.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of two. A trisomy has one copy of chromosome 21 and one copy of chromosome 18. It can be caused by a mutation in either chromosome 21 (trisomy 21) or chromosome 18 (trisomy 18). However, trisomy 20 is rare and may only occur in the context of an autosomal recessive disorder. Cystic fibrosis (CF) is an inherited genetic disorder characterized by progressive lung diseases. The disease is classified into four main groups: bronchopulmonary syndrome, non-pulmonary pulmonary syndrome, cystic fibrosis, and chronic fatigue syndrome.

Year 1452 ( MCDLII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar, and ending on Sunday of the Gregorian calendar. The Julian date system has been in use since the 4th century BC; there is no precise consensus on its exact date, though most consider it to have been established around 1 January AD 564. Hilbert I (8 November 1805 – 15 December 1884) was the King of Prussia, the country's first emperor, and the founder of modern Prussia.

EventsJanuary–March  January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar, son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb, initiates a civil war in India. With the support of troops from the Rajput states, Akbar declares himself the new Mughal Emperor and prepares to fight his father, but is ultimately defeated. January 3 – The Treaty of Bakhchisarai is signed, between the Ottoman vassal Crimean Khanate and the Russian Empire. January 18 – The "Exclusion Bill Parliament", summoned by King Charles II of England in October, is dissolved after three months, with directions that new elections be held at that a new parliament be convened in March in Oxford.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday , one day ahead of the Julian and Gregorian calendar.The name "Lundstände" is a portmanteau of "la lund" (lunch) and "strond". The Lundmarkt, commonly abbreviated Lund, is a small municipality in central Sweden, located in the province of Västerås south of Stockholm, north of the Mälaren river, east of the city of Karlskrona, southeast of Gothenburg, and west of Örebro. It is the seat of the municipality of Borg-Uppsala and its surroundings. The population was 1,084,611 as of 31 December 2013.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman . Set in the late 1960s, the series revolves around Honolulu District Attorney Jim Hopper (John Cho) and his pursuit of high-profile crime.The series follows the trials and tribulations that ensue when Hopper is tasked with the prosecution of a particularly difficult murder case. The series' theme of corruption permeates both its narrative and its production. Heinrich Hertz (December 11, 1930 – June 21, 1988) was an Austrian economist who served as the prime minister of Austria from January 1944 until May 1949.

Year 1023 ( MXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the year 1000 in the Julian calendar.In the first quarter of the year 1000, John the Forerunner, king of Northumbria, abdicated his throne due to his wife Elisabeth's illness. This triggered an upheaval in the Kingdom of England known as the "Rise and Fall of the English Tudors".The following year, King Henry II granted Edward VI the title of "King of Ireland", thus establishing a dynasty which would later become known as the Tudors.

Moore's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit (IC) doubles about every two years. Moore's law is an observation and projection of a historical trend. Rather than a law of physics, it is an empirical relationship linked to gains from experience in production.The observation is named after Gordon Moore, the co-founder of Fairchild Semiconductor and Intel (and former CEO of the latter), who in 1965 posited a doubling every year in the number of components per integrated circuit, and projected this rate of growth would continue for at least another decade.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis. The term ski jumping has come into use to distinguish it from snowboarding, which refers to skiing with skis or other snow-shoes, and is also sometimes referred to as sled riding. There are many forms of skiing, and each sport has its own set of guidelines, regulations, and rules. Sociology ( ) is a discipline of study devoted to understanding human behavior through social, moral, political, cultural, economic, and historical aspects.

Year 1413 ( MCDXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) or on the first Monday after the 28th of January. It was officially abbreviated to MCD and is often shortened to just MCD, but is also called Mid Year 1. A mermaid, also known as a sea slither, is one of the four types of water creatures commonly associated with Mermaid Week. Other names for the species are  or  . In folklore, mermaids are sometimes depicted as beautiful maiden-type figures, usually female, who ride on the backs of fish or other aquatic life.

Arthrobacter (from the Greek, "jointed small stick”) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in soil. All species in this genus are Gram-positive obligate aerobes that are rods during exponential growth and cocci in their stationary phase. Arthrobacter have a distinctive method of cell division called "snapping division" or reversion in which the outer bacterial cell wall ruptures at a joint.DescriptionArthrobacter can be grown on mineral salts pyridone broth, where colonies have a greenish metallic center on incubated at . Under the microscope, Arthrobacter appear as rods when rapidly dividing, and cocci when in stationary phase.

Year 1335 ( MCCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic calendar, and followed by an abbreviated Gregorian calendar. It was commonly used in both the Eastern Orthodox Church and in the Latin world. Abbreviation: AD or AD+
The American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII code) is a set of Unicode character codes that are used to encode text and other data types in the International Telecommunications Union (ITU) International Telecommunication Standard (ITS) International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) International Telecommunication Union (ITU/IETF) Generalized Markup Language (GML) language.

Margaret ( , ; March or April 1283 – September 1290 ) , known as the Maid of Norway , was a Protestant saint of Norway. She is regarded as the patroness of musicians, artists, writers, writers' assistants, and writers. In the early days of her missionary work, she established an orphanage in Leiden, serving many poor people during the winter season. As a nun, she taught music to children in various parts of Europe. An archipelago consisting of at least five main land masses, each with its own coastline.

In software quality assurance , performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs under various types of failure. Such tests are considered the primary source of information about a program's reliability. They can be conducted by independent testers, or by groups of test engineers who use a tool called an instrumentation suite (ISS). Chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS), also referred to as myalgic encephalomyelitis or ME, is a medical condition that affects approximately 4 million Americans. CFS causes widespread fatigue and muscle pain, often lasting for weeks or months at a time.

Events January–June January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim : The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg . January 6 – Dutch East India Company War – Battle of Valkenburg : France and Britain sign a peace treaty on the Isle of Wight during the Dutch East India Company war, ending the first Dutch colonial war. February 2 – Spanish-American War – Battle of San Jacinto : In July 1898, the Spanish-American War took place over two months in the southern United States.The United States had declared war against Spain because of its seizure of Guam, a U.S. territory ceded to the United States as part of the Philippine-American War.

Edmund of Abingdon (also known as  Edmund Rich, St Edmund of Canterbury, Edmund of Pontigny, French: St Edme; c. 11741240) was an English-born prelate who served as Archbishop of Canterbury. He became a respected lecturer in mathematics, dialectics and theology at the Universities of Paris and Oxford, promoting the study of Aristotle. Having already an unsought reputation as an ascetic, he was ordained a priest, took a doctorate in divinity and soon became known not only for his lectures on theology but as a popular preacher, spending long years travelling within England, and engaging in 1227 preaching the sixth crusade.

Year 1033 ( MXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday 15 April 1205 CE.The year began on Monday, 8 January 1204 CE in the reign of Emperor Henry V of England and lasted until 31 March 1210 CE. The feast day is now celebrated on 3 April 1212 CE.In the Middle Ages, the year began on Sunday 1 October 1207 CE, which marked the birth of King Edward I of England. Hugh Glass was an American writer and stage actor best known as the author of two novels: In the Fade and A Tale of Two Cities.

Events January – March January 7 – In India , Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had been living in Lahore after the Pakistani army sacked the city. The year began with a massacre of Shia Muslims by the Sikhs of Punjab and continued into February, culminating in a battle between the two countries at the town of Faisalabad that lasted until the end of the summer. On 16 January 1747, it became clear that the Indian Government was preparing an attack on the British garrison at Calcutta (later known as Calcutta Island) in preparation for the next phase of the War of Independence.

Broca 's area , or the Broca area ( , also , ) , is a region in the frontal lobes located between the superior colliculus and the inferior colliculus. It is responsible for most complex speech sounds, including the vocalizations that form the phonemes (phoneme units) used by human languages. The Broca's area consists of two parts: an area bounded by the superior colliculus, and a smaller area bounded by the inferior colliculus. The Böhm-Bawerk model of economic behavior (BDM) is an economic model that attempts to explain human behavior.

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as well as King of France and Countess of Orange . She was the younger sister of Edward VI and was the eldest daughter of Henry VIII and Margaret Beaufort, but she was separated from her two older sisters at the time of the Tudor dynasty's foundation.Born in the Scottish city of St Andrews, she was one of several illegitimate children of the English lord Richard II, who died without a male heir. Her father's wife, Elizée, also had an illegitimate son, Earl of Warwick.
