Year 1350 ( MCCCL ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday. This year was celebrated in the United Kingdom as St Andrew's Day. It was also an associated day for Easter in parts of Scotland, Ireland and the Isle of Man. The Cambridge University Library (CULC), founded by King John in 1436, is the principal repository of materials related to the history, geography, economy, culture and languages of England, Wales and Northern Ireland from around the time when the first written accounts were drawn up to the end of the 20th century.

Year 1292 ( MCCXCII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) or Wednesday, depending on which month is selected. It began with the Julian calendar's Gregorian calendar. Leap years usually have an extra leap day and do not occur on the 15th of the month. They are counted from December 31st of the previous leap year. The year 1000 has an extra leap day. In computer programming, a binary search tree is a graph of pointers where each node is either 0 or 1 and in addition it contains one or more edges connecting each node to the others.

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as the most general form of a force in General Relativity . (For details, see The Equivalence Principle .) "Cheek-bone"—also spelled cheekbone or gable bone—is a thin bone that runs from the middle of the front of the head, down to the neck. Cheekbones are often found at birth, but may sometimes develop after puberty. Cheekbones may become fused together during pregnancy. A full-sized skull usually has two pairs of cheekbones on each side of the occiput.

Prince Igor is an opera in four acts with a prologue , written and composed by Alexander Borodin . The opening act was first presented at the St. Petersburg International Opera House on January 27, 1867, as part of a Russian premiere series, and has been performed every autumn since. It is the most popular opera of the Russian operatic tradition, with over twenty-two million performances to date. Herman Melville (born August 14, 1895) is a Canadian novelist and short story author best known for his 1932 novel Moby Dick, which won the World Fantasy Award, its first ever.

Events January–June January 13 – Edward Sexby , who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell , dies in the Tower of London on March 9, 1536.1536–1538 On August 12, King Charles VI abdicated and was succeeded by his son, King Francis I . Edgar Allan Poe (; born February 21, 1809 – August 10, 1894) was an American short story writer and author. He wrote nearly a hundred stories during his lifetime, many of which have been attributed to Poe. His literary style was characterized by a distinct use of long, elliptical sentences that often veer between melodramatic and tragic.He was known primarily for his supernatural tales.

Year 1501 (MDI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Cesare Borgia returns triumphantly to Rome, from Romagna. March 25 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova probably discovers Ascension Island. It is definitely sighted and named on May 20, 1503 (Feast of the Ascension) by Afonso de Albuquerque. April – The Rebellion of the Alpujarras ends with the surrender of the last Muslim insurgents in the Alpujarra Mountains, who are given the choice of expulsion or conversion to Christianity.

Abolitionism , or the abolitionist movement , was the movement to end slavery . In Western Europe and the Americas it was associated with a variety of different political and ideological causes, including racialism, xenophobia, anti-Semitism, and religious fundamentalism. It developed in the United States during the late 18th and early 19th centuries and grew in popularity among abolitionists after the American Civil War.Historical eventsThe first recorded use of the term "abolitionism" dates back to 1824, when the Massachusetts abolitionist Horace Greeley said, "I am an abolitionist, but not an abolitionist of Negroes alone. There must be freedom for all!"

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow, twisting, banked, iced tracks in a gravity-powered sleigh. International bobsleigh competitions are governed by the International Bobsleigh and Skeleton Federation, also known as FIBT from the French . National competitions are often governed by bodies such as the United States Bobsled and Skeleton Federation, Bobsleigh Canada Skeleton, and the German Bobsleigh, Luge, and Skeleton Federation.The first bobsleds were built in the late 19th century in St. Moritz, Switzerland, by wealthy tourists from Victorian Britain who were staying at the Palace Hotel owned by Caspar Badrutt.

Year 990 ( CMXC ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar.The year 990 marks the birth of Christ; it is generally considered to mark the beginning of the Christian era. The year 990 is not a leap year. In mathematics, ρ is an integer less than 1. It is the reciprocal of its inverse, π. Its value is the square root of π.For example, pi is 1.41421957... and 2pi is 2π/1.41421957... This relationship is expressed as:  ρ = -(2πr)2.

Year 1318 (MCCCXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March – King Birger of Sweden is deposed, and forced to flee to Denmark (alternative date is April). April 1 – Berwick-upon-Tweed is retaken by the Scottish from the English. April – The inhabitants of Benevento, Italy rise against the Pope, and demand some political autonomy. The rebellion is crushed by William of Frejus, and the archbishop of Naples. May 11 – Battle of Dysert O'Dea: The Irish armies of Conor O'Dea defeat the Hiberno-Normans under Richard de Clare.

Year 1316 ( MCCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) at 23:59 hours UTC on August 12, 2009. On February 6, 2063, the year is known as 2018.HistoryIn its early history this year was used in many ways to mark the start and end of the Middle Ages. The German language, or Deutsche Bundesländisch-German (Danish/Swedish), is one of the Germanic languages spoken around the world. It is divided into three sub-races: Alsatian, Finno-Ugric, and Low German. Most dialects have varying degrees of phonetic variation.

Year 1231 (MCCXXXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Frederick II promulgates the Constitutions of Melfi (Liber Augustalis), a collection of laws for Sicily, as well as the edict of Salerno, regulating the exercise of medicine and separating the professions of physician and apothecary, and requiring medical schools to practice dissection. Castillan forces under King Ferdinand III (the Saint) re-conquer the city of Quesada. Battle of Jerez: Ferdinand III defeats Emir Ibn Hud of the Taifa of Murcia.

Digital electronics  is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use or produce them. This is in contrast to analog electronics and analog signals.Digital electronic circuits are usually made from large assemblies of logic gates, often packaged in integrated circuits. Complex devices may have simple electronic representations of Boolean logic functions.HistoryThe binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705) and he also established that by using the binary system, the principles of arithmetic and logic could be joined. Digital logic as we know it was the brain-child of George Boole in the mid 19th century.

Events January–June January 1 Colonel George Monck ( with his regiment ) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Haddington, which was a stronghold of the Lancastrians in the 16th and 17th centuries. February 2 The First Battle of Bosworth Field takes place, between the British Army and the Royal Scots Fusiliers led by Henry Hamilton. March 29 The Duke of Brunswick's expeditionary force meets the French at Agincourt, culminating in the Battle of Agincourt in July 1415. April 1 The Siege of Pisa begins. May 19 Pope Clement VI sends the legate to France to negotiate peace; the negotiation fails.

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are used as building blocks for proteins. They have two hydrogen bonds between an aliphatic sugar group at the 4-position of the double stranded DNA helix, and two hydrophobic bonds between carbon atoms of the A–T transition region. Vitamin A is a light-absorbing vitamin that is derived from the retinol moiety of the vitamin A molecule; it is present in animal foods but not in plants. Its absorption is dependent on the type and amount of its pigment, retinol.

Year 1484 (MCDLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – William Caxton, the first printer of books in English, prints his translation of Aesop's Fables in London. May 30 – Charles VIII of France (Charles l'Affable) is crowned. June 22 – The first known book printed by a woman, Anna Rügerin, is an edition of Eike of Repgow's compendium of customary law, the Sachsenspiegel, produced in Augsburg. July 6 – Portuguese sea captain Diogo Cão finds the mouth of the Congo River.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with Switzerland. It is situated in the southern half of the Franconian part of the state of Hesse, about 80km south-west of Gelsenkirchen. It has a population of about 1.7 million (2011 census), as against the approximately 3.1 million population of the entire state of Hesse itself. Cocaine is a widely used drug in cocaine-related industries. It is sold under the name cocaine hydrochloride by various street names like white gold, coke, snort, or blotter.

Year 1355 ( MCCCLV ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar and ending on Saturday or Sunday of the same year (as set down in the Gregorian calendar).The first four years of the year followed a sequence of 12 equal days of alternating 12-hour days. The last two weeks of the year were known as "sabbat" or "the sabbath." Alchemy is a subfield of alchemy that deals with the transmutation of volatile materials, such as ore, metals, and other organic substances, into more volatile substances, such as gold or silver.

Year 1379 (MCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  May 29 – John I succeeds his father, Henry II, as King of Castile and King of León. June 30 – New College, Oxford, is founded in England by William of Wykeham, Bishop of Winchester. July 1 – Forces of the Republic of Venice and Ottoman Turks, having invaded Constantinople, restore John V Palaiologos as Byzantine co-emperor. Andronikos IV Palaiologos is allowed to remain as co-emperor, but is confined to the city of Silivri for the remainder of his life.

Year 1132 (MCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Summer – Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk governor (atabeg) of Aleppo and Mosul, marches on Baghdad (the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) to add it to his dominions. He is defeated by the forces of Caliph Al-Mustarshid near Tikrit (modern Iraq). Zengi flees and escapes with help of Tikrit's governor Najm ad-Din Ayyub (the father of Saladin) who conveys him across the River Tigris.

Year 1494 ( MCDXCIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the reign of Henry Tudor. It was one of only four common years in the first half of the Tudor and Stuart dynasty, the others being 1285 (William the Conqueror), 1516 (Edward the First), and 1604 (Henry VIII). An amoeba , also known as a cyanobacteria , is a single-celled life form that lives by eating bacteria. They are among the smallest known organisms, comprising about 10–100 times fewer cells than a human cell.

In computer programming, a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of some section of code or after an operation in a formal specification. Postconditions are sometimes tested using assertions within the code itself. Often, postconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.For example: The result of a factorial is always an integer and greater than or equal to 1. So a program that calculates the factorial of an input number would have postconditions that the result after the calculation be an integer and that it be greater than or equal to 1.

Events  January–March  January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against France. January 27 – The first fire engine company (in what will become the United States) goes into service. February 18 – The first part of English nonconformist preacher John Bunyan's Christian allegory, The Pilgrim's Progress, is published in London. March 6 – King Charles II of England opens his third Parliament. March 21 – Thomas Shadwell's comedy, A True Widow, is given its first performance, debuting at The Duke's Theatre and staged by the Duke's Company.

Frederick Barbarossa ( 1122 – 10 June 1190 ) , also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire.He was the grandson and half-brother of King Charles III of England. Frank Lloyd Wright  (May 18, 1925–January 4, 2011) was an American architectural and landscape architect.Born in Los Angeles, California, Wright took up architecture as a young man after moving to the United States with his family when he was only eight years old. He earned his bachelor's degree in 1955 from the University of California, San Diego, and his Ph.D. in 1964 from the Rhode Island School of Design.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists of a straight line marked with a number, usually denoting a North, South or East pole. There are hundreds of different designs, most of which appear to have some resemblance to each other. Compass bearings vary in distance from their source. Co-operative game , sometimes also called a "game," is a type of computer-operated cooperative board game, typically played by groups of players who work cooperatively to achieve a particular victory condition.

Solidarity Electoral Action ( , AWS ) was a political coalition in Poland . Since 1997 , its official name has been the Social Democratic Party of Poland (PSL).The Polish PSL is led by Zbigniew Jankowski and was co-founded by Stanislaw Komorowski, who was the first head of state in the country's postwar democracy. In October 1996, following the collapse of communism, the PSL formed a coalition with the National Radical Party (NP), which had been banned from public office. George Bernard Shaw (; August 9, 1870 – February 7, 1954) was a British philosopher and playwright.

Year 1024 ( MXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of each year in the Gregorian calendrical system, as well as many other calendars, but not used by most people today.The dates are generally considered to be historically accurate, since the Julian calendar, adopted in the early 5th century BC, was based on astronomical observations that did not take into consideration the fact that the Sun was moving behind the Earth. However, they can be inaccurate for some reasons. Anaemia is an acute, immune-mediated inflammation caused by increased production of certain white blood cells called erythrocytes.

Events  January–June  January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England, Sweden and the United Provinces. February 13 – In Lisbon, a peace treaty is established between Afonso VI of Portugal and Carlos II of Spain, by mediation of Charles II of England, in which the legitimacy of the Portuguese monarch is recognized. Portugal yields Ceuta to Spain. May 2 – The first Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle ends the War of Devolution. July–December  July 7 – Bishop Isaac Barrow founds the Bishop Barrow Trust with the intention of establishing a university on the Isle of Man; this becomes King William's College.

Year 1203 (MCCIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It was also the first year to have all digits different from each other since 1098.Events  By place  Fourth Crusade  April 20 – The Crusader army evacuates Zadar, and sets sail to Corfu; Boniface of Montferrat and Doge Enrico Dandolo stay behind to await Prince Alexios Angelos. After a brief pause at Durrës (modern Albania), the fleet reaches Corfu. Meanwhile, news of its approach (through spies) have reached Emperor Alexios III (Angelos) at Constantinople.

Year 1533 (MDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – King Henry VIII of England formally but secretly marries Anne Boleyn, who becomes his second queen consort. January 26 – Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden, is appointed Lord Chancellor of England. March 30 – Thomas Cranmer becomes Archbishop of Canterbury. April – The Statute in Restraint of Appeals in England declares the king to be the supreme sovereign and forbids judicial appeals to the papacy.

The Æsir ( Old Norse : ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion . They include Asgard, the god of the sky, fauna, and people; Odin, son of Fingolfin; Thor, leader of the warriors; Frigg, goddess of sex; and Heimdall, protector of the realm. The Art of Motorcycle Maintenance (also known as the  "Lines of Automobile Maintenance" or "Motorcycle Maintenance Manual") is a book published in 1954 by the Harley Davidson Company and illustrated by George Mazzini and published by Vollrath Books.

McLean Hospital  (formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont, Massachusetts. It is noted for its clinical staff expertise and neuroscience research and is also known for the large number of famous people who have been treated there. McLean maintains the world's largest neuroscientific and psychiatric research program in a private hospital. It is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School, an affiliate of Massachusetts General Hospital, and part of Mass General Brigham, which also includes Brigham and Women's Hospital.History McLean was founded in 1811 in a section of Charlestown, Massachusetts that is now a part of Somerville, Massachusetts.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed lizard or African katydid) is native to southeastern Africa. The genus Xenopus is considered to be an isolated taxon, and it includes only three species: Xenopus albiventris , Xenopus acanthoi , and Xenopus lutea . It ranges throughout the southern and eastern part of the continent. In the south, it is found in dry rocky habitats including rainforests. In the east, it is found in wetlands and moist tropical forests. Elon Musk is an American businessman, inventor, and founder of electric vehicle company Tesla Motors.

Year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – September 3 – Siege of Lisbon by the Castilian army, during the 1383–85 Crisis in Portugal. August 16 – The Hongwu Emperor of Ming China hears a case of a couple who tore paper money notes, while fighting over them. Under the law, this is considered to be destroying stamped government documents, which is to be punished by a caning with a bamboo rod of 100 strokes. However, the Emperor decides to pardon them, on the grounds that it was unintentional.

Year 1404 ( MCDIV ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar and ending on Sunday ( link will display the abbreviated calendar ) in all subsequent years.It is now considered as the second-most important leap year of the Christian calendar, after the leap year introduced in 1582. The number of days in this year is slightly longer than it was in 1493, since the first day of the new year is added to the current year rather than being added to the previous year.

Year 1412 ( MCDXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on New Year's Day, 22 February. The Gregorian calendar was adopted in this period as the basis for all modern calendars.Before the first leap second was introduced to ensure that the Julian day number would not change, each of the leap years used different methods to define the start of its month. A leap day occurs when it falls on an exact second after January 1.The earliest known leap day occurs on January 15, 1352 AD, although it does not exist in the Julian calendar.

William Makepeace Thackeray (; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863) was a British novelist, author and illustrator. He is known for his satirical works, particularly his 1848 novel Vanity Fair, a panoramic portrait of British society, and the 1844 novel The Luck of Barry Lyndon, which was adapted for a 1975 film by Stanley Kubrick.BiographyThackeray, an only child, was born in Calcutta, British India, where his father, Richmond Thackeray (1 September 1781 – 13 September 1815), was secretary to the Board of Revenue in the East India Company.

The sousaphone  is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba. Created around 1893 by J.W. Pepper at the direction of American bandleader John Philip Sousa (after whom the instrument was then named), it was designed to be easier to play than the concert tuba while standing or marching, as well as to carry the sound of the instrument above the heads of the band. Like the tuba, sound is produced by moving air past the lips, causing them to vibrate or "buzz" into a large cupped mouthpiece.

Year 1439 ( MCDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the Roman Empire. It was the last month of the year, excepting January. It was used as the first Monday after the New Year's Day when the moon passes between the Earth and the sun; it was also the first day of the month when there were no solstices or equinoxes. The time was originally considered to be 5 hours late, though by the 12th Century this had changed to 4 hours and 48 minutes.

Lazzi (; from the Italian lazzo, a joke or witticism) are stock comedic routines that are associated with Commedia dell'arte. Performers, especially those playing the masked Arlecchino, had many examples of this in their repertoire, and would use improvisatory skills to weave them into the plot of dozens of different commedia scenarios. These largely physical sequences could be improvised or preplanned within the performance and were often used to enliven the audience when a scene was dragging, to cover a dropped line or cue, or to delight an expectant audience with the troupe's specialized lazzi.Lazzi could be completed by a single player (e.g.

Year 1559 (MDLIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 15 – Elizabeth I of England is crowned, in Westminster Abbey. February 27 – Queen Elizabeth I of England establishes the Church of England, with the Act of Uniformity 1558 and the Act of Supremacy 1558. The Oath of Supremacy is reinstated. March 23 – Emperor Gelawdewos of Ethiopia, defending his lands against the invasion of Nur ibn Mujahid, Sultan of Harar, is killed in battle. His brother, Menas, succeeds him as king.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed to be launched in the late 1960s to explore Mars. The first, Mariner 2, failed after reaching a distance of 17.8 million km from its intended landing site, but the second managed to land safely on Mars. The mission was an international collaboration led by the United States and Britain that included Canada, Germany, Japan and South Africa. Médecins Sans Frontières or MFS is an international health group that has served people in conflict zones for more than 50 years.

Dari ( , , ) , or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of Persian, including Dari. The primary language of the Persian Empire from the 7th century to the 15th century, the language of the ruling class and educated elite, the aristocracy, and the clergy, as well as the culture of the nation, has been widely spoken in modern-day Iran, Azerbaijan, northern Iraq, Central Asia, Pakistan, and India. In computer science, key is an abstract data type whose semantics is defined by its encoding in a set of alphanumeric bits.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 26 – War of Spanish Succession: The uprising by Bavarians against the occupation of the  Electorate of Bavaria by Austrian troops ends after 75 days, and ends the plans of Maximilian, the Elector of Bavaria, to bring Bavaria under the rule of the House of Wittelsbach. January 26 – Great Northern War: The Battle of Grodno begins when a coalition of 34,000 Swedish and Polish troops besieges the then-Lithuanian city in the winter time and clashes with 41,000 Russian and Saxon troops.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly known as Gram-positive staphylococci. It is one of the most numerous gram-negative bacterial species on earth and is responsible for about 25% of human illness. The genus was originally named Aetiologicala by Paul Laffoley in 1797; however, it was later changed to Ascaris after Laffoley's death. The Australian Institute of Marine Science has been conducting research in the marine environment for more than 120 years. Its principal research focuses on ocean chemistry and ecology, marine biology, energy, fisheries and climate change.

Year 1456 ( MCDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and continued for one year. This year of 365 days is traditionally associated with Jesus' birth. It is the first leap year with no leap years.According to Christian theology, every year begins with the time that the earth began its 24-hour day. The British military in the second half of the eighteenth century was led by King George III during which time Britain was the most powerful nation in Europe. In 1759, it was the only European kingdom to have successfully defeated the French at the Battle of Waterloo.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger . For comparison , a handgun can fire two rounds per pull of the trigger. Semi-automatic weapons are more accurate than fully automatic rifles but slower to fire. (   , ) is a computer program written in C/C++. Originally designed as a replacement for the IBM PC's COBOL, it is still used in modern operating systems and other software. The source code consists of 2,000 individual source lines. The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain by occupying Roman forces. It began in AD 43 under Emperor Claudius, and was largely completed by 87 when the Stanegate was established.The Roman army was generally recruited in Italia, Hispania, and Gaul. To control the English Channel they used the newly formed fleet.The Romans under their general Aulus Plautius first forced their way inland in several battles against British tribes, including the Battle of the Medway, the Battle of the Thames, and in later years Caratacus's last battle against Caratacus and the Roman conquest of Anglesey.

The European bison (Bison bonasus) or the European wood bison, also known as the wisent ( or ), or the zubr , or colloquially the European buffalo, is a European species of bison. It is one of two extant species of bison, alongside the American bison. The European bison is the heaviest wild land animal in Europe and individuals in the past may have been even larger than their modern-day descendants. During late antiquity and the Middle Ages, bison became extinct in much of Europe and Asia, surviving into the 20th century only in northern-central Europe and the northern Caucasus Mountains.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men's singles, ladies' singles, and pair skating but not ice dancing. Jumping in figure skating is "relatively recent". They were originally individual compulsory figures, and sometimes special figures; many jumps were named after the skaters who invented them or from the figures from which they were developed. It was not until the early part of the 20th century, well after the establishment of organized skating competitions, when jumps with the potential of being completed with multiple revolutions were invented and when jumps were formally categorized.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married, especially in Western cultures. A ring is presented as an engagement gift by a partner to their prospective spouse when they propose marriage or directly after a marriage proposal is accepted. It represents a formal agreement to future marriage. In Western countries, engagement rings are worn mostly by women, and rings can feature diamonds or other gemstones. The neologism "mangagement ring" is sometimes used for an engagement ring worn by men. In some cultures, men and women wear matching rings, and engagement rings may also be used as wedding rings.

The human leg, in the general word sense, is the entire lower limb of the human body, including the foot, thigh and even the hip or gluteal region. However, the definition in human anatomy refers only to the section of the lower limb extending from the knee to the ankle, also known as the crus or, especially in non-technical use, the shank. Legs are used for standing, and all forms of locomotion including recreational such as dancing, and constitute a significant portion of a person's mass.

Year 1150 (MCL) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Battle of Tara: The Byzantines defeat the Serbian-Hungarian army under Grdeša, count (župan) of Travunija, near the snow-covered Tara River. The Serbs are overpowered, and Grand Prince Uroš II is forced to accept the peace agreement made by Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos). Uroš is succeeded by his brother Desa, who  becomes co-ruler of the Principality of Serbia (until 1153).

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.
